(1) Northward to its intersection with the shoreline of mainland Massachusetts;
and on the west by the eastern boundary of the Mid-

Atlantic regulated mesh area.<p>

<a name="mam"><a href="#mam1">The Mid- Atlantic Regulated Mesh
Area</b><p></a></a>

The Mid- Atlantic Regulated Mesh Area is that area bounded on the east
by a line running from the Rhode Island shoreline at 41 18.2' N. and 71
51.5' W. (Watch Hill, RI) southwesterly through Fishers Island, NY, to
Race Point, Fishers Island, NY, and from Race Point, Fishers Island,
NY, southeasterly to the intersection of the 3 nautical mile line east
of Montauk Point, southwesterly along the 3 nautical mile line to the
intersection of 72 30' W. Longitude and south along that line to the
intersection of the outer boundary of the EEZ.<p>

<a name="das"><b>The Large Mesh DAS Program</b></a> is for fishing vessels under a groundfish DAS with a
Large Mesh Individual or Large Mesh Fleet DAS category permit.  The minimum
mesh size for sink gillnets gear is 7 inches throughout the entire net and the
minimum mesh size for trawl gear is 8 inches throughout the entire net,
regardless of area fished.<p>

<img width=700 height=40 alt="Transit & Stowage Provisions" src="d1c.gif"><p>
<i>The following information pertains to all fishing vessels unless a
vessel is fishing with a  particular gear type that has been deemed
exempt.  </i><p>

<b>TRANSITING </b><p> <b> Closed
Areas:  Nantucket Lightship Closed Area, Closed Area I, Northeast
Closure Area,  Mid- coast Closure Area, and the Massachusetts Bay Closure Area</b><p>

Vessels may transit these areas during the closure periods, provided that the
gear is stowed in accordance with the <a href="#stow">regulations</a>.<p>

<b>Closed Area II</b><p>
Vessels may transit Closed Area II for safety reasons, provided the
operator has determined that there is a compelling safety reason and
that fishing gear is stowed in accordance with the <a
href="#stow">regulations</a>. <p>

<b>Regulated Mesh Areas:  Gulf of Maine/Georges Bank  (GOM/GB)
Regulated Mesh Area</b><p> 

Vessels may transit through the GOM/GB regulated mesh area with nets on
board with mesh smaller than the minimum regulated mesh size with small
mesh exempted species on board, provided that:

<p> *       The small
mesh nets are stowed in accordance with the <a href="#stow">regulations</a>.<p> 

* Vessels have on board an authorizing letter issued by the Regional
Director.<p> 

*       That vessels do not fish for, possess on board, or
land any species of fish, except, when fishing in the Cultivator Shoal
whiting and Nantucket Shoals dogfish fishery exemptions areas and the
Southern New England and Mid- Atlantic regulated mesh areas, vessels
may retain the respective small mesh exempted species.<p>


<b>Stellwagen Bank/Jeffreys Ledge (SBJL) Juvenile Protection Area</b><p>


Vessels fishing under the GOM Small Mesh Exemption program and the
small mesh subareas, Small Mesh Area 1/Small Mesh Area 2 may transit
through the SB/JL juvenile protection area with nets on board that do
not conform with the SB/JL mesh requirements provided that the nets are
stowed in accordance with the <a href="#stow">regulations</a>.

<p> <b>Small Mesh Exemption Area</b>

<p> Vessels may transit through the Small Mesh
Exemption Area with nets on board with mesh smaller than the minimum
regulated mesh size provided that nets are stowed in accordance with
the <a href="#stow">regulations</a>, and provided the vessel has no fish on board.
<p> 

<a name="stow"><b>STOWAGE PROVISIONS</b><p> </a>

<b></b><p> <b>Net Stowage Requirements </b>

<p> Net vessels must stow nets so that they are not available for
immediate use according to one of the following specifications:

<p>
*       A net stowed below deck provided: it is located below the main
working deck from which the net is deployed and retrieved; the towing
wires, including the leg wires, are detached from the net; and it is
fan- folded (flaked) and bound around its circumference; or

<p> *
A net stowed and lashed down on deck, provided: it is fan- folded
(flaked) and bound around its circumference; it is securely fastened to
the deck or rail of the vessel; and the towing wires, including the leg
wires, are detached from the net.

<p> *       A net that is on a reel
and is covered and secured, provided: the entire surface of the net is
covered with canvas or other similar material that is securely bound;
the towing wires, including the leg wires, are detached from the net;
and the codend is removed from the net and stored below deck.

<p>
*       *Nets that are secured in a manner authorized in writing by the
Regional Director.

<p>
<b>Scallop Dredge Vessels </b>

<p>
Scallop dredge vessels  must detach the towing wire from the scallop
dredge, reel the wire up onto the winch, and secure and cover the dredge so
that it is rendered unusable for fishing.<p>
   

<b>Hook Gear Vessels</b><p>
Hook gear vessels using gear other than pelagic hook gear must secure
all anchors and buoys, and have all hook gear, including jigging machines,
covered.<p>

<b>Sink Gillnet Vessels</b><p>


Sink gillnet vessels must cover all nets with canvas or similar material and
lash or otherwise securely fasten the nets to the deck or rail, and must have
all buoys larger than six inches in diameter, high flyers and anchors
disconnected.

<p><a href="#top">Top of page</a>
</td></table></center>


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
