<td valign=top>
<img border=0 width=453 height=40 alt="Large Mesh Exempjpgns" src="f1a.gif"><p>
<img border=0 width=453 height=372 alt="Map" src="map3a.gif"><p>

<b>EXEMPTED FISHERIES</b><p>
<p>
An exempted fishery is one that the Regional Director has determined will
result in a minimal bycatch of regulated multispecies and will not jeopardize
fishing mortality objectives.  Specifically, the percentage of regulated
multispecies bycatch must be less than 5 percent by weight of total catch.  For
directions on how to add an exempted fishery, <a href="#exem">click here</a>.  The following
fisheries have been determined to be consistent with the exemption criteria:<p>

</td></tr> 
</table>
<!---End  main Table -->

<!--- Main Table sets total width-->
<table width=700 border=0>
<td>

<p>
<b>Southern New England Monkfish Fishery Exemption</b><p>

Allows a trawl vessel (otter or beam trawl) to fish in the following area
when not under a day-at-sea.<p>

<b>SNE Monkfish Exemption Area:</b>  The area bounded on the north by a line
extending eastward along 40 degrees 10 minutes N.latitude, and bounded
on the west by the eastern boundary of the Mid-Atlantic Regulated Mesh Area.
<p>

Vessels fishing in this exemption may not fish for, possess, or land any
species of fish other than monkfish and the previously exempted species and
amounts for the SNE Area.
<p>

<b>SNE exempted species:</b>  Butterfish, dogfish (trawl), herring,
mackerel, ocean pout, scup, shrimp, squid, summer flounder, silver hake, and
weakfish.
<p>

<b>SNE bycatch species:</b>  Conger eels, searobins, black sea bass, red
hake, tautog (blackfish), blowfish, cunner, John Dory, mullet, bluefish,
tilefish, longhorn sculpin, fourspot flounder, alewife, hickory shad,
blueback herring, sea ravens, Atlantic croaker, spot, swordfish, monkfish
and monkfish parts--10 percent, by weight, of other species onboard,
lobster--the lesser of 10 percent, by weight, of other species onboard or
200 lobsters, skate parts--up to 10 percent, by weight, of other species
onboard.
<p>

<b>Minimum mesh size:</b>  8 inches square or diamond mesh applied throughout the
codend for at least 45 continuous meshes forward of the terminus of the net. 
All nets with a mesh size smaller than the minimum mesh size must be
properly stowed and nets must also be stowed when transiting to and from the
SNE Monkfish fishery Exemption Area from north of 40 degrees 10 minutes N.
latitude and east of the Mid-Atlantic Regulated Mesh Area boundary.
<p> 

<b>SNE Monkfish Sink Gillnet Exempted Area</b><p>

Sink gillnet vessels may participate in this fishery, provided the vessel
complies with the following specifications:

<b>Area:</b> Defined by a line running south from the Massachusetts shoreline at 41
degrees 35 minutes N. latitude and 70 degrees 00 minutes W. Longitude and
bounded on the west by the Mid-Atlantic Regulated Mesh Area.
<p>

<b>Specifications:</b>  a) From July 1 through October 31, 1996, an exempted
fishery for monkfish may be conducted by vessels using sink gillnet gear
only.  b) Vessels fishing under this exemption are restricted to a minimum
mesh size of 12 inches (diamond).  c) No species other than monkfish may be
retained when fishing in this exempted fishery. 

<b>SNE Dogfish Sink Gillnet Exemption Area<p></b>

Area:  Defined by a line running south from the Massachusetts shoreline at
41 degrees 35 minutes N. Latitude and 70 degrees 00 minutes W. Longitude and
bounded on the west by the Mid-Atlantic Regulated Mesh Area.

Specifications:  a)	From July 1, 1996 through OCtober 31, 1996 an
exempted fishery for dogfish may be conducted by vessels using sink gillnet
gear only. NOTE: This is a change FOR GILLNET VESSELS ONLY to the small mesh
exemptions previously applicable to vessels fishing in Southern New England. 
b) Effective July 29, 1996, vessels fishing under this exemption are
restricted to a minimum mesh size of 6 inches (diamond).  c)  The previously
allowed bycatch species for vessels under the SNE small mesh examption
applies.  There is no change.  
<p>

<center>
<a name="exem"><img width=700 height=40 alt="How to request Fishery Exemptions" src="f1b.gif"></a>

An exempted fishery may be added, deleted or modified pursuant  to the
procedure described here:<p>
</center>

1.	Applicants must submit a written request to the Regional Director, NMFS, One
Blackburn Drive, Gloucester, MA 01930- 2298.

 The request should describe the area in which the fishery would operate, the
period in which it would operate, the gear it would use, the approximate number
of vessels likely to participate, and the species it would target, retain and
land.<p>

2.	Those proposing that a fishery should be exempt should describe the fishery
and present all information possible that helps determine that the fishery
meets the bycatch standard.  The Regional Director will investigate NMFS data
sources, but proposals for exemptions should be complete and clear to
facilitate the process.  State agencies and universities, for example, may have
additional data available and proposers may contact them for assistance.<p>

3.	When a request for an exempted fishery is submitted, the request and any
accompanying data are reviewed by the Regional Director to determined whether
such a fishery would meet the exemption qualifying criteria, which are
described in the first paragraph of this information sheet. The Regional
Director will also consult with the New England Fishery Management Council on
any exemptions requested.  This process may take several weeks to complete.

<p><a href="#top">Top of page</a>
</td></table>

</center>


</BODY>
</HTML>
