<title> NEFSC </title>
<BODY  bgcolor="#f8f8ff">
<blockquote>
<img align=right src="/labs/narra.gif">
<h2>
Narragansett Laboratory<br>
Northeast Fisheries Science Center<br>
National Marine Fisheries Service,NOAA<br>
</h2>
<h3>
28 Tarzwell Drive<br>
Narragansett, RI 02882-1199<br>
</h3>
<p>
Telephone:  (401)782-3200, FTS 401-782-3200<br>
FAX:  (401) 782-3201, FTS 401-782-3201  <br>
<p>
<b>Officer-In-Charge:  Dr. Kenneth Sherman, x210<br></b>
<a href="http://chips2.gso.uri.edu/narr_home_page.html">Home Page</a><p>
<a href="http://mola.gso.uri.edu/">Home Page</a><p>
<p>
The facility is located on approximately 3 acres adjacent to the URI Graduate
School of Oceanography and the EPA Laboratory.
The laboratory has several special features including an automatic image
analysis plankton sorting system and a remote sensing
satellite link with URI. URI has large ship docking capability nearby.
<p>
     Elements of both the Conservation and Utilization Division and
the Environmental Processes Division are located at the
Narragansett Laboratory.  IT is also the site of the NEFSC/NOAA
Coast Watch Node.
     Research emphasis is on oceanographic system studies of ocean
circulation, nutrients, temperature fluctuations, and fish
populations as related to fish life cycles.  Research is focused on
environmental processes and fisheries ecology with specific
investigations in marine climatology, early life history dynamics,
plankton ecology, apex predator ecology, and fisheries engineering. 
Primary activities are:
<p>
*    Quantitative research on the physical and biological
     mechanisms affecting recruitment processes of major pelagic
     and demersal species of the northeast;
<p>
*    Monitoring interannual and seasonal variability in the
     community structure, abundance, and distribution of plankton
     to characterize changes in food availability for early life
     stages of pelagic and demersal fish;
<p>
*    Biological studies of migratory apex predators, especially
     sharks;
<p>
*    Conservation gear experimentation; 
<p>
*    Analysis of long-time records of meteorological and
     oceanographic conditions to determine their influence on
     fisheries and on pollution impacts; and
<p>
*    Analysis of satellite remotely sensed data to determine the
     influence of oceanographic conditions on the distribution and
     abundance of living marine resources.
<p>
<p>
<p><a href="/noaa.html" TARGET=_top><img height=50 width=30 
src="/images/sfbairdicon.gif"><br>Home</a>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT12-B25-16</DOCNO>
