<title> NEFSC </title>
<BODY  bgcolor="#f8f8ff">
<blockquote>
<img align=right src="/labs/milford.gif">
<p>
<h2>
Milford Laboratory<br>
Northeast Fisheries Science Center<br>
National Marine Fisheries Service,NOAA<br>
</h2>
<h3>
212 Rogers Road<br>
Milford, CT 06460-6499<br>
</h3>
<p>
Telephone: (203) 783-4200, FTS 203-783-4200<br>
FAX: (203) 783-4217, FTS 203-783-4217<br>
<p>
<b>Officer-In-Charge: Dr. Anthony Calabrese, x240<br></b>
<p>
<a href="http://clam.mi.nmfs.gov/">Home Page</a><p>

The Milford Laboratory is the location of the Enhancement and
Aquaculture Branch of the Environmental Processes Division.  The facility has
an extensive seawater system providing thermally conditioned seawater to <b>13
"wet" labs</b> and numerous experimental tanks; the laboratories are designed
to enable spawning and rearing of marine animals through their life stages.  It
is the location of  an <b>Algal Culture Laboratory</b> for both the grow out of
unicellular algae and the maintenance of an extensive collection of microalgae,
a <b>pollutant-exposure laboratory</b>, including a computerized
sediment-dosing system,  a<b> tank farm </b>comprising sixty 40 x 4 x 2-foot
tanks for experimentation and grow out of marine animals, and a 96-square foot
<b>greenhouse</b> for daily production of 5,000 gallons of dense algal cultures
in seawater for rearing mollusks.  It is the home port for the 50-foot research
vessel<b> R/V Shang Wheeler</b>.<p>
	<p>
Research is focused on experimental biology with specific studies on the
aquaculture of marine organisms and on habitat studies, using the scientific
disciplines of culture, genetics, bacteriology, immunology, biochemistry,
algology, pathology, physiology, and fishery biology/ecology.  Research
objectives are:<p>
<p>
</center>o	Examination of animal life histories through laboratory and field
experimentation;<p>
<p>
o	Evaluation of food requirements of bivalve mollusks that feed on
microalgae;<p>
<p>
o	Development of culture methodologies for mollusks and finfishes;<p>
<p>
	o	Determination, through lab experiments, of the effects of pollutants on the
life functions of fishes and invertebrates;<p>
<p>
	o	Assessment of the effects of microorganisms on the health, survival, and
growth of living marine resources;<p>
<p>
	o	Development and application of genetic technologies in pollutant and
aquaculture research;  and <p>
<p>
	o	Habitat studies of young-of-the-year fishes.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
