<title> NEFSC </title>
<BODY  bgcolor="#f8f8ff">
<blockquote>
<img align=right src="/labs/sh.jpg">
<p>
<h2>
James J. Howard Marine Sciences Laboratory<br>
Northeast Fisheries Science Center<br>
NOAA, National Marine Fisheries Service<br>
</h2>
<h3>
74 Magruder Road, Sandy Hook<br>
Highlands, NJ 07732<br>
</h3>
<p>
Telephone:  (908) 872-3000, FTS: 908-872-3000<br>
FAX:  (908) 872-3088, FTS: 908-872-3088<br>
<p>
<b>Officer-In-Charge:  Anne Studholme, x3001<br></b>
<a href="http://www.sh.nmfs.gov/">Home Page</a><p>
<p>
     The James J. Howard Marine Sciences Laboratory, located on the New
Jersey shore at Sandy Hook, is a new, state-of-the-art marine research
facility shared by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
(NOAA) and the State of New Jersey.  Federal research at the laboratory is
conducted by NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).
<p>
     The primary mission of the Howard Laboratory is to conduct research in
ecology, leading to a better understanding of both coastal and estuarine
organisms and the effects of human activities on nearshore marine
populations.  To achieve this mission, NMFS research at the laboratory is
organized into the following components:
<p>
   Fishery Ecology Branch<br>
   ----------------------<br>
   Scientists in the Fishery Ecology Branch study the interaction of fishes
   with their environment and how production, growth, survival, and
   migration are affected by environmental change.  A current focus is on
   striped bass and bluefish, and species that interact with these two
   economically important fishes.  Three areas of research are life history
   and recruitment, fish behavior, and habitat evaluation and restoration.  
   In general, scientists working in these areas survey the distribution and
   abundance of fishery resources, study differences in habitat use, and
   gather baseline information on natural biological rates and cycles of
   marine organisms.  With this information, the effects from human causes
   can be distinguished from normal background variability.  Results are used
   to determine the resiliency of ocean and estuarine systems to habitat
   alteration and restoration, and to larger cycles such as global climate
   change.
<p>
   Environmental Chemistry and Quality Branch<br>
   ------------------------------------------<br>
   Research in the Branch addresses how environmental degradation from
   contaminants and nutrient over-enrichment affects fisheries productivity
   as well as our use of fishery resources.  Scientists conduct studies to
   determine the distribution of contaminants in estuarine and continental 
   shelf habitats and in the tissues of animals that reside in those
   habitats.  They also study the biological effects of environmental
   degradation on the food web, develop data to use in verifying models to
   estimate how the marine environment assimilates organic material and 
   contaminants, and study natural processes that govern the dynamics of
   these materials in the hydrosphere.
<p>
   Northern Demersal Program - Stock Assessments<br>
   ---------------------------------------------<br>
   Staff with the Northeast Center's Conservation and Utilization Division
   develop stock assessment information on the status of various mid- and
   north Atlantic commercial fish stocks.  Work within the Division also
   focuses on fisheries interactions, estimates of fishing effort, and
   bycatch issues.  This type of current assessment information allows
   fishery managers to plan and evaluate the effects of various fishery
   management actions.
<p>
   Habitat Conservation Unit<br>
   -------------------------<br>
   Staff with the Habitat Conservation Branch of NMFS' Northeast Regional
   Office review all federal projects and other activities that require a 
   federal permit because of their potential impact on living marine
   resources.  They review projects within the region through on-site
   investigations, field sampling, and literature review.  Recommendations
   are made to regulatory agencies so that projects can proceed with a
   minimum of destruction of important habitat.  The unit receives direction
   from the Northeast Regional Office headquarters in Gloucester, MA.
<p>
The Facility
<p>
     The facility consists of two buildings: a new 32,000 sq ft structure
housing experimental seawater, analytical chemistry, and microbiology
laboratories and, directly across the street, a renovated 35,000 sq ft Army
barracks building converted into offices, conference rooms, and the Lionel
A. Walford Marine Science Library.  The new laboratory was completed in
October 1993.  Renovation of the historic 1890s army building was completed
in 1994.  Design of the new building and renovation of the old were
carefully planned to retain the unique historical character of Fort Hancock
(a historic landmark), while meeting rigorous technical standards demanded
by scientists and conforming to environmental and safety requirements.  NOAA
leases a major portion of the facility, which is owned and operated by the
State of New Jersey.
<p>
History
<p>
     The Howard Marine Laboratory was preceded by NMFS' Sandy Hook
Laboratory, which began operation at Fort Hancock in 1961.  It was
established as a research arm of the Interior Departments's Bureau of Sport
Fisheries and Wildlife, following passage of the Marine Game Fish Act in
1959, and became a regional center for research on marine game fish and the
environment.
     In 1971, the laboratory became part of the newly formed National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the National Marine Fisheries
Service.  Research expanded to include studies of ecosystem responses to
toxins and other environmental degradation, focusing on the New York Bight,
where inshore impacts were profound.
     In 1985, the Sandy Hook Laboratory was destroyed by arson.  Most
equipment, and a 33,000 volume fisheries library were lost.  After the fire,
the staff moved into trailers and old former army barracks to carry out
modest experiments in limited space.  In 1986-87, New Jersey was selected as
the location for constructing a new facility close to the former laboratory
site.  At the groundbreaking ceremony in 1989, the new lab was named the
James J. Howard Marine Sciences Laboratory after the late James Howard, U.S.
Representative of New Jersey's 3rd District, who led the lab rebuilding
effort.
<p>
     
