<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

  <h2 align=center>  Conservation &amp; Utilization Division
</h2>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<p>
<h3 align=center>Dr. Fredric M. Serchuk, Chief<br>
Dr. Stephen H. Clark, Deputy Chief</h3><p>
<p>
The Conservation &amp; Utilization Division collects and analyzes data on the
populations of fishery resources and protected species; the ecological
processes which control resource productivity; the fisheries and other uses of
these resources; and the economics of fishery-resource-based activities.  From
this data collection and analysis, the Division develops information and
provides advice needed by fishery resource and habitat managers at the
regional, national, and international levels for enhancing, conserving, and
allocating fishery resources and for maintaining and enhancing levels of
protected species.  The Division operates through five Branches.<p>
<p>

<h3>
<a name="pdy">Population Dynamics Branch          </h3></a>

<p>
<b>Dr. Steven Murawski, Chief</b><p>
The Population Dynamics Branch develops statistical information and provides
advice to resource managers on the current status and future trends in
abundance and productivity of marine fishery resources off the Northeast coast
of the United States.  The Branch determines the effects of management
alternatives on population sizes and yields of fish and invertebrate stocks and
develops improved quantitative techniques for stock assessment, forecasting of
resource trends, and ecosystem modeling.  Additional research deals with
mixed-fishery and multispecies effects on yields and population trends of
component species-stocks and on marine ecosystems.  Other studies focus on the
biology and/or fisheries for species of particular concern, such as striped
bass and Atlantic salmon.<p>
<p>
<h3>
<a name=pbb>Population Biology Branch          </h3></a>


Dr. Michael Fogarty, Acting Chief</b><p>
The Population Biology Branch conducts research to estimate population age
composition, growth, maturation and mortality rates, fecundity levels and other
biological features of economically important species.  Much of this work is
dependent on aging, by Branch staff, of fishes and invertebrates collected
during both commercial sampling operations and fishery-independent surveys,
which in turn requires development and validation of aging techniques.  Branch
staff also investigate marine food webs through field and laboratory studies of
fish consumption rates and feeding selectivity patterns.  Results of these
studies are incorporated into recruitment and multispecies models to
investigate effects of predation and compensatory population mechanisms on
long-term stability, production, and structure of fish communities of the
Northeast Continental Shelf Ecosystem under different harvest strategies and
environmental regimes.  There is also a substantial commitment to studies of
the biology, feeding, and migratory movements of apex predators, particularly
large sharks.<p>
<p>


<h3>
<a name="ssb1">Survey and Sampling Branch          </h3></a>


Darryl Christensen, Chief</b><p>
The Survey and Sampling Branch collects fishery-dependent data at sea and at
dockside and fishery- independent data during standardized research vessel
surveys from Cape Hatteras to the Scotian Shelf.  Branch staff and observers
under contract perform at-sea operations aboard commercial vessels to collect
information of fishing operations, fishing effort and catch data, including
bycatch and discard information, economic data and vessel efficiency, and
biological samples of landed catch and discard.  Considerable effort is
directed towards monitoring and biological sampling of takes of protected
species.  Branch staff also collect biological samples of the landed catch and
ancillary information at dockside.  During research vessel surveys, the Branch
gathers data on distribution, abundance, and size/age composition of stocks of
economically important species.  Data collected in these programs are archived
into computer data files which are vital for assessment and management.  The
Branch designs, builds, and/or tests much of its sampling gear and evaluates
hydroacoustic sensing systems.  Branch staff also conduct vessel and gear
standardization studies to infuse comparability of survey indices over time and
permit statistical evaluations of sampling adequacy.<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>
Protected Species Branch          </h3>


<p>
David Potter, Acting Chief</b><p>
The Protected Species Branch conducts research, principally off the Northeast
coast of the United States, in support of the NMFS responsibilities under the
Marine Mammal Protection Act, Endangered Species Act, and Magnuson Fishery
Conservation and Management Act.  Research is focused on three areas:
ecological roles and habitat, human interactions including bycatch mitigation,
and population assessment including determination of optimum sustainable
population levels.  As part of this research, the Branch develops improved
population and bycatch estimation techniques and assesses the efficacy of
management actions for bycatch reduction.  The Branch provides information and
advice to the NMFS Northeast Regional Office, the New England and Mid-Atlantic
Fishery Management Councils, NMFS Headquarters, the U.S. Marine Mammal
Commission, and the International Whaling Commission.<p>
<p>

<h3>
Social Sciences Branch         </h3>


Dr. Philip Logan, Chief</b><p>
The Social Sciences Branch gathers data, develops information, and conducts
applied economic and sociocultural research and analyses of marine resource
exploitation and management issues.  It provides analyses and advice to state
and federal agencies, fishery management councils, and other constituents on
the economic, sociocultural, and community effects of interventions into the
operation of the harvest, processing, distribution, final demand, and trade
sectors of the commercial fisheries, and recreational fisheries sectors as
well.  Through such analyses, the Branch seeks to increase the net benefits the
nation derives from living marine resource exploitation.  Social impact
assessments and benefit-cost analyses of regulatory change are executed with
each fishery management plan amendment as required by law.  The Branch's market
news offices in Boston and New York collect and contract to broadcast product
price and inventory information in support of market operations.<p>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="dri">Population Dynamics Branch<br></a>
Demersal Resources Investigation<br>
</h3>


CONTACT:  Wendy Gabriel  NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                         


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Develop information on the present and likely future status of the demersal
fishery resources in the Northeast Region.<p>
<p>
The abundance of demersal fishery resources in the Northeast Region varies due
to the amount of fishing, natural fluctuations in recruitment levels, possibly
longer-term fluctuations in environmental factors, and pollution and habitat
destruction.  Fishery managers make management decisions using information on
the current abundance of the fishery resources, the effect of fishing, and the
likely effect of different fishery regulations.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Update stock assessments for assigned species and provide current scientific
information for Atlantic cod, haddock, yellowtail flounder, pollock, redfish,
white hake, silver hake, winter flounder, witch flounder, American plaice,
cusk, wolffish, ocean pout, red hake, summer flounder, windowpane flounder,
goosefish, tilefish,  blue-fish,and scup. <p>
<p>
<li>Participate in semiannual Northeast Regional Stock Assessment Workshops for
review of new stock assessment procedures, approaches, and methodologies, and
for development of peer-reviewed assessment advice for managers.<p>
 <p>
<li>Review and evaluate the adequacy of 1995 commercial biological sampling
activities, develop and provide 1996 commercial port sampling and sea sampling
requirements, and evaluate logbook data collection program for use in stock
assessments.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytic support and technical infor-mation to regional fishery
management councils (including New England Fishery Management Council
Groundfish Plan Development Team and Mid-
                                                                                              
Atlantic
Fishery Management Council Summer Flounder Technical Monitoring Com-mittee),
Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission (ASMFC) (including ASMFC technical
committees), Chesapeake Bay Stock Assessment Technical Advisory Group,
North-west Atlantic Fisheries Organization (NAFO),  International Convention
for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas (ICCAT), and Canadian Regional
Assessment and Advisory Process meetings.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in NMFS National Stock Assessment Workshop and on committees and
working groups of the International Council for the Exploration of the Sea
(ICES), and in annual U.S./Canada Scientific Discussions.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate on the Scientific and Statistical Committee of the Mid-Atlantic
Fishery Manage-ment Council.<p>
<p>
<li>Assist Washington Office and NMFS Southeast Fisheries Science Center (SEFSC)
with assessment of large pelagics (recreational fishery statistical
analysis).<p>
<p>
<li>Assist SEFSC with assessment of sea turtles (expert panel mandated by
biological opinion).<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct research on fisheries technical interactions, including evaluation of
effects of management options on Mid-
                                                                                              
Atlantic
mixed- species trawl and recreational fisheries for scup, black sea bass, and
summer flounder.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Develop bioeconomic models of stock rebuild	-ing strategies for depleted New
England ground-fish resources.  Develop fishing mortality-effort relationships
to monitor effectiveness of effort control programs for New England
groundfish.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue research on potential effects of tem-perature changes on
distribution of Northwest Atlantic fishery resources, based on historical NEFSC
trawl survey data.<p>
</ul>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<b></b>			<p>
<li>Updated assessments of status, e.g., summer flounder, bluefish, goosefish, or
other groundfish, as recommended by the SAW Steering Com-mittee; and completed
major revisions of assess-ments of Southern New England/Mid-Atlantic winter
flounder and Gulf of Maine winter flounder, including SARC working papers, SARC
subcommittee reports, and <i>NEFSC Reference Documents</i>.<p>
<p>
<li>Evaluation of trends in relative abundance and spatial and temporal
distributions for stocks comprising the Northeast demersal complex.<p>
<p>
<li>Evaluation of fishing vessel logbook data for various uses in stock
assessments.<p>
<p>
<li>Updated sections of "Status of Fishery Resources  off the Northeastern United
States."<p>
<p>
<li>Updated sections for the U.S. Research Report to NAFO for 1995.<p>
<p>
<li>Information for the New England Fishery Management Council on the impacts of
trip limits, closed areas, and effort limitation on rebuilding time for
depleted New England groundfish stocks.<p>
<p>
<li>Information for the New England Fishery Management Council on the development
of overfishing definitions for goosefish.<p>
<p>
<li>Information for the Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management Council on the impacts of
alter-native levels of fishing mortality on potential landings and spawning
stock biomass of summer flounder, and on multispecies management
perspectives.<p>
<p>
<li>Additional technical information for the New England and Mid-Atlantic Fishery
Management Councils and the Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission.<p>
<p>
<li>Presentations to American Fisheries Society  regional and national meetings,
and ICES Annual Science Conference.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="iri">Population Dynamics Branch<br></a>
Invertebrate Resources Investigation</h3>


CONTACT:  Paul Rago     NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                          


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Develop information on the present and likely future status of the invertebrate
fishery resources in the U.S. Northeast Region, improve size-based assessment
techniques, and develop forecasting methods.<p>
<p>
Commercially important invertebrate species exhibit a wide array of life
history strategies -- ranging from mobile <i>Loligo</i> squid that live only 10
months to sedentary ocean quahogs that live up to 100 years.  Thus, the
relative importance of fishing mortality and environmental factors varies
considerably among species.  Management advice for invertebrate resources must
incorporate uncertainty in estimation and objectives for long-term
utilization.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Update stock assessments for assigned species and provide current scientific
information for long-finned (<i>Loligo</i>) and short-finned (<i>Illex</i>)
squid, American lobster, sea scallops, surf clams, ocean quahogs, and northern
shrimp.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in semiannual Northeast Regional Stock assessment Workshops for
review of new stock assessment procedures, approaches, and methodologies, and
for development of assess-ment advice for managers.<p>
<p>
<li>Review and evaluate the adequacy of 1994 commercial biological sampling
activities, and develop and provide 1995 commercial port and sea sampling
requirements.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytical support and technical informa-tion to regional fishery
management councils, Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission, and other
regulatory bodies.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in the ICES Annual Science Conference, NMFS National Stock
Assessment Workshop, ICES working/study groups and committees, and the annual
U.S./Canada Scientific Discussions.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue research on fisheries technical inter-actions, especially bycatch of
finfish in mobile gear (e.g., scallop dredges, shrimp trawls).<p>
<p>
<li>Continue studies on effort reduction, optimal harvest strategies, and
economics of invertebrate resources in the Northeast Region.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct methodological research on size- and stage-based population models.<p>
<p>
<li>Improve stochastic forecasting methods for medium- and long-term
predictions.<p>
<p>
<li>Develop Geographic Information System (GIS) applications for integration of
commercial fishery, sea sampling, and survey data.<p>
<p>
<li>Evaluate data collection procedures for surfclam and ocean quahog
assessments.<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Catch advice on surf clam, ocean quahog, long-finned (<i>Loligo</i>) and
short-finned (<i>Illex</i>) squid, and American lobster for the New England and
Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management Councils.<p>
<p>
<li>SAW working papers and subcommittee reports, and Center reference documents
on surf clams, ocean quahogs, long-finned and short-finned squid, and American
lobster.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Major revisions of long- and short-finned squid and American lobster stock
assessment infor-mation.<p>
<p>
<li>Technical information for New England Fishery Management Council on potential
effectiveness of effort reduction measures in coastwide lobster fisheries, and
on use of fishery-dependent infor-mation in scallop assessments.<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Technical information for Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management Council on
biological reference points and harvest policies.<p>
<p>
<li>Completed research project on <i>Illex</i> squid (in cooperation with
Department of Fisheries and Oceans, St. Johns, Newfoundland).<p>
<p>
<li>Assessment software for stochastic projections and DeLury population model.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>

<a name="cpri">Population Dynamics Branch<br></a>
Coastal/Pelagic Resources Investigation</h3>


CONTACT:  William Overholtz    NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                   


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Develop information on the present and likely future status of the coastal and
pelagic fishery resources in the NMFS Northeast Region, including the
congressionally authorized Atlantic salmon and striped bass programs.<p>
<p>
The abundance of the coastal and pelagic fishery resources in the Northeast
Region varies due to the amount of fishing, natural fluctuations in recruitment
levels, and possibly longer-term fluctuations in environmental factors.
Fishery managers make management decisions using information on the current
abundance of the fishery resources, the effect of fishing, and the likely
effect of different fishery regulations.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Update stock assessments for assigned species and provide current scientific
information for Atlantic mackerel, herring, Atlantic salmon, butterfish, shad,
river herring, striped bass, black sea bass, bluefish, and scup.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in semiannual Northeast Regional Stock Assessment Workshops for
review of new stock assessment procedures, approaches, and methodologies, and
for development of assess-ment advice for mangers.<p>
<p>
<li>Review and evaluate the adequacy of 1994 commercial biological sampling
activities, and develop and provide 1995 commercial port and sea sampling
requirements.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytical support and technical infor-mation to regional Fishery
Management Councils, Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission, and other
regulatory bodies.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in ICES Annual Science Conference, committees, and working/study
groups; and in annual U.S./Canada Scientific Discussions.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct research on fisheries technical inter-actions.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue studies of effort reduction, optimal harvest strategies, and
economics of coastal and pelagic fishery resources in the Northeast Region.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct analyses on the effects of global climate change on the distribution,
abundance, and biological productivity of coastal and pelagic fishery resources
in the Northeast Region.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Assessment advice on Atlantic mackerel for the Mid-Atlantic Fishery
Management Council.<p>
<p>
<li>SAW working papers and subcommittee reports, and Center reference documents
on scup and black sea bass.<p>
<p>
<li>Sections for "Status of Fishery Resources off the Northeastern United
States."<p>
<p>
<li>Major revisions to scup and black sea bass assessments.<p>
<p>
<li>Technical information for the New England and Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management
Councils.<p>
<p>
<li>Presentations at American Fisheries Society regional and national meetings
and the ICES Annual Science Conference.<p>
<p>
<li>Contributions to "Our Living Oceans" and to "Status and Trends of the
Nation's Living Marine Resources" for the status and trends report of the
National Biological Service.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<hr>
 <h3> 
<a name="ass"?Population Dynamics Branch<br></a>
Coastal/Pelagic Resources Investigation<br>
Atlantic Salmon Study</h3>


CONTACT:  Kevin Friedland     NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                    


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Obtain information to determine the status of Atlantic salmon stocks and
impacts of distant-water fisheries, investigate the role of oceanographic
factors as determinant of early marine survival, provide analytical support for
interagency restoration programs, and evaluate applicability of Endangered
Species Act to New England salmon populations.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Conduct laboratory, field, and computer modeling studies on the maturation,
growth, recruitment, and early marine life history of Atlantic salmon in both
North America and Europe.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in ICES North Atlantic Salmon Working Group to develop assessment
of stock status and catch advice for salmon in the North Atlantic.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in U.S. Atlantic Salmon Assessment Committee meetings to review
current status of U.S. stocks.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytical support and technical information to U.S. commissioners of
North Atlantic Salmon Conservation Organization (NASCO).<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in interagency assessment of naturally reproducing Atlantic
salmon populations and determination of status under the Endangered Species
Act.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Serve as chairman of ICES Anadromous and Catadromous Committee.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in cooperative research with University of Rhode Island
(electronic data-logging tag), Florida State University (historical ocean
climate), University of Massachusetts (marine predation on salmon), and Maine
Sea Run Salmon Commission (salmon population assessment).<p>
<p>
<li>Provide technical support to NEFSC on population consequences of proposed
hydroelectric facilities.<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Reports of the North Atlantic Salmon Working Group and the U.S. Atlantic
Salmon Assessment Committee.<p>
<p>
<li>Paper on the comparative survival and growth of two salmon stocks submitted
to<i> Fishery Bulletin</i>.<p>
<p>
<li>Working papers for ICES working groups and presentations on elemental
analysis of salmon otoliths at the ICES Annual Science Conference.<p>
<p>
<li>Section for "Status of Fishery Resources off the <p>
Northeastern United States for 1995."<p>
<p>
<li>Paper on basinwide juvenile population estimates submitted to <i>North
American Journal of Fisheries Management</i>.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="esbr">Population Dynamics Branch<br></a>
Coastal/Pelagic Resources Investigation<br>
Striped Bass Study<p>

</h3>

CONTACT:  Gary Shepherd NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                          


<b></b><p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Under the Congressionally authorized Striped Bass Study, obtain information
necessary to assess the status of striped bass juvenile and adult stocks;
provide advice to state and federal fishery managers; and prepare an annual
report to Congress.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Participate in meetings of ASMFC Technical Committee and Stock Assessment
Subcommittee to review current status, evaluate effectiveness of existing
management measures, and recommend revised management measures.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate on interagency teams to review states' implementation of
Amendment 5 of the Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission  Striped Bass
Management Plan.<p>
<p>
<li>Investigate striped bass tagging data bases (ASMFC, American Littoral
Society) using GIS and statistical models.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytical support to NEFSC on contracts and cooperative agreements
related to interstate assessment of striped bass resources.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Section of "Status of Fishery Resources off the Northeastern United
States."<p>
<p>
<li>Manuscript on "A Case History of Effective Fishery Management:  Atlantic
Striped Bass."<p>
<p>
<li>Revised source documents for the ASMFC Striped Bass Management Plan
(Amendment 5).<p>
<p>
<li>Revised analytical assessment of stocks of Atlantic coast striped bass.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="fcdi">Population Biology Branch<br>   </a>
Food Chain Dynamics Investigation<p>
</h3>



CONTACT:  Rodney Rountree NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                        


<b></b><p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Food web studies indicate that predation on pre-recruit fish represents a major
component of natural mortality which controls recruitment and overall fish
production.  Density-dependent, predator-prey inter-actions are of particular
importance since they affect the stock/recruitment relationships which are
critical to understanding long-term dynamics of fish populations.  The chief
objective of this task is to determine consumption rates and the functional
form of feeding interrelationships of fish, and to develop recruitment and
multispecies models which incor-porate these effects.  These models will be
used to help predict long-term impacts of various harvest strategies and
environmental trends on yield potential and species composition.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Sample fish stomachs on fall, winter, spring, and summer Resource Survey
Investigation bottom trawl surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct special Coastal Ocean Program research cruises during May, June, and
August. These cruises will track the density distribution of larval cod and
haddock on Georges Bank throughout the pelagic phase and into the early
postsettlement juvenile phase.  Food habit samples together with hydroacoustic
and bottom trawl surveys will be used to relate pelagic and demersal predator
densities with larval and early juvenile cod and haddock densities, in order to
quantify predation mortality of cod and haddock larvae on Georges Bank.<p>
<p>
<li>Perform audits and data entry on stomach data from priority cruises.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Continue development of the 1963-95 food habits data time series, as a
relational data set linked with Resource Survey Investigation bottom trawl
survey data, and Fishery Biology Investigation age and growth data.<p>
<p>
<li>Further develop extensive online documentation for Food Chair Dynamics
Investigation data sets and data base management system, including various
aspects of user assistance programs, tutorials, etc.<p>
<p>
<li>Determine diet, consumption rates, and prey fields for major pelagic and
demersal fishes.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue analysis of consumption, diet overlap, and feeding selectivity of
mackerel/herring sampled on Georges Bank in April-May 1990.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue development of multispecies models of the Georges Bank Ecosystem.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue analyses of biomass shifts, diet overlap and predator-prey
interactions involving principal groundfishes and flounders versus
elasmobranchs and other groundfishes.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue correlation analysis of mackerel 	migration, satellite and MARMAP
data, and gadid recruitment on Georges Bank during 1981-1987.<p>
<p>
<li>Determine predator species guilds (species assemblages with similar diet and
habits) based on food habits data collected on Georges Bank during 1973-1990.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue development of multispecies virtual population analyses with
colleagues at the University of Rhode Island.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Integrate laboratory studies of gastric evacuation conducted in cooperation
with colleagues at the University of Rhode Island and the University of
</ul>

<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>1973-1990 food habits data as part of a relational data set linking food
habits, bottom trawl survey, and age-growth data sets.<p>
<p>
<li>Online documentation of the Food Chain Dynamics Investigation data base
management system and data bases, including World Wide Web page access to the
documentation.<p>
<p>
<li>Six weeks of special study cruises during May-August 1996 to obtain data on
pelagic predator, and larval cod and haddock, densities and distributions,
together with data on predation on larval cod and haddock by pelagic and
demersal fishes.<p>
<p>
<li>Software to audit 1991-1996 data from Resource Survey Investigation bottom
trawl surveys and special Food Chain Dynamics Investigation research cruises.<p>
<p>
<li>Software to enter food habits data from laboratory and at-sea processed
samples.<p>
<p>
<li>Technical report documenting diet composition of key predators by size class
and geographic area, based on food habits data collected during 1973-1990
Resource Survey Investigation bottom trawl surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Report on predator guild structures on Georges Bank based on food habits data
from bottom trawl surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Report on the prevalence of cannibalism among fishes sampled during 1973-1990
bottom trawl surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Draft report comparing young-of-the-year Atlantic cod and haddock inter- and
intra-annual spatial distributions with respect to environmental factors and
potential predator fields, based on data collected during 1993-1996 Food Chain
Dynamics Investigation special research cruises. <p>
<p>
<li>DNA/RNA and polyclonal antibody probes for cod and haddock to be used in
testing for the presence, in the stomachs of potential predators, of cod and
haddock larvae which have been digested beyond recognition. <p>
<p>
<li>Processed stomach samples for key predators from the 1981-1984 period.<p>
<p>
<li>Report on macrobenthic invertebrates of Georges Bank/Gulf of Maine region.<p>
<p>
<li>Data report on the diet of 180 species of Northwest Atlantic fishes.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="fbi">Population Biology Branch<br>   </a>
Fishery Biology Investigation<br>   
</h3>    


CONTACT: Frank P. Almeida NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                        


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<b></b><p>
Compile data and develop information relative to growth and mortality rates,
maturation, fecundity, and physiological and behavioral characteristics. Major
emphasis is directed towards determining age for characterizing population age
structure. Biolo-gical parameter estimates for finfish and shellfish species
are required for stock assessments and related research.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Conduct routine age determinations for 17 species: cod, haddock, pollock,
mackerel, butterfish, redfish, silver hake, yellowtail flounder, summer
flounder, winter flounder, scup, Atlantic herring, black sea bass, American
plaice, witch flounder, white hake, and surf clam; and for special research
studies as required.<p>
<p>
<li>Audit and finalize age data files and biological data (fish length,
identification, weight, sex, maturity) collected during resource surveys;
maintain and modify age data building system; and improve data accessibility
and reliability.<p>
<p>
<li>Develop improved biological parameter estimates and current growth parameter
estimates for ocean pout and larval/juvenile cod and haddock.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct population biology studies; validation and growth studies for white
hake and longfin squid; and growth and maturation studies for ocean pout, cod,
haddock, and silver hake.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue to evaluate biological sampling require-ments for commercial catches
and resource surveys.  Participate in sample collection as required.<p>
<p>
<li>Investigate new technology for aging and other research.<p>
<p>
<li>Participate in age structure exchanges with Canadian and other aging
laboratories.  Host American Fisheries Society-sponsored aging workshop.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide aging support to constituent groups.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Audited age data files.<p>
<p>
<li>Ocean pout growth study.<p>
<p>
<li>White hake validation study.<p>
<p>
<li>Age data building system for all sample sources (research vessel surveys,
commercial fishery, and domestic sea sample program) converted to network
computer system.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="apex">Population Biology Branch<br>   </a>
Apex Predators Investigation<br>   
</h3>    


CONTACT:  Nancy Kohler     NEFSC, Narragansett Laboratory                                     


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Study the biology of highly migratory species of apex predators with emphasis
on migrations, age and growth, reproductive biology, food chain dynamics, and
population changes of large Atlantic sharks.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Continue cooperative shark tagging program.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide information for shark management.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct a shark survey cruise.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue reproductive, food habit, and age-and- growth, and migration
studies of Atlantic sharks.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li><i>The Shark Tagger</i> newsletter.<p>
<p>
<li>Age and growth of the bignose sharks.<p>
<p>
<li>Blue shark food habits.<p>
<p>
<li>Sexual maturity of large Atlantic sharks.<p>
<p>
<li>Overview of migration and distribution of large Atlantic sharks.<p>
<p>
<li>Age and growth of the South African dusky shark.<p>
<p>
<li>Sandbar shark nursery grounds.<p>
<p>
<li>Porbeagle repoduction.<p>
<p>
<li>Nurse shark habitats.<p>
<p>
<li>Overview of skate age and growth.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="ssb">Survey and Sampling Branch<br>    </a>
Resource Surveys Investigation<br>    
</h3>


CONTACT: Thomas Azarovitz                     NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                    


<b></b><p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Provide quantitative population data for assessments and ecosystem research, as
well as data for broad-scale ecosystem studies. Although directed at
economically important finfish and shellfish species, data are collected on all
species caught.  The surveys also provide opportunities for collecting
ocean-ographic and plankton data, and for monitoring disease.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Plan and conduct winter, spring, summer, and autumn bottom trawl surveys, and
scallop and shrimp cruises.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue to study and analyze gear and vessel effects; maintain and test
clam, scallop, and trawl gear. <p>
<p>
<li>Continue to introduce new technology to surveys; improve data entry and
archiving procedures; and improve accessibility to and reliability of data
files.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li><i>Fishermen's Report</i>, timely summary of data from the NEFSC bottom trawl
and sea scallop surveys.  Reports contain listed and plotted catch data
(unaudited) of commercially and recreationally important species from Cape
Hatteras to western Scotian Shelf.<p>
<p>
<li>Audited bottom trawl, scallop, and shrimp files.<p>
<p>
<li>Automated electronic station selection and plotting system for resource
surveys, eliminating the need to routinely plot stations on paper charts.<p>
<p>
<li>Documentation of improvements to multiyear SURVAN analysis program, and to
survey data collection procedures.<p>
<p>
<li>Data samples and reports for constituent groups.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="psi">Survey and Sampling Branch<br>   </a>
Port Sampling Investigation<br>   
</h3>


CONTACT: Harold Foster NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                           


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Collect and report biological samples and data to characterize fishery
resources of the Northeast Continental Shelf as required for assessment and
management; conduct studies to improve precision and reliability of biological
sampling activities; and collect and report samples and information for other
studies as required.  Collection of fisheries data and biological samples is
mandated by the Magnuson Fisheries Conservation and Management Act of 1976 and
other legislation.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<b></b>o	Collect (from dealers, processors, and vessel captains) biological
samples and related information <p>
<p>
<li>Coordinate with state agencies and maintain liaison with industry to obtain
basic biological data.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Biological samples, including scales, otoliths, and other hard body parts for
aging work.<p>
<p>
<li>Reports and data files for use in stock assessments and related studies.<p>
<p>
<li>Reports and data files for ancillary studies as requested.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<h3>
<a name="ssi">Survey and Sampling Branch<br>   </a>
Sea Sampling Investigation<br>   
</h3>


CONTACT:  Patricia Gerrior NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                       


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Obtain and maintain data for the characterization of catch, bycatch, and
discards in Northwest Atlantic domestic and foreign fisheries; provide mandated
Marine Mammal Protection Act and fishery management plan observer coverage of
specific domestic fisheries; and provide 100 percent observer coverage of East
Coast foreign fishing activity as mandated by the Magnuson Fishery Conservation
and Management Act and the Atlantic Tunas Conservation Act.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Deploy observers to domestic and foreign fishing vessels to collect catch,
effort, incidental take, gear, economic, environmental, and biological data and
to monitor compliance with applicable domestic and foreign fishing
regulations.<p>
<p>
<li>Manage above data.<p>
<p>
<li>Monitor observer contract.<p>
<p>
<li>Schedule coverage to meet legal mandates and NMFS data needs.<p>
<p>
<li>Train observers.<p>
<p>
<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Catch, effort, incidental take, gear, economic, environmental, and biological
data from approximately 3,000 domestic and 150 foreign sea days.<p>
<p>
<li>Reports, data files, and analyses as requested to meet stock assessment,
Marine Mammal Protection Act, Endangered Species Act, fisheries management, and
industry needs. <p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="psb3"><h3>Conservation &amp; Utilization Division<br>   </a>
Protected Species Branch<br>   
</h3>


CONTACT:  David Potter                         NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                   


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Marine mammals off the Northeast coast of the United States are managed under
the provisions of the Marine Mammal Protection Act, Endangered Species Act, and
Magnuson Fishery Conservation and Management Act.  Several populations of
marine mammals are subject to incidental mortality associated with commercial
fishing operations.  Additionally, several populations consume species of fish
of economic value. The significance of this predation on the fishery resources,
and conversely, the significance of the bycatch of protected species are of
primary concern. <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Administer mandated research funds for marine mammal research, including
research planning and proposals, contract administration, preparation of annual
reports to Congress, U.S. Marine Mammal Commission, and International Whaling
Commission.    <p>
<p>
<li>Estimate abundance of harbor porpoise in northern Gulf of Maine and Bay of
Fundy, based on summer 1995 surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Continue investigation of the relationship between porpoise and prey fish
distributions and ocean-ographic features.<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct pilot study to investigate adaptive cluster sampling techniques to
estimate abundances.                    <p>
<li>Continue PINGLE, at-sea, data-entry system development and testing.<p>
<p>
<li>Analyze season/area closure effects and determine appropriate responses (year
2).<p>
<p>
<li>Conduct pelagic delphinid necropsy survey, targeting species killed in
driftnet fisheries.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide more complete abundance estimates of marine mammal species,
particularly strategic species using summer 1995 survey data.<p>
<p>
<li>Estimate total bycatch levels of each population of each marine mammal
species for each fishery using sea sampling data. Determine stock structure for
each species subject to significant bycatch, principally harbor porpoise, pilot
whales, and bottlenose dolphins.<p>
<p>
<li>Determine vital rates for each species subject to significant bycatch.  Life
history parameters: vital rates analyses and population modeling (cooperative
agreement with WHOI).<p>
<p>
<li>Maintain photoidentification catalogs for right, humpback, and fin whales
(contracts with New England Aquarium, College of the Atlantic, University of
Rhode Island, and Center for Coastal Studies).<p>
<p>
<li>Serve as the Head of the U.S. Scientific  Delegation to the International
Whaling Com-mission and attend their Annual Meeting.<p>
<b></b><p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Evaluation of marine mammal biology, distri-bution,  population size, and
ecological relation-ships, based on results of summer 1995 aerial and shipboard
surveys.<p>
<p>
<li>Analyses of line-transect survey data sets to evaluate factors affecting
population size estimates.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Bycatch estimates for marine mammals from commercial and  sea sampling data
files.<p>
<p>
<li>Revised stock assessments for marine mammal species indigenous to
northeastern coastal waters of the United States.<p>
<p>
<li>New statistical techniques for estimating popu-lation size and bycatch
estimates of marine mammals.<p>
<p>
<li>Necropsy sessions to collect biological data for harbor porpoise and other
strategic species killed in fishing operations.<p>
<p>
<li>Line-transect workshop (will be conducted pending availability of funds).<p>
<p>
<li>Analyses of fishery and ecological interactions for selected cetaceans, and
of cetacean habitat use.<p>
<p>
<li>Analyses in support of work of the International Whaling Commission.<p>
<p>
<li>Publication of survey research results in peer- reviewed journals.<p>
<p>
<li>Report summarizing two decades of NEFSC- funded marine mammal research.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="ssb4"><h3>Conservation &amp; Utilization Division<br>   </a>
Social Sciences Branch<br>   
</h3>


CONTACT:  Philip Logan              NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                              


<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Increase the net economic and social benefits the national derives from living
marine resource exploitation, both commercial and recreational by: (1)
providing advice, analyses, and publications to enhance the understanding of
the economic, social, and cultural forces affecting exploitation and the
consequences of the management of that exploitation on participants and
communities; and (2) collecting and communicating information on ex-vessel and
wholesale prices and inventories to help create efficient markets for marine
products.<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Provide advice and social and economic analyses in the development of fishery
management plans and amendments through participation on various plan
development teams.<p>
<p>
<li>Develop bioeconomic models of commercial and recreational fisheries to
enhance policy analysis.<p>
<p>
<li>Review fishery management plans and amendments.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide data, analyses, and profiles on request of various aspects of the
harvest sector, processing sector, and trade and recreational fisheries to
regional fishery management councils and within NMFS and NOAA.<p>
<p>
<li>Develop cost and earnings surveys for recreational and commercial fisheries.
Support state-initiated recreational data collection efforts.<p>
<p>
<li>Report early morning daily prices and landings to phone network to establish
New England prices for groundfish and lobsters.<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Collect, compile, and transmit wholesale price and inventory information to
NMFS Headquarters for the International Fax on Demand Program.<p>
<p>
<li>Review fishing industry grant proposals, CMER proposals, S-K proposals, and
various journal articles.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide guidance on the development of social science data needs, on the
development of social impact assessments to fishery managment plans, and on the
execution of data gathering contracts.<p>
<p>
<li>Provide analytical support to U.S. representatives on international
management bodies: NASCO, ICCAT, ICES, etc.<p>
<p>
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<p>
<li>Annual overview of the economic performance of fisheries in the region for
the "Status of the Fishery Resources off the Northeastern United States" and
national and regional sections for the national publication "Economic Status of
Fisheries."<p>
<p>
<li>Publication on description and analysis of North-east gillnet fleet.<p>
<p>
<li>Published compendium of economic data requirements for fishery management.<p>
<p>
<li>Data bases and information for monitoring and analysis of days-at-sea
provisions of Amendment 7.<p>
<p>
<li>Databases and analyses for design of potential vessel retirement program.
Provide analysis of preliminary program.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>Published research report on available data on vessel fixed and operating
costs.<p>
<p>
<li>Party and charter vessel cost and earnings Survey design instrument.<p>
<p>
<li>Draft environmental impact statement analyses and regulatory impact reviews
for groundfish, scallops, bluefin tuna, lobsters, and others.<p>
<p>
<li>Various written and oral presentations to regional fishery management
councils and their committees in support of plan development.<p>
<p>
<li>Formal reviews of fishery economic impact statements and social impact
assessments for fishery management plans.<p>
 <p>
<li>Agency position papers/planning documents on social and economic issues
related to fisheries.  <p>
<p>
<li>Publication, "Summary Report of Economic Add-on Survey of Marine Recreational
Fisheries in the Northeast."<p>
<p>
<li>Publication with ASMFC, "Marine Recreational Data Needs." <p>
<p>
<li>Presentation at Bioeconomics Workshop,"Age Based Bioeconomic Model."</body></html>
</ul>
