<h2 align=center>Research Planning and Coordination Staff<br></h2>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h3>Research Planning, Evaluation, and Coordination</h3>

CONTACT: Dr. Ambrose Jearld, Jr.  Woods Hole Laboratory                                       

<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Provide for a planning, evaluation, and coordination process that addresses
internal and external integration of the NEFSC research program for reporting
purposes; establish and monitor com-munication linkages with users of NEFSC
information; work closely with the users to assure that their information needs
are communicated and understood; work closely with Northeast Regional
Adminstrator, the Northeast Regional Operations Office staff, and NEFSC
scientists to assure that research products address user needs; identify
studies that are conducted at various institutions, which may augment NEFSC
research, then coordinate integration of these efforts into the NEFSC research
program; manage CMER programs; and address identified issues in the foreseeable
future.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Lead Center research planning and evaluation activities.
<p>
<li>Serve as regional representative on the NMFS Strategic Planning Team.
<p>
<li>Serve as NMFS Chair of the Extramural Steering Committee on Expanding
Opportunities in Ocean Services.
<li>Serve as the Center representative for technology transfer, Extramural Grants
Coordinator, contact for Stellwagen Bank National Marine Sanctuary, 
and represent the Center on the Marine Mammal Protection Act Task Force.
<li>Coordinate production of Center responses to requests from various components
of NMFS and other federal, state, and private organizations.

<li>Coordinate Center research vessel activities and assist in identifying
acceptable charter vessels.

<li>Participate in the reassessment of NOAA's Fleet Replacement and Modernization
plan.

<li>Review requirements for fisheries research vessels.

<li>Serve as liaison to regional fishery management councils.

<li>Serve as secretariat for the Northeast Regional Stock Assessment Workshops
(SAWs).

<li>Chair  and coordinate SAWs 21 and 22, and produce SAW documentation.

<li>Coordinate Center participation on the Lobster Review Panel.

<li>Coordinate Center activities in support of fishery management plan
developmental amendment.

<li>Manage CMER programs at the Universities of Massachusetts and Rhode Island
and at Rutgers University.

</ul>





<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>

<li>Quarterly progress reports of Center research activities.

<li>Annual summary of funded Center research.

<li><i>NEFSC Research Directory, 1996</i>.

<li>Draft problem formulation document for the Waquoit Bay Watershed Ecological
Risk Assessment Project.

<li>Report to Congress on cumulative effects of multiple stressors from the
Symposium on the Gulf of Maine Ecosystem Health Workshop.


<li>Announcements of extramural funding opportu-nities. 

<li>Reports of the 21st and 22nd SAWs:  "Stock Assessment Review Committee (SARC)
Consensus Summary of Assessments" and "Advisory Report on Stock Status."

<li>Annual report and statement of program direction of CMER at the Universities
of Massachusetts and Rhode Island and at Rutgers University.

<li>Memorandum of Agreement with Kingsborough Community College.

<li>Issues of the RPAC newsletter,<i> LINKAGES</i>.
</ul>



<hr>

<h3>
UMass/NOAA Cooperative Marine Education and Research (CMER)
Program</h3>

CONTACT:  John Boreman  Amherst, MA                                                           

<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
Under a Cooperative Agreement between the University of Massachusetts (UMass)
and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration , combine university
and agency expertise to address marine issues affecting the commonwealth,
region, and nation.<p>
<p>
<b>ONGOING PROJECTS IN FY96</b>

<ul>
<li>Prey Size and Type Selectivity and Predator Dynamics of Marine Fish on the
Northeast Continental Shelf.

<li>Contemporary Use of Marine Resources for Subsistence:  an Exploratory Study
in the Com-monwealth of Massachusetts.

<li>Detection of Irradiated Seafood.	

<li>Biology of the Longhorn Sculpin.

<li>Quality Determination in Atlantic Mackerel.

<li>Seabird Entanglement by Commercial Fisheries in the Northwest Atlantic
Ocean.

<li>Early Development and Metamorphosis of the American Goosefish.

<li>Establishment of NOAA-supported Under-graduate Summer Research Internships.
</ul>

