<h2 align=center>Program Support Staff</h2>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h3> Research Communications</h3>


CONTACT:  Teri Frady      NEFSC, Woods Hole Laboratory                                        

<p>
<b>OBJECTIVE</b><p>
<p>
The Research Communications Unit of the NEFSC is responsible for information
acquisition for and transfer among NEFSC research and management programs, and
for public presentation of NMFS Northeast Region activities, information, and
policy.  The Unit's activities are conducted on a regional basis (for all
laboratories and programs of the NEFSC, and for the staff of the regional
office in the area of public communications) and encompass five areas:  (1)
operating a research and public display aquarium; (2) operating research
libraries and providing library services to researchers, managers, and other
clients; (3) scientific and technical publishing; (4) graphic services for
presenting research activities in publications and presentations; and (5)
public communication of research activities and management policy through
organized activities in public and constituent affairs, and public education.
<p>
<p>
<b>ANTICIPATED ACTIVITIES IN FY96</b>
<ul>
<li>Maintain aquarium tanks, water quality, environment, and marine taxa held in
NEFSC research/public display aquarium in Woods Hole.

<li>Carry out aquarium research (growth studies, tag retention studies, studies
relating to holding marine animals for display).

<li>Act as liaison with the Marine Mammal Stranding Network, NMFS NER Office, and
NMFS Office of Protected Resources for marine mammals and turtles held at the
facility.

<li>Develop and execute educational outreach programs and materials in support of
the NEFSC efforts to encourage science education and to transfer research
results to client groups and the public.


<li>Operate full-service, professionally staffed, marine science field libraries
at two sites, and marine science collections at two sites.

<li>Continue transition to electronic delivery of library services and products
where appropriate.

<li>Manage contracts for library services.

<li>Maintain NER/NEFSC Scientific Publication Archive.

<li>Operate and referee the inhouse process for peer review and NEFSC approval of
approximately 250 manuscripts, presentations, and poster displays annually.

<li>Perform copy technical editing and managing editing for manuscripts. 

<li>Print and distribute two internally published series of technical reports. 

<li>Maintain mailing lists for various NEFSC technical series.  

<li>Design, composite, and produce mechanicals for NER/NEFSC printed materials.


<li>Design and/or create graphics in a variety of media for oral presentations
and publication.

<li>Design and produce exhibits for NEFSC Woods Hole Aquarium and other public
display opportunities.

<li>Develop and manage NEFSC Photo Archive.  

<li>Continue graphic shop conversion to digital base and resulting online
delivery systems.



<li>Execute public affairs tasks relating to media coverage of NER/NEFSC research
results and activities (i.e., developing message statements and talking points
with staff on issues, managing media contacts and events, acting as
spokesperson, tracking media coverage.

<li>Producing NER/NEFSC news releases, <i>Research Highlights</i>, and other
research communications for a popular audience.

<li>Act as field contact for the NOAA Public Affairs and Legislative Affairs
staff stationed in Washington, DC. 
</ul>
<b>ANTICIPATED PRODUCTS IN FY96</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Improved perception of NOAA/NMFS science and public policy management
resulting in an image of the agency as a prudent and fair steward of the
nation's living marine resources.

<li>Responses to approximately 300,000 instances of onsite visitations, telephone
inquiries, and written requests instituted by or referred to the staff for
action.

<li>Successful completion of day-to-day support for staff in the areas of
responsibility.
<li>Emergency communications plan.

<li>Specific communications plans for "hot" Northeast issues.  Most likely: New
England groundfish, New Bedford Harbor clean-up, Atlantic salmon Endangered
Species Act listing, American lobster management, enforcement actions, marine
mammal stranding and entanglement coverage.

<li>Regular issuance of NER/NEFSC published information products: 4-6 <i>Research
Highlights</i>, 2-4 media guides on issues, 3-12<i> NOAA Technical Memoranda
NMFS-NEz</i>, 10-25 <u>Northeast Fisheries Science Center Reference
Documents</u>, and  biennial indexed publication listing.

<li>Expanded Web Site to include public affairs section.

<li>Online photo archive.

<li>Improved "gateway" to the aquarium.
</ul>




</DOC>
