<body bgcolor="#f8f8f8">

<h1 align=center>
NOAA ALBATROSS IV 96-08
</h1>

<font size=+1>
<p>
The Food Chain Dynamics Investigation of the NOAA/NMFS Northeast
Fisheries Science Center plans to conduct three Coastal Oceans
Program (COP) Predator-prey study research cruises on Georges
Bank during 1996, pending final administrative approval.
                               
Current plans are for the second cruise to take place on or about
17-28 June, 1996 aboard the research vessel NOAA ALBATROSS IV. 
The primary  objective of this cruise is to investigate predation
on larval fish (particularly Atlantic cod and haddock) by pelagic
fish predators on Georges Bank.  
<p>
PRELIMINARY DESCRIPTION OF METHODS
<p>
     A systematic grid survey of approximately 70 stations will
be conducted across the Georges Bank region (Fig. 1) during the
first week of the cruise.  Time permitting, a second phase of
sampling will involved site-specific sampling in an area of
highest densities of post-larval cod and haddock.
<p>
     At each station, a 61 cm bongo sampler (fitted with 0.333
and 0.505 mm mesh plankton nets) with an attached CTD will be
deployed to determine density distributions of larval fish and
conductivity-temperature-depth profiles. The bongo/CTD array will
be fished double-obliquely at about 1.5-2 knots according to
standard MARMAP procedures.  A larger sampler (e.g., Methot
trawl) may also be used for sampling post-larval and juvenile
age-0 fish, depending on the availability of funds.  Immediately
after each bongo/CTD haul, a standard Yankee 36 bottom trawl will
be fished to collect potential pelagic fish predators of larval
fish.  The Yankee 36 trawl will be fished at 3.5 knots for 30
minute duration according to standard  NEFSC groundfish survey
procedures.  After each trawl, a surface bucket temperature and
secchi disc casts will be taken before heading to the next
station.  Bridge/station and scientific/catch sampling data will
be recorded on standard NEFSC trawl and bongo logsheets using
standard NEFSC procedures.
<p>
     Acoustical data will be collected using the vessel's Simrad
EK500 Scientific Sounder and haul-mounted split-beam transducers
(38 and 120 kHz).  Echo-integration of the acoustical data will
be done at sea using the Simrad BI500 Post-processing software. 
The SCS computer and sensing system will also be used throughout
the cruise to collect various navigational, meteorological, and
environmental data.  Several hours at the beginning and/or end of
the cruise will be devoted to the calibration of the 38 and 120
kHz transducers.  Calibration of each transducer involves
suspending a standard calibration sphere below the vessel
directly within the acoustical beam.  Typically, this is
accomplished by suspending a sphere using 3 monofilament lines
attached at three positions around the vessel.  A minimum depth
of 20 meters is needed for calibrations, and this might be done
during slack tide either along the dock of the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution or anchored at sea. 
<p>
     Scientific sampling on deck will involve weighing and
measuring fish collected by the Yankee 36 trawl.  Trawl catches
will be processed using standard NEFSC methods.  In addition,
age-0 cod and haddock collected by the trawl will be measured to
the nearest mm and recorded on the back of the trawl log. 
Stomach contents of selected fish predators will be preserved in
10% formalin solution.  Subsamples (0.1-0.5 ml) of unidentified
age-0 fish prey found in stomachs will be frozen in liquid
nitrogen for identification of species (i.e., sand lance, cod or
haddock) using DNA and polyclonal probes in the laboratory.
Stomach samples of other predator species will be examined at
sea.  Bongo samples will be sorted for ichthyoplankton during the
cruise.  Bongo samples will be preserved in 4% formalin solution. 
Other special biological sampling requests may be completed as
time permits.
<p>
</pre>
<p align=center>
<img src="geomap.gif">
<p>

Figure 1.  Proposed study area for NOAA's Coastal Ocean Program
           (COP) Predator-Prey research cruises during 1996.
