<body bgcolor="#f8f8f8">

<h1 align=center>
NOAA ALBATROSS IV 96-10
</h1>

<font size=+1>

<p>
The Food Chain Dynamics Investigation of the NOAA/NMFS Northeast
Fisheries Science Center plans to conduct three Coastal Oceans
Program (COP) Predator-prey study research cruises on Georges
Bank during 1996, pending final administrative approval.
                               
Current plans are for the third cruise to take place on or about
28 August - 6 September, 1996 aboard the research vessel NOAA
ALBATROSS IV.  The primary  objective of this cruise is to
investigate predation on age-0 cod and haddock during their
transition from pelagic to early-demersal phases of life history.
<p>

PRELIMINARY DESCRIPTION OF METHODS
<p>

A systematic grid survey of approximately 70 stations will be
conducted across the Georges Bank region (Fig. 1) during the
first week of the cruise to examine the distribution of age-0 cod
and haddock during their early-demersal phase of life history. 
The second phase of the cruise will involve a fine scale grid
survey and site-specific sampling in the region of high
concentrations of age-0 cod and haddock (historically on the
Northeast Peak) to examine spatial and diel changes in
predator-prey interactions and catchability.
<p>
At each station, the primary sampling gear will be a standard
NEFSC Yankee 36 bottom trawl.  Standard procedures and logsheets
typically used for NEFSC bottom trawl surveys will be followed,
however modifications may be specified by the chief scientist
during operations depending on catch results.  Surface bucket
temperature and Seabird CTD profiles will also be taken before
each trawl deployment.  A small pipe dredge will be attached to
the foot-rope of the trawl to verify substrate type.  A small
naturalist dredge may also be deployed during site-specific
operations.
<p>
     Scientific sampling on deck will involve weighing and
measuring fish collected by the Yankee 36 trawl.  Trawl catches
will be processed using standard NEFSC methods.  In addition,
age-0 cod and haddock collected by the trawl will be measured to
the nearest mm and recorded on the back of the trawl log. 
Stomach contents of potential predators on age-0 fish will be
examined and weighed at sea.  Subsamples (0.1-0.5 ml) of
unidentified age-0 fish prey found in stomachs will be frozen in
liquid nitrogen for identification of species (i.e., sand lance,
cod or haddock) using DNA and polyclonal probes in the
laboratory.  Remains of unidentified age-0 fish prey will be
preserved in 10% formaldehyde solution.  Otoliths from
unidentified fish prey may also be saved (in A&G envelops) to
identified back in the laboratory.  Other special biological
sampling requests may be completed, time permitting.
<p>

</pre>
<p align=center>
<img src="geomap.gif">

<p>
Figure 1.  Proposed study area for NOAA's Coastal Ocean Program
           (COP) Predator-Prey research cruises during 1996.

