<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<center>
<p><b>IN THE
               SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES
                                                
<P>
                         October Term, 1977
                                                
<P>
                             No. 77-528
<P>
                   FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION,
Petitioner,
<p>
v.
<P>
                             PACIFICA FOUNDATION,
Respondent.
<P>
                    On Writ of Certiorari to the
United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
Circuit
</b></center>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=100%><br>
<P>
  BRIEF OF THE AMERICAN CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION, THE ASSOCIATION
OF AMERICAN
PUBLISHERS, INC., THE CITIZENS COMMUNICATION CENTER, THE FREEDOM
TO
  READ FOUNDATION, P.E.N. AMERICAN CENTER, and POETS &amp; WRITERS,
INC., 
<P>
                            AMICI CURIAE
<P>
                        INTEREST OF AMICI

<P>
      Amici are six organizations whose work depends on the
safeguards of
 
freedoms of speech and
 
  press secured by the First Amendment and abridged by the Federal
Communications
 
  Commission in this case.
 
  <BR>

<P>
           The American Civil Liberties Union is a nationwide,
non-partisan
 
organization of two
 
  hundred thousand members, dedicated to defending the principles
embodied in
 
the Bill of Rights
 
  to the Constitution.  For over fifty years, the ACLU has sought
to preserve
 
and strengthen the
 
  First Amendment as a bulwark against all forms of governmental
censorship.
 
  <BR>

<P>
      The Association of American Publishers, Inc. is the major
national
 
association for publishers
 
  of general books, textbooks and educational materials in the
United States.
 
AAP's more than 325
 
  members include large commercial book publishers and smaller
or non-profit
 
publishers,
 
  including university presses and scholarly associations and,
in the
 
aggregate, publish a majority
 
  of all general and educational books produced in the United
States.  The
 
AAP has traditionally
 
  sought to protect First Amendment rights and has opposed censorship
and
 
other attempts to limit
 
  freedom of communication.
 
  <BR>

<P>
      The Citizens Communication Center is a public interest
law firm
 
specializing in
 
  communications law.  CCC represents the rights of listeners
before federal
 
agencies and in
 
  federal courts.
 
  <BR>

<P>
           The Freedom to Read Foundation, a nonprofit organization
supported
 
by voluntary
 
  donations, was established in 1969 by the American Library
Association to
 
promote and defend
 
  First Amendment rights; to foster libraries as institutions
wherein every
 
citizen's First
 
  Amendment freedoms are fulfilled; to support the right of
libraries to
 
include in their collections
 
  and make available any work which they may legally acquire;
and set legal
 
precedent for the
 
  freedom to read on behalf of all citizens.
 
  <BR>

<P>
      P.E.N. American Center, the United States chapter of International
 
P.E.N., is a non-profit
 
  association of 1500 leading American poets, playwrights, essayists,
 
editors, novelists and
 
  translators.  One of P.E.N.'s basic goals is to promote cooperation
among
 
men and women of
 
  letters in the interest of freedom of expression everywhere.
 The charter
 
of International P.E.N.
 
  affirms that P.E.N. stands for the principle of unhampered
transmission of
 
thought within each
 
  nation and between all nations, and members pledge themselves
to oppose any
 
form of
 
  suppression of freedom of expression in the country and community
to which
 
they belong.
 
  <BR>

<P>
           Poets &amp; Writers, Inc., is a non-profit corporation
organized to
 
disseminate information on
 
  the literary world to creative writers and to the public,
through
 
publications and through financial
 
  support of public readings by poets and writers of their creative
works.
 
  <BR>

<P>
      The interests of amici in fostering the widest diversity
of artistic,
 
literary, political, and social
 
  expression of which our nation is capable, and in protecting
&quot;uninhibited,
 
robust, and wide-open&quot;
 
  comment, expression, and dissent, would be critically affected,
directly or
 
indirectly, if the
 
  Commission's order is sustained.  Contrary to the Commission's
view, there
 
is only one First
 
  Amendment, and it is applicable to all forms of expression.
 Amici urge the
 
Court, once again, to
 
  deny to the government the power it seeks to protect us from
&quot;indecent&quot;
 
language, and to
 
  reaffirm that the freedoms of speech and press are inimical
to the regime
 
of the censor, in all of
 
  its varied forms.
 
  <BR>

<P>
                        <h4>Questions Presented</h4>
 
                                                           

<P>
          1. May a licensed radio station be forbidden by the
Federal
 
Communications Commission to
 
  broadcast any program containing such words as &quot;fuck&quot;
and &quot;shit&quot;?
 
  <BR>

 
  
<P>
      2.  Do the &quot;special qualities&quot; of broadcast
communication justify
 
government censorship of
 
  radio station WBAI's programs?
 
  <BR>

 
  
<P>
      3.  May the constitutional right of minors to receive
broadcast
 
communication be limited to
 
  programs which the FCC considers decent?
 
  <BR>

 
                       <h4>Preliminary Statement</h4>
 
  <BR>

<P>
      In 1973, George Carlin, the comedian and social satirist,
recorded a
 
commentary on attitudes
 
  toward language and certain &quot;filthy words&quot; that
are an integral part of it.
 
Carlin catalogued and
 
  verbally dissected what he prophetically labeled the seven
words that &quot;you
 
couldn't say on the
 
  public...airwaves.... The ones you definitely couldn't say.&quot;
Undeniably,
 
the message
 
  communicated by the monologue depend upon Carlin's artistic
repetition and
 
incantation of the
 
  seven words themselves, to illustrate the amusing, inconsistent
and
 
hypocritical conventions that
 
  apply to our use of the language. Certainly, no &quot;translation&quot;
of the
 
monologue not employing the
 
  seven words themselves could possibly convey Carlin's insight
and ideas
 
about language in as
 
  incisive or persuasive a fashion. (1)
 
  <BR>

<P>
  1/    Although it does a gross disservice to Carlin's masterful,
satirical
 
presentation for one simply
 
  to enumerate the seven words upon which the Commission fixated,
the list is
 
as follows:  &quot;fuck,&quot;
 
  &quot;shit,&quot; &quot;piss,'' &quot;motherfucker,&quot;
&quot;cocksucker,&quot; &quot;cunt,&quot; and &quot;tit.
 
  <BR>

<P>
           In the fall of 1973, WBAI, a listener supported,
non-profit radio
 
station in New York City
 
  known for a political and intellectual format intended for
a limited and
 
sophisticated segment of
 
  the listening audience, broadcast the Carlin monologue in
the context of a
 
general discussion of
 
  contemporary attitudes toward language.  Mindful that, despite
its serious
 
approach toward this
 
  significant topic, use of the seven words might offend some
listeners, WBAI
 
advised those who
 
  might be offended to tune out the monologue segment of the
discussion.  The
 
broadcast that
 
  ensued, however, offended one listener, who registered his
complaint with
 
the Federal
 
  Communications Commission.
 
  <BR>

<P>
     As a result of this single, isolated complaint, the FCC
ratified the
 
prophetic Carlin list of seven
 
  &quot;unmentionable&quot; words and disciplined WBAI for having
broadcast them.
 
Entirely ignoring the
 
  serious context and purpose of WBAI's broadcast of the Carlin
monologue,
 
and without any
 
  in-depth consideration, inter alia, of the sociological, linguistic
or
 
educational implications of its
 
  ipse dixit ruling, the FCC simply characterized the seven
words as per se
 
&quot;obnoxious, gutter
 
  language&quot; having as their inevitable effect the &quot;debasing
and brutalizing
 
of human beings.&quot;  It
 
  therefore held that the seven words -- and presumably other
&quot;indecent&quot;
 
words of a similar
 
  character -- may never be broadcast, at least when there is
a &quot;reasonable
 
risk&quot; that children &quot;may
 
  be&quot; in the audience.  During the &quot;late evening hours&quot;
when the number of
 
children in the
 
  audience &quot;reduced to a minimum,&quot; such offensive
words may &quot;conceivably&quot; be
 
aired but only
 
  with a warning and at the broadcaster's peril since any words
used must be
 
found to have &quot;serious
 
  literary, artistic, political, or scientific value.&quot;
 And even in the
 
context of live coverage of a
 
  news-making event, where broadcast of &quot;indecent&quot;
words may be unavoidable
 
and therefore
 
  permissible, the FCC suggested that repeated news broadcast
of such words
 
may lead to
 
  disciplinary action.
 
  <BR>

<P>
                        <h4>Summary of Argument</h4>
 
                           
<P>
     Today, its order on &quot;indecent&quot; language having
been reversed as an
 
&quot;unconstitutional act of
 
  censorship&quot; by the Court of Appeals, the Commission asks
this Court to
 
sanction its attempt to
 
  censor non-obscene words, taken out of context, that it considers
 
inappropriate for broadcast.  In
 
  amici's view, the FCC order would impose an unprecedented
form of
 
censorship, barred by the
 
  FCC's own statutory mandate, and entirely unconnected to the
kind of grave
 
or imminent danger
 
  of harmful conduct over which any organ of the state could
purport to have
 
jurisdiction.  This
 
  arrogation by the FCC of censorial power over offensive&quot;
language would
 
deprive a substantial
 
  portion of the adult population of the United States of an
opportunity to
 
hear broadcasts of
 
  serious, non-obscene materials of undeniable intellectual,
cultural or
 
legitimate entertainment
 
  value.  The FCC order would prevent broadcasters, who are
in any event
 
bound to use their
 
  license in the public interest, from exercising their already
limited
 
discretion freely to determine
 
  the content of their broadcasts.  And, despite the FCC's cavalier
 
assumption that it is capable of
 
  standing in loco parentis with regard to material that may
be broadcast to
 
children, the FCC order
 
  wholly fails to recognize that it would also deprive children
of a
 
significant range of materials
 
  considered appropriate and worthwhile for their education
or entertainment,
 
and of their
 
  constitutional right to receive ideas via radio. 
 
  <BR>

<P>
     To the extent the FCC has purported to fit its order within
the category
 
of unprotected
 
  &quot;obscenity,&quot; by reformulating the standards of Miller
v. California, 413
 
U.S 15 (1973), to give
 
  meaning to the prohibition in 18 U.S.C. 1464 of &quot;indecent&quot;
language, its
 
ruling conforms neither
 
  procedurally nor substantively to any &quot;obscenity&quot;
standard ever adopted by
 
this Court.  Indeed,
 
  the FCC, in its proscription of words that &quot;depict sexual
and excretory
 
activities in a manner
 
  patently offensive by contemporary community standards for
the broadcast
 
medium,&quot; has cut
 
  itself entirely free from the moorings of this Court's strictly
 
circumscribed definition of the
 
  permissible reach of obscenity laws or regulations.
 
  <BR>

<P>
     Thus, this Court's view of the constitutional law of obscenity
-- as an
 
exception to the literal
 
  command of the First Amendment rests upon the premise that
obscenity is
 
expression devoid of
 
  social value.  Yet the FCC order purports to censor words
without regard to
 
social value. 
 
  Although the law of obscenity as defined by this Court has
always been
 
concerned with the
 
  depraved or titillating appeal to &quot;prurient interest,&quot;
the FCC ban holds
 
prurience to be entirely
 
  unnecessary to justify the censorship it deems appropriate
with regard to
 
expression broadcast
 
  over media it licenses or regulates.  Finally, although the
American
 
constitutional law of
 
  obscenity since Roth -- and indeed dating back to the Ulysses
case and
 
beyond -- has definitively
 
  rejected the &quot;Hicklin&quot; rule and has held that obscenity
can be determined
 
based only on the
 
  predominant appeal&quot; of the work &quot;taken as a whole,&quot;
the FCC order permits
 
censorship of single
 
  words wholly out of context, regardless of the nature of the
entire work.
 
  <BR>

<P>
       Set adrift from every one of constitutional standards
for determining
 
what is obscene, the first
 
  FCC application of its new law of offensive broadcast expression
has
 
yielded the following
 
  results:
 
  <BR>

<P>
  -- The FCC seeks to protect unsupervised minors from material
broadcast
 
during an hour when
 
  the number of children in the audience is at a minimum and
in a listening
 
situation -- an
 
  automobile -- where children are by definition under the control
of an adult.
 
  <BR>

<P>
  -- The FCC purports to be concerned with the &quot;thrusting&quot;
of unwanted
 
materials in a situation
 
  where the licensee gave a warning prior to the broadcast and,
in any event,
 
where a dial-twister,
 
  unwittingly tuning in on the broadcast, could avoid further
messages by a
 
further twist of the
 
  dial, a negligible burden on the few persons who wished not
to hear the
 
messace in order to
 
  protect the constitutional rights of those who with to hear
the message.
 
  <BR>

<P>
  -- The FCC purports to censor in order to further the &quot;larger
and more
 
effective use of radio in
 
  the public interest,&quot; yet an extensive body of highly
significant
 
literature, drama, poetry and
 
  prose intended or adults and for children which portrays the
reality of the
 
human experience, but
 
  which may contain what the FCC views as offensive words, is
either banned
 
or relegated to
 
  hours when a majority of the public is no longer in the radio
(or
 
television) audience.
 
  <BR>

<P>
  These results are wholly at odds with the First Amendment
jurisprudence of
 
this Court and with
 
  the basic premises of a free society.
 
  <BR>

<P>
       The FCC Order also infringes the distinct constitutional
rights of
 
minors to be free of
 
  unconstitutional censorship of messages they might wish to
receive.
 


<P>
      Finally, the Commission's actions, in imposing a prior
restraint on the
 
broadcast of &quot;indecent&quot;
 
  words with none of the safeguards afforded by a criminal proceeding,
are
 
without express
 
  statutory authorization and conflict with the express Congressional
ban on
 
censorship of radio. 
<h4>Notes</h4>
<p> (1)    Although it does a gross disservice to Carlin's masterful,
satirical
 presentation for one simply
   to enumerate the seven words upon which the Commission fixated,
the list is
 as follows:  &quot;fuck,&quot;
   &quot;shit,&quot; &quot;piss,'' &quot;motherfucker,&quot;
&quot;cocksucker,&quot; &quot;cunt,&quot; and &quot;tit.
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
