<head>
<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">

<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Docket 93-1823<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">STATE OF MISSOURI, et al.,<br>
Petitioners<br>
v.<br>
KALIMA JENKINS, et al.,<br>
Respondents<br></font></h2>

<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>INTEREST OF AMICI (1)</h4>

   <p>    The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is a nationwide,
nonprofit, nonpartisan organization with nearly 300,000 members dedicated
to the principles of liberty and equality embodied in the Constitution. 
The ACLU of Western Missouri is its local affiliate with offices in Kansas
City, Missouri.  The ACLU and its affiliates have been deeply involved in
the effort to desegregate America's schools and to remove the vestiges of
prior, de jure segregation.  As part of that ongoing effort, the ACLU
served as counsel in Freeman v. Pitts, 503 U.S. ___, 112 S.Ct. 1430
(1992), this Court's most recent school desegregation decision.</p>

<p>       The American Jewish Congress (AJC) is an organization of American
Jews founded in 1918 to protect the civil, political, economic and
religious rights of American Jews.  Beginning long before Brown v. Board
of Education, AJC has participated in cases involving the desegregation of
the nation's public schools.
</p>
 <p>       The Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund (AALDEF) is a
nonprofit civil rights organization dedicated to defending the rights of
Asian Americans through litigation, community education, and advocacy to
shape public policy in the areas of voting rights, immigrants' rights,
employment and labor rights, and environmental justice.  AALDEF currently
represents victims of anti-Asian violence and Japanese Americans who were
incarcerated in U.S. camps during World War II.
</p>
 <p>      The National Women's Law Center (Center) is a non-profit legal
advocacy organization dedicated to the advancement and protection of
women's rights and the corresponding elimination of sex discrimination
from all facets of American life, with a special emphasis on promoting
equal opportunity of education for girls and women.  Since 1972, the
Center has actively participated in litigation to secure the rights of
women and has participated in major Supreme Court cases addressing women's
right to equal protection under the law.
</p>
<p>       The Puerto Rican Legal Defense and Education Fund (PRLDEF) exists
to ensure that every Puerto Rican and other Latino is guaranteed the
opportunity to succeed.  Through advocacy, education and litigation,
PRLDEF seeks to secure and safeguard the political, economic, social and
legal rights of our community.  We will succeed when Latinos enjoy full
and equal participation in American society.  Over the 22 years since its
founding PRLDEF has initiated hundreds of cases to combat discrimination
in education, voting rights, employment and housing.  PRLDEF has
successfully argued landmark cases including several in the United States
Supreme Court. 
</p>
<h4>STATEMENT OF THE CASE</h4>

<p>       An historical context is necessary to understand the current
posture of this case.  In 1984, the district court held that the
respondent Kansas City, Missouri School District (KCMSD) and the
petitioner State of Missouri (Missouri) were liable for segregation in
KCMSD.  Jenkins v. Missouri, 593 F.Supp. 1485 (W.D.Mo. 1984).  In
discussing the racial composition of the schools within KCMSD, the
district court found that "vestiges of [the former] dual system still
remain."  Id. at 1493.  Of particular relevance here, the court found that
"the inferior education indigenous of the state-compelled dual school
system has lingering effects in [KCMSD]."  Id. at 1492.  Not surprisingly,
the district court also found that this "inferior education" had "produced
low achievement."  Id.  Each of these findings was supported by specific
evidence in the record.  Perhaps for that reason, "[t]he State did not
appeal [the 1984] decision . . . and that holding is not challenged here." 
Brief for Petitioners at 7, n.8.  The parties were then ordered to propose
remedies for the constitutional violations the district court had found. 
593 F.Supp. at 1506. 
</p>
<p>       At the remedy stage, all parties, including Missouri, proffered
remedial plans that involved educational enhancements.  "Both the State of
Missouri and the KCMSD have proposed program components designed to
increase student achievement . . . ."  Jenkins v. Missouri, 639 F.Supp.
19, 25 (W.D.Mo. 1985).  For example, "both the State of Missouri and the
KCMSD endorse[d] achieving AAA status [a state evaluation of the quality
of education], reducing class size at the elementary and secondary level,
summer school, full day kindergarten, before and after school tutoring and
early childhood development programs."  Id. at 26.  Moreover, at least one
of these programs, achieving AAA status, was proposed by Missouri as well
as the KCMSD "to regain and maintain a quality education program . . .
[and] to assist in attracting and maintaining non-minority enrollment." 
Id. at 27. 
</p>
 <p>      In determining which plans to adopt, the district court made clear
that its "goal [was] the elimination of all vestiges of state imposed
segregation."  Id. at 23.  The court acknowledged that its "broad
equitable powers" were limited by "the nature and scope of the
constitutional violation, the interests of state and local authorities in
managing their own affairs consistent with the Constitution, and insuring
that the remedy is designed to restore the victims of discriminatory
conduct to the position they would have occupied in the absence of such
conduct."  Id. at 23.  Pursuant to those broad but limited powers, the
court accepted some proposed programs and rejected others.  In some
instances, such as the early childhood development program, the district
court rejected the KCMSD plan and accepted that proposed by Missouri.  Id.
at 32.  In making its decisions, the court repeatedly stated that its goal
was to "to improve the academic achievement of students within KCMSD, both
as a remedial measure and to maintain and attract non-minority enrollment
. . . . "  Id. at 31.  Recognizing its obligation to consider alternative
remedial measures, however, the court adopted this approach only after
concluding that "mandatory student reassignment" would not be effective. 
Id. at 38. 
</p>
 <p>      Missouri did not challenge many of these orders on appeal. 
Jenkins v. Missouri, 807 F.2d 657, 682, 683 (8th Cir. 1986).  For example,
Missouri did not challenge the order requiring that AAA rating be achieved
throughout KCMSD, regardless of whether it affected non-minority children
as well as minority children.  Similarly, Missouri did not challenge the
goal identified by the district court -- namely, to improve educational
achievement in order to remedy past harm to achievement and in order to
attract non-minorities into the district.  Instead, Missouri focused its
appeal on those aspects of the district court's remedial plan that the
state, alone, was required to finance.  Id. at 682.  In an en banc
decision, the Eighth Circuit adjusted some of the funding formulas to
reassign more of the costs to KCMSD.  However, the Eighth Circuit
unanimously affirmed the propriety of an educational enhancement remedy in
this case.  Id. at 682-86.  In addition, the court of appeals expressly
rejected arguments that one part of the remedy (voluntary interdistrict
transfers) was, in part, imposing "an interdistrict remedy for an
intradistrict violation."  Id. at 683. 
</p>
 <p>     Despite the Eighth Circuit's 1986 rulings, the district court
found that for the following seven years Missouri "opposed the
implementation of any program offered to desegregate the KCMSD . . . ." 
Jenkins v. Missouri, Order, April 16, 1993, at 2.  The district court
further noted that "the State has never offered the Court a viable, even
tenable, alternative and has been extremely antagonistic in its approach
to effecting the desegregation of the KCMSD."  Id. (emphasis in original). 
</p>
<p>      In 1992 and 1993, Missouri opposed the continuation of some of the
education programs ordered by the district court.  The district court
largely rejected that opposition and the court of appeals affirmed. 
Jenkins v. Missouri, 11 F.3d 755 (8th Cir. 1993).  The court of appeals
noted that the goal of educational improvement to remedy past educational
deficits and attract non-minority students had been set in the liability
and remedy orders.  Id. at 759.  The court of appeals also concluded that
the district court had implicitly found that vestiges of segregation
remained in KCMSD and it affirmed that finding as well.  Id. at 762.  As
the Eighth Circuit observed in its 1993 decision:  "The only evidence
before the district court with respect to the degree of progress on
elimination of vestiges of past discrimination was at best that a start
had been made."  Id. at 765.  Finally, in "a few further words," the court
of appeals noted that the appropriate measure of any desegregation remedy
is its effectiveness in eliminating the vestiges of segregation.  Id. at
765-66. (2)
</p>
<p>      In a petition for en banc review, Missouri argued that the court
of appeals had set a new and improper goal by insisting that test scores
in KCMSD must reach some unspecified level for unitariness to exist. 
Jenkins v. Missouri, 19 F.3d 393 (8th Cir. 1994).  Significantly, however,
the authors of the panel opinion rejected that interpretation of their
prior decision, which they construed as holding only that test scores were
a relevant criterion in measuring the effectiveness of a desegregation
remedy.  Id. at 395. 
</p>
    <p>   Meanwhile, the district court began the process of providing for
the orderly termination of this case.  Order, April 16, 1993.  The court
found that as a result of the desegregation remedies in this case there
had been "substantial progress toward desegregating the schools."  Id. at
8.  The court also found that "there has been a trend of improvement in
academic achievement in the KCMSD" but that more was practical and
feasible.  Id. at 11.  In response to additional programs proposed by both
KCMSD and plaintiffs, the district court noted that "it is time that the
District be subject to a very definite reality check" and that the
district could simply not "dream" up new programs.  Id. at 13. 
Accordingly, KCMSD was ordered to provide a plan for funding education in
Kansas City when "the court ordered funding would be withdrawn."  Id. at
21.  Thus, contrary to the impression conveyed by Missouri, this case now
comes before the Court as it is moving toward its conclusion. 
</p>
<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT</h4>
<p>
        In the district court and the court of appeals, and to a large
extent in its petition for certiorari in this case, Missouri relied
primarily on its claim that it had eliminated all vestiges of segregation
that it had caused because it had provided sufficient funds to Kansas City
to make expenditures at least as high as in surrounding districts.  That,
Missouri argued, was all it had to do.  Although in those courts, and in
this Court, Missouri purported to be arguing a simple application of
existing law, the argument was instead a fundamental challenge to the
long-established principle of Brown v. Board of Education, 349 U.S. 294
(1955)(Brown II), Green v. School Board of New Kent County, 391 U.S. 430
(1968); Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education, 402 U.S. 1
(1971), and other cases that compliance has been achieved not when a
remedy has been instituted but when that remedy has been effective. 
</p>
 <p>      In its brief on the merits in this Court, though Missouri still
professes to be simply applying existing law, it goes even farther in a
fundamental challenge to the entire structure of desegregation law.  The
district court found that segregation had caused a drop in educational
achievement.  Missouri and all other parties had initially proposed
remedies designed to improve educational achievement and to attract
additional non-minority students.  The district court found that those
remedies were working in eliminating the vestiges of segregation and
attracting non-minority children.  Missouri concedes that this conclusion
was a reasonable one.  Brief for Petitioners at 19, 21.  Nevertheless,
Missouri argues -- for the first time -- that the entire remedial concept
in this case is improper as a matter of law.  That remedy, Missouri notes,
is designed to achieve two goals, to improve educational achievement and
to attract non-minority children.  Missouri challenges the legitimacy of
both goals in this case. 
</p>
 <p>      Missouri's principal challenge is to the goal of improving
educational achievement.  It argues that educational deficits cannot, as a
matter of law, ever be considered vestiges of segregation, a principle
rejected in Brown v. Board of Education, 347 U.S. 483 (1954)(Brown I), and
thereafter.  It argues that nothing but the factors identified in Green
can be considered a vestige, a principle rejected most recently in Freeman
v. Pitts, 503 U.S. ___, 112 S.Ct. 1430 (1992); see also id. at 1454, n.1
(Souter, J., concurring).  Here, the district court specifically found
that deficiencies in student achievement caused by segregation remain. 
Despite this finding, Missouri argues that because 40 years have elapsed
since Brown,(3) the Court should hold as a matter of law that, regardless
of the evidence, no court can find vestiges of depressed achievement.  If
adopted, the principle that time has erased all vestiges of segregation
cannot be limited to achievement.  Taken to its logical limit, it would
open up every school desegregation case to a motion to dismiss on the
grounds that no vestiges can possibly remain as a matter of law. 
</p>
 <p>      Missouri also argues that the goal of attracting non-minority
white children from private schools and from the surrounding suburbs is
improper, as a matter of law, based on the principle of Milliken v.
Bradley, 418 U.S. 717 (1974) (Milliken I), that an intradistrict violation
cannot form the basis of a interdistrict remedy.  In Milliken I, the Court
held that parties, such as suburban districts, that had not violated the
Constitution, could not be required to participate in a remedy to cure the
violation.  However, in Hills v. Gautreaux, 425 U.S. 284 (1976), the Court
expressly rejected the interpretation of Milliken I that Missouri now
advances.  As the Gautreaux Court explained, the error of the district
court in Milliken I was not in ordering relief that had effects beyond the
borders of Detroit, but in ordering remedial actions by parties who were
not found to have caused any violation.  In this case, the remedy order
may have effects beyond the borders of Kansas City, but it does not order
actions by any parties other than those found to have violated the law. 
Missouri's argument would thus amount to a wide expansion of the Milliken
I holding and an explicit overruling of Gautreaux. 
</p>
    <p>   Finally, Missouri argues that even if the goals of the remedy
order are acceptable, the remedy order is broader than necessary to cure
the violations on several grounds.  First, Missouri argues that the remedy
is overbroad because it is expensive, a proposition contradicted by Swann. 
Second, Missouri argues that the remedy is overbroad because it benefits
white children as well as minority children.  This may be true but, as the
district court noted, Missouri has failed to offer a practical method of
achieving the twin goals of the remedy without affecting white children in
the district.  Third, Missouri argues that one of the measures to be used
to determine compliance -- i.e., that test scores must reach national
averages -- is improper because it is unattainable and because it requires
curing at least some educational deficits that were not caused by
segregation.  To the extent the lower courts were to hold that test scores
must reach national averages, regardless of whether that improvement was
necessary to cure constitutional violations, they would be in error,
violating the causation principles most recently reiterated in Freeman. 
However, neither the district court and the court of appeals have so held. 
Rather, they have held that test scores are relevant in determining if all
vestiges of depressed educational achievement have been eliminated.  To
hold that test scores are irrelevant, as a matter of law, because
improvement is unattainable or for any other reason would not only reject
the long-established principle that remedies must be effective, but would
also have this Court definitively resolve questions of educational
methodology best left, in the first instance, to the district courts after
an evidentiary hearing. 
</p>
  <p>    Thus, although Missouri has couched its argument in the guise of
application of existing law, it is instead a request for a radical
revision of existing law.  No reasons are suggested for this Court to
reverse the long-standing principles of school desegregation law and none
could be.  The district court's most recent opinions in this case have
shown its sensitivity to the need to bring this case to an end upon
elimination of the vestiges of segregation in KCMSD.  This Court's
intervention is not needed to accomplish that goal.  More generally, lower
courts throughout the country are bringing school desegregation cases to a
conclusion, as evidenced by the decreased number of such cases and the
increasing findings of unitary status.  But, where district courts find
that vestiges of segregation do remain, this Court should not hold as a
matter of law that those district courts were wrong, and dismantle
desegregation remedies that are proving effective.  For this Court to do
so would send a powerful and unfortunate signal that this Court has
abandoned its demand that all state-imposed segregation end. 
</p>
<center>
<hr width=60%>
</center>
<p>1.  Letters of consent to the filing of this brief have been lodged with
the Clerk of the Court pursuant to Rule 37.3. 
</p><p>
2.  The district court and the court of appeals also addressed Missouri's
objections to ordered salary increases for KCMSD personnel.  Amici do not
address this portion of those orders. 
</p><p>
3.  As KCMSD notes in its brief, the remedy in this case was only fully
implemented three years ago, not 40.
</p>
</blockquote>
<center>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
