</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Aclu in the Court</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Docket 93-1525<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">LEBRON<br>
 v.<br>
 NATIONAL RAILROAD PASSENGER CORPORATION<br></font></h2>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>The court below erred when it dismissed Lebron's claim on the
ground that Amtrak has significant and pervasive connections to
the government. Under the &quot;mutual contacts&quot; test for state action
that this Court has applied since Burton v. Wilmington Parking
Authority, 365 U.S. 715, 725 (1961), and has continued to apply
in more recent years, see, e.g., Lugar v. Edmondson Oil Co., 457
U.S. 922 (1982), respondent should be held to be a state actor
and its actions should be required to conform to the First
Amendment.
</p>
<p>     This Court has long recognized that in certain circumstances
where the government and a private actor are pervasively
intertwined, state action should be found regardless or whether a
specific action has been funded, encouraged or coerced by
government. This Court has looked to three factors in making this
determination: (1) whether the government is significantly and
pervasively involved in the private entity's affairs; (2) whether
the government controls the activities of the private entity; and
(3) whether the ties between the government and the private
entity create the appearance of state involvement in
unconstitutional conduct. Under these guidelines, Amtrak, with
its broad and pervasive ties to the federal government, is a
state actor subject to constitutional standard.
</p>
<p>     The court below also erred in holding that different tests
of state action should be used to determine whether an ostensibly
private entity should be held to constitutional standards
depending on the constitutional right involved. The state action
analysis should not vary depending on the constitutional right
involved. Moreover, in no case should a test be applied that
accords the First Amendment anything less than the highest level
of protection.
</p>
</blockquote>
<center>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
<p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
