HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 13:21:38 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:01 GMT
Content-length: 7368
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Court</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">No. 94-5707<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">Wilson v. Arkansas</font></h2>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>STATEMENT OF THE CASE
</h4>
<p>On December 31, 1992, Arkansas law enforcement officers executed a search
warrant to look for illegal narcotics and a small caliber handgun at the
home of the petitioner, Sharlene Wilson.  According to the testimony at
the suppression hearing, when the police arrived at petitioner's home,
petitioner, her son, petitioner's soon-to-be husband, and two friends were
inside the house.  See J.A. 62-63.  Officer Henry Efird, who had obtained
the search warrant, admitted that he heard no officer announce their
presence, knock on the door of petitioner's home, or state their purpose
for being there.  J.A. 40. 
</p>
<p>Officer Roger Walls testified that he &quot;was either [the] first or second&quot;
officer who entered petitioner's home.  J.A.40.  Officer Walls stated that
when the search team arrived at petitioner's home it &quot;was late evening,&quot;
although he could not recall the exact time or whether it was already
dark.  J.A. 41.  Officer Walls testified that the &quot;prime door&quot; was open,
but a screen door was shut.  Officer Walls testified that he and another
officer &quot;identified ourselves as police officers and told them [the
occupants of petitioner's home] we had a search warrant and entered while
we were doing that.&quot;  J.A.41. 
</p>
<p>No testimony indicated that petitioner or anyone inside was given an
opportunity to admit the police into petitioner's home.  Moreover, no
testimony revealed that the police had any reason to believe when they
approached petitioner's home either that petitioner or anyone else in the
home might destroy evidence, or that the occupants of the home represented
a threat to the safety of the officers. 
</p>
<p>The search of the home disclosed, inter alia, evidence of drug possession
and a small caliber handgun.  J.A. 53.  The trial court denied
petitioner's motion to suppress the evidence due to the failure of the
officers to announce their presence and purpose before entering
petitioner's home.  J.A. 45.  On appeal, the Arkansas Supreme Court
concluded that &quot;[t]he testimony indicated that the officers entered the
home while they were identifying themselves.&quot;  J.A. 77.  There is no
indication from that court that exigent circumstances justified an
immediate police entrance into petitioner's home.  The court ruled that
the officers had followed Rule 13.3(e) of the Arkansas Rules of Criminal
Procedure, which does not require that officers announce their presence
and purpose in the execution of a search warrant.[2]
</p>
<p>On appeal, the Arkansas Supreme Court dismissed petitioner's claim that
the Constitution requires officers to announce their presence and purpose
before forcibly entering a home.  The court ruled:  &quot;There is no authority
for Ms. Wilson's theory that the knock and announce principle is required
by the Fourth Amendment.&quot;  J.A. 77. 
</p>
<p>In this Court, petitioner argues that the Fourth Amendment requires police
officers to announce their presence and purpose before they forcibly enter
a private home. 
</p>
<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>When assessing the reasonableness of a challenged police practice, this
Court often considers common law principles.  Under the common law, a
governmental officer was required to announce his authority and purpose
before breaking open the doors of a home.  The origins of the announcement
rule have been traced back to dicta from the seventeenth century. 
Semanye's Case, 77 Eng.Rep. 194, 1955 (K.B. 1603).  That dicta, however,
subsequently received the approval of many British and American legal
authorities.  Today, the announcement requirement stands as a fundamental
right that is an essential component of the privacy surrounding the home. 
</p>
<p>In concluding that the announcement requirement is not compelled by the
Fourth Amendment, the court below ignored this Court's many rulings which
have rejected the position that the Constitution has nothing to say about
how police officers execute an intrusion of a home.  While there was no
definitive opinion in Ker v. California, 374 U.S. 23 (1963), eight
Justices agreedthat police entries into a home must withstand scrutiny
under the Reasonableness Clause of the Fourth Amendment.  No Justice in
Ker supported the notion that officers are free from constitutional
restraints to force open doors whenever they possess a warrant or probable
cause to enter.  Rulings since Ker establish that police do not have
unchecked discretion to decide how to enter or invade a home. 
</p>
<p>Furthermore, under the Reasonableness Clause of the Fourth Amendment, the
Court has evaluated the manner in which a search and seizure is executed. 
Prior precedents, including Maryland v. Garrison, 480 U.S. 79 (1987);
Tennessee v. Garner, 471 U.S. 1 (1985); and Chimel v. California, 395 U.S.
752 (1969), establish that the manner in which a particular intrusion is
carried out -- even one authorized by a warrant or valid exception to the
warrant rule -- must satisfy the reasonableness test of the Fourth
Amendment.  No ruling of this Court supports the broad discretionary
powers sanctioned by the court below.  Indeed, in Camara v. Municipal
Court, 387 U.S. 523, 532 (1967) -- which involved an entry substantially
less intrusive than the entry of petitioner's home -- this Court
recognized that a homeowner has constitutional interests in being notified
of an official's presence and the lawful limits of that official's
authority to enter and search. 
</p>
<p>Finally, the announcement rule advances compelling privacy and security
interests of a homeowner.  Those who criticize the rule take a position
that is not consistent with the reasoning of this Court's cases. 
Likewise, those who malign the announcement rule are wrong when they
declare this safeguard only benefits the guilty.  This Court and the
United States Congress, among others, have rejected this judgment.  The
notification requirement is a protection the Fourth Amendment affords to
all persons. 
</p>
<p>2.  [see notes on footnotes in &quot;Summaries of Argument&quot;]
Ark.R.Crim.P. 13.3(e), in pertinent part, provides:
</p>
<p>The executing Officer, and other officers accompanying and
assisting him, may use such degree of force, short of deadly force, against
persons, or to effect entry or to open containers as is reasonably
necessary for the successful execution of the search warrant with all
practicable safety ....
</p>
</blockquote>
<center>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
