<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572"> </P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<H3>Current Press Releases</H3>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="voting"></A><A HREF="n020497a.html">2/4/97 -- Requiring Photo
Identification for Voters Called Unconstitutional in Michigan</A><BR>DETROIT --
The ACLU of Michigan has urged Governor John Engler to let stand a recent ruling
by the      state's attorney general that a plan to require voters to produce
photo identification would create an      unconstitutional barrier to the
people's access to the ballot. </P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n020397a.html">2/3/97 -- Indiana Lawsuit
Challenges Police Traffic Stops Based on Race</A><BR>INDIANAPOLIS -- Lawyers
from the Indiana Civil Liberties Union and from Johnson, Smith, Pence,     
Densborn Wright &amp; Heath have filed a lawsuit against the City of Carmel, the
Carmel Police Department      and an individual Carmel Police Officer
challenging the Citys policy and practice of conducting traffic stops     
without lawful cause. </P>
<P><A HREF="n013197a.html">1/31/97 -- Cleveland Homeless Lawsuit Scheduled for
Trial</A><BR>CLEVELAND -- A lawsuit brought by the ACLU of Ohio on behalf of
four Cleveland area homeless      individuals and the Northeast Ohio Coalition

for the Homeless will go to trial on February 18. </P>
<P><A HREF="n013097c.html">1/30/97 -- ACLU Warns that Christian Coalition's
New Agenda Has Same Old Constitutional Problems</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- Draped in
an aura of racial harmony and outreach, the Christian Coalition today presented
a new legislative agenda that is nothing more than a frontal assault on
constitutional rights and civil rights enforcement.</P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A NAME="voting"></A><A HREF="n013097b.html">1/30/97
-- Study Finds that Huge Numbers  Of African-American Men Are Barred From Voting</A><BR>WASHINGTON
-- Commenting on a new national study, the American Civil Liberties Union today
said that voting rights of African-American men have become yet another casualty
in the nation's long and misguided war on drugs.</P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n013097a.html">1/30/97 -- Georgia Courtroom
Gets Wired As Groups Present Evidence In First Challenge to State
Cyber-Censorship Law</A><BR>ATLANTA--In a courtroom hearing this morning on the
first-ever challenge to a state Internet censorship      statute, a witness will
conduct a live tour of the Internet for a federal district judge.</P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n012897a.html">1/28/97 -- Federal Appeals Court
Debates Alabama Law Barring Gay Student Groups from Campus</A><BR>ATLANTA -- In
a closely watched case about the rights of gay students, a federal appeals court
today heard a      challenge to an Alabama law seeking to keep lesbian, gay and
bisexual student groups off university campuses.</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n012897b.html">1/28/97 -- ACLU Sues McKeesport
Over Anti-Loitering Ordinance</A><BR>McKEESPORT, PA -- The American Civil
Liberties Union this morning filed a federal civil rights law suit against the
City of McKeesport and high ranking officials alleging that a municipal
ordinance forbidding &quot;loitering&quot; is unconstitutional.</P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n012397a.html">1/23/97 -- ACLU Victorious
In Cleveland Camcorder Case</A><BR>CLEVELAND -- Following numerous court
appeals and extended negotiations, the American Civil Liberties Union of Ohio
Foundation and the City of Cleveland have reached a settlement in an illegal
search and seizure case. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n012397b.html">1/23/97 -- Phoenix Bus
Advertising Policy Challenged:  Religious Organizations and ACLU Say the Policy
Violates First Amendment</A><BR>PHOENIX -- A federal lawsuit challenging the
constitutionality of the City's new policy that bans all non-commercial
advertising on city transit buses was filed late today in the U.S. District
Court in Phoenix. </P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n012297b.html">1/22/97 <I>Reno v. ACLU</I>
Update: Government's Brief Asserts Unprecedented Powers to Criminalize Online
Speech; Court Sets Oral Argument for March 19</A><BR>New York--After reviewing
the Justice Department's brief on the Communications Decency Act filed late
yesterday with the U.S. Supreme Court, the ACLU said that the government is
seeking unprecedented powers to criminalize speech on the Internet.</P>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n012297a.html">1/22/97 -- Catherine
Weiss Named Director of the ACLU's Reproductive Freedom Project</A><BR>NEW YORK
-- The American Civil Liberties Union today marked the 24th anniversary of <I>Roe
v. Wade</I> by naming Catherine Weiss as director of the ACLU's Reproductive
Freedom Project.  She will be responsible for overseeing the ACLU's legal,
advocacy, and public education work on reproductive rights.</P>
<P><A HREF="n011697a.html">1/16/97 --ACLU Decries Atlanta Bombings of Abortion
Clinic<BR>
</A>ATLANTA -- The American Civil Liberties Union is appalled by the two
bombings at the Atlanta Northside Family Planning Services this morning. Our
sympathies are with the people injured and with all the doctors and clinics that
have the courage to continue providing abortion services in this atmosphere of
unrelenting terror.</P>
<P><A HREF="n011597b.html">1/15/97 -- National Campaign on Affirmative Action?</A><BR>Statement
of Dorothy Ehrlich Executive Director, ACLU of Northern California<BR>SAN
FRANCISCO -- Despite Ward Connerly's repeated announcements that he is launching
a national campaign to bring Proposition 209 to other states, his campaign
remains stalled and his analysis deeply flawed. </P>
<P><A HREF="n011597a.html">1/15/97 -- Individual Rights Have 'Low Profile' At
Aviation Security Conference<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON &shy; The American Civil Liberties Union today criticized Vice
President Al Gore for continuing to virtually ignore the civil liberties
implications of airport security measures being discussed and proposed by his
special commission. </P>
<P><A HREF="n011497d.html">1/14/97 -- Doctors, Patients File Class Action Suit
To Block Federal Punishment for Medical Marijuana<BR>
</A>LOS ANGELES -- A group of physicians and patients today filed a class action
suit in federal court in San Francisco seeking an injunction blocking federal
officials from taking any punitive action against physicians who simply
recommend the medical use of marijuana to their patients. </P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n011497b.html">1/14/97 -- ACLU Urges
Supreme Court to Strike Down Georgia Law Requiring Urine Drug Tests for
Candidates <BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- In an important review of drug testing policies, the American
Civil Liberties Union today urged the Supreme Court to strike down a Georgia law
requiring candidates for statewide office to submit to, and pass, a urine drug
test before qualifying for nomination or election.</P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n011497a.html">1/14/97 -- ACLU, Library
Groups and Others Sue to Block New York State Internet Censorship Law<BR>
</A>New York---The American Civil Liberties Union, the New York Civil Liberties
Union, the American Library Association and others today filed a lawsuit seeking
an injunction against a New York statute criminalizing free speech in
cyberspace. </P>
<P><A HREF="n011497c.html">1/14/97 -- Court Upholds Religious Liberty, Rules
Against Jersey City Holiday Display<BR>
</A>NEWARK, NJ -- Addressing an issue that perennially polarizes the winter
holiday season, the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit
yesterday upheld a federal district court ruling that the city of Jersey City
violated the Establishment Clause of the federal constitution by displaying a
Menorah and Nativity Scene in front of the City Hall during Hanukkah and
Christmas. The court also reversed a later finding by the district court that
the addition of a plastic snowman, Santa Claus and a red sleigh had sufficiently
secularized the display to avoid Establishment Clause concerns.</P>
<P><A HREF="n011397a.html">1/13/97 -- 'Equal Justice For All' Means the
President is Not Above the Law<BR>
</A>NEW YORK -- In the case of Clinton v. Jones being argued today before the
Supreme Court, the ACLU has submitted a friend-of-the-court brief supporting the
right of Paula Corbin Jones to sue the President.</P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n011097a.html">1/10/97 -- D.C. Court of
Appeals To Hear Encryption Case<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- A three-judge panel in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia heard oral arguments today about whether or not
cryptography, or encoded electronic speech, is a legitimate form of speech
protected under the First Amendment from government access and control.</P>
<P><A HREF="n010997a.html">1/9/87 -- Legal Services Programs Challenge
Restrictions on Non-LSC Funds<BR>
</A>Honolulu, Hawaii -- In the first sweeping challenge of its kind, five legal
services programs from Hawaii, California and Alaska, which together serve over
a million low-income families and individuals, have asked a federal court to
prevent the Legal Services Corporation (LSC) from enforcing restrictions on the
use of funds given to the organizations by non-LSC sources, such as states,
municipalities, charitable foundations and private donors.</P>
<P><A NAME="death"></A><A HREF="n010897c.html">1/8/97 -- Arkansas Schedules
Triple Execution of Death Row Prisoners <BR>
</A>The United States is the only industrialized nation in the world to use the
death penalty: every other nation has realized that it has no place in a society
that cherishes justice, humanity, and the rule of law.</P>
<P><A HREF="n010897b.html">1/8/97 -- ACLU Says Terminally Ill Patient Act
Provides Guidelines for Aid-in-Dying<BR>
</A>SEATTLE, WASHINGTON -- The ACLU of Washington has drafted the Terminally Ill
Patient Act to revise the state's 140-year-old statute, which was declared
unconstitutional in 1994. The Terminally Ill Patient Act provides that a
terminally ill, mentally competent adult may obtain from his or her primary-care
physician a prescription for medication to shorten the process of dying in a
dignified and humane manner. The bill is endorsed by the Committee for the
Terminally Ill Patient Act, a group of prominent Washington citizens.</P>
<P><A HREF="n010897a.html">1/8/97 -- Supreme Court Should Heed Compassion and
the Constitution in Physician Aid-In-Dying Case, ACLU Says<BR>
</A>The case before the Court today touches on issues with profound significance
to a person's individual, familial, moral, spiritual and religious beliefs, and
is bound to affect the way we as a society deal with death and dying in the
years to come. </P>
<P><A HREF="n010797a.html">1/7/96 -- ACLU Welcomes 105th Congress; Warns of
Anti-Liberty Leftovers from 104th<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON As Congress returns to Washington for the beginning of its 105th
Session, the whirlwind surrounding Newt Gingrich's bid for re-election Speaker
of the House has taken center stage. But the American Civil Liberties Union,
deeply concerned about what will follow this initial burst of activity, warned
of continued attacks on civil liberties after the opening session flurry. </P>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n010397a.html">1/3/97 -- COURT
DISMISSES CRIMINAL CHARGES BROUGHT AGAINST WOMAN FOR HER CONDUCT DURING
PREGNANCY
<BR>
</A>NEWARK, NJ -- A trial court judge today dismissed criminal charges of
aggravated manslaughter and child endangerment brought against a woman who was
alleged to have used cocaine during her pregnancy and who gave birth prematurely
to a fetus that died shortly after birth. Judge Donald S. Goldman, of Essex
County Criminal Court, held that the legislature did not intend for activities
by a woman during pregnancy which may harm her fetus to constitute crimes under
New Jersey law. </P>
<P><A NAME="church"></A><A NAME="criminal"></A><A NAME="cyber"></A><A
NAME="death"></A><A NAME="free"></A><A NAME="aids"></A><A NAME="immigrants"></A><A
