<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  02/03/97 -- Indiana Lawsuit Challenges  Police

Traffic Stops Based on Race</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Indiana Lawsuit Challenges  Police Traffic Stops Based on Race</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Monday, February 3, 1997</B></P>
<P>INDIANAPOLIS -- Lawyers from the Indiana Civil Liberties Union and from
Johnson, Smith, Pence, Densborn Wright &amp; Heath have filed a lawsuit against
the City of Carmel, the Carmel Police Department and an individual Carmel Police
Officer challenging the Citys policy and practice of conducting traffic stops
without lawful cause. 
</P>
<P>The suit alleges that the stops are motivated by the race of the vehicles
drivers as well as other improper reasons. The lawsuit is brought on behalf of
an Indiana State Police Sergeant who suffered such  a stop, as well as the
Indianapolis Chapter of the NAACP which has had at least one member affected by
the policy. 
</P>
<P>The plaintiffs are filing the case as a class action seeking an injunction
against the policy.  Additionally, the State Police Department Sergeant is
seeking damages flowing from the unlawful stop.  The lawsuit will be filed in
the United States District Court for the Southern District of Indiana, located
in Indianapolis. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
