<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/31/97 -- Cleveland Homeless Lawsuit Scheduled
for Trial</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Cleveland Homeless Lawsuit Scheduled for Trial</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Friday, January 31, 1997</B></P>
<P>CLEVELAND -- A lawsuit brought by the ACLU of Ohio on behalf of four
Cleveland area homeless individuals and the Northeast Ohio Coalition for the
Homeless will go to trial on February 18. 
</P>
<P>The case, Clements v. City of Cleveland, involves the &quot;dumping&quot; of
homeless people by Cleveland police. It was assigned to U.S. District Court
Judge David Katz and will be tried in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>In the fall of 1992, the ACLU received an anonymous tip that Cleveland
police were routinely harassing, intimidating and, in some cases, removing area
homeless individuals against their will from downtown shopping districts and
dumping them in far-away, remote areas. 
</P>
<P>After extensive research and repeated allegations from area homeless
regarding the dumping by Cleveland police, the ACLU filed a lawsuit against the
City of Cleveland on behalf of four individuals and the coalition alleging that
the City was engaging in unconstitutional activities in an effort to &quot;sanitize&quot;
the downtown area.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
