<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/30/97 -- ACLU Warns that Christian Coalition's
New Agenda Has Same Old Constitutional Problems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Warns that Christian Coalition's New Agenda Has Same Old
Constitutional Problems</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, January 30, 1997</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- Draped in an aura of racial harmony and outreach, the
Christian Coalition today presented a new legislative agenda that is nothing
more than a frontal assault on constitutional rights and civil rights
enforcement.</P>
<P>The ACLU welcomed the Christian Coalition's participation in the national
dialogue on race in America, but cautioned that many of its proposals would
actually weaken society's ability to deal with these complicated issues.</P>
<P>For example, the Christian Coalition's eight-point agenda identifies
so-called &quot;Faith Solutions&quot; on drug treatment that would remove the &quot;obstacles&quot;
that keep religious organizations from receiving government funds.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The obstacle that Ralph Reed would so easily brush aside is nothing
less than the United States Constitution,&quot; said Laura W. Murphy, Director
of the ACLU's National Washington Office. &quot;It is this breezy dismissal of
our laws and traditions that is most worrisome about the Coalition's agenda.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Christian Coalition's plan calls for many such leaps over constitutional
?obstacles,&quot; Murphy said.  The so-called &quot;Hope and Opportunity
Scholarships,&quot; for example, are in reality a repackaged version of the
controversial school vouchers that would send government dollars to religious
institutions at the expense of public schools.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Rather than filling the inner cities with hope and opportunity,&quot;
Murphy said, &quot;the Christian Coalition voucher scheme would leave the vast
majority of public school children with no hope and no opportunity.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The ACLU also greeted with skepticism the Coalition's &quot;strong families&quot;
and &quot;safe neighborhoods&quot; proposals, saying that they too raise serious
concerns about individual rights and government's power to impose one religion's
viewpoint on all Americans.</P>
<P>In his presentation this morning, Reed saved for last the heart of the
Coalition's true agenda: a constitutional amendment to allow prayer in school,
continuing extremist attacks on women's  reproductive freedoms, and an attack on
other individual rights of self-determination such as physician-aid-in-dying.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Whether it's called a contract or a project or a laundry list , the
Christian Coalition's divisive agenda is always the same: anti-choice, anti-gay,
anti-religious freedom, and anti-civil liberties,&quot; the ACLU's Murphy said. &quot;There's
no question that the fabric of our society needs strengthening, but pulling
apart the Constitution is no answer.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1997, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
