<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/30/97 -- Study Finds that Huge Numbers  Of
African-American Men Are Barred From Voting</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Study Finds that Huge Numbers  Of African-American Men Are Barred From
Voting</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, January 30, 1997</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- Commenting on a new national study, the American Civil
Liberties Union today said that voting rights of African-American men have
become yet another casualty in the nation's long and misguided war on drugs.   
 </P>
<P>A report released today by the Sentencing Project found that one in seven
African American men is currently or permanently disenfranchised as a result of
a felony conviction.     </P>

<P>The study, &quot;Intended and Unintended Consequences: State Racial
Disparity in Imprisonment,&quot; found that 1.46 million black males of a total
voting age population of 10.4 million have lost the right to vote because of a
felony conviction.    </P>
<P>Many of those convictions, the report continued, can be attributed to policy
choices that have led to increased arrests for minor drug offenses and the
mandatory sentences for drug offenders in effect in 31 states.    </P>
<P>About 510,000 black males are permanently disenfranchised because of laws in
13 states, the Sentencing Project said. The remaining 950,000 are currently
ineligible to vote because of laws in 46 states regarding offenders in prison or
on probation or parole.    </P>
<P>Calling the new statistics &quot;disturbing,&quot; ACLU Legislative Counsel
Mark Kappelhoff said that they &quot;are not entirely unexpected in light of the
racial disparity found throughout the nation's criminal justice system where
black men are being stopped, arrested, convicted and sentenced in proportions
far higher than is right or fair in a democratic society.&quot;    </P>
<P>Kappelhoff said that laws mandating the loss of voting rights after a felony
conviction -- which were introduced in our country at the same time that
literacy tests and poll taxes were being used to disenfranchise blacks after the
Civil War -- cut to the very core of our democracy.    </P>
<P>&quot;Disproportionately excluding an entire segment of our society from
voting further polarizes our country along racial lines,&quot; Kappelhoff added,
&quot;and laws that target voting, one of the most fundamental features of our
participatory democracy, undercut everything for which this country stands.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1997, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
