<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/28/97 -- ACLU Sues McKeesport Over
Anti-Loitering Ordinance</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Sues McKeesport Over Anti-Loitering Ordinance</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Tuesday, January 28, 1997</B></P>
<P>McKEESPORT, PA -- The American Civil Liberties Union this morning filed a
federal civil rights law suit against the City of McKeesport and high ranking
officials alleging that a municipal ordinance forbidding &quot;loitering&quot;

is unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>The suit is filed on behalf of a McKeesport woman, Deborah Wilson, who has
been cited several times by McKeesport police for violating the law.  The relief
requested in the suit is a declaration that the law is unconstitutional, a
preliminary and permanent injunction, and damages. 
</P>
<P>Chuck Van Keuren, the volunteer ACLU lawyer handling the case, said that the
U.S. Supreme Court has held similar laws unconstitutional as far back as the
1960's. &quot;Anti-loitering ordinances are nice for the police because they can
be used to arrest anyone the police don't like, regardless of whether a crime
has been committed,&quot; Van Keuren said. &quot;But for this reason the law is
patently unconstitutional.&quot; 
</P>
<P>ACLU Pittsburgh Director Vic Walczak, who is co-counsel on the case, said
that he expects the suit to have an impact beyond just McKeesport. 
</P>
<P>&quot;This is the fourth anti-loitering ordinance that the ACLU has
challenged in the past 18 months,&quot; Walczak said. &quot;Small towns across
the state need to know that from now on there will be a price to pay for
continued enforcement of these vague anti-loitering laws.&quot;  
</P>
<P>Within the past year and a half, the ACLU has been successful in convincing
officials in Export, Wilmerding and Seward Boro to repeal similar anti-loitering
ordinances. 
</P>
<P>The law at issue makes it a crime for someone in McKeesport to loiter or
loaf or walk about aimlessly in a public area. The police are empowered to
arrest loiterers who, among other things, &quot;annoy&quot; another person or &quot;make
unsolicited remarks of an offensive, disgusting or insulting nature&quot; to

someone else. 
</P>
<P>Under well established case law, &quot;loitering&quot; is a constitutionally
protected activity. In  Papachristou v. City of Jacksonville in 1972 the Court
held Jacksonville, Florida's law criminalizing loitering &quot;plainly
unconstitutional.&quot; 
</P>
<P>The real danger of laws, such as those prohibiting loitering, is that they
are vague.  Vague laws are dangerous and unconstitutional for three primary
reasons: 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(1) They do not give people a reasonable opportunity to know what is
prohibited, so that they may act accordingly; 
</P>
<P>(2) They delegate too much discretion to policemen, judges and juries to
decide, in an ad hoc and subjective manner, what is permitted and what isn't,
which usually results in arbitrary and discriminatory enforcement of the law;
and 
</P>
<P>(3) They inhibit people from fully exercising their constitutional rights of
assembly and travel for fear of prosecution. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In the decision holding an anti-loitering law unconstitutional, the Supreme
Court articulated the dangers of such vague loitering laws: 
</P>
<P>&quot;It would certainly be dangerous if the legislature could set a net
large enough to catch all possible offenders, and leave it to the court to step
inside and say who could be rightfully detained and who should be set at large.
Here the net is cast large, not to give the courts power to pick and choose but
to increase the arsenal of the police. 
</P>
<P>The result, the Court said, &quot;is to enable men to be caught who are
vaguely undesirable in the eyes of the police and prosecution, although not
chargeable with any offense. Those convicted may be punished for no more than
vindicating affronts to police authority.&quot; 
</P>
<P>The Court noted that experience and common sense teach that such
discretionary authority is used by the police against poor people,
nonconformists, dissenters and minorities. 
</P>
<P>&quot;Where, as here, there are no standards governing the exercise of
discretion granted by the ordinance, the scheme permits and encourages an
arbitrary and discriminatory enforcement of the law,&quot; the Justices wrote. &quot;It
furnishes a convenient tool for `harsh and discriminatory enforcement by local
officials, against particular groups deemed to merit their displeasure.'  It
results in a regime in which the poor and the unpopular are permitted to 'stand
on a public sidewalk  . . . only at the whim of any police officer.'&quot; 
</P>
<P>The ACLU said it will give McKeesport officials a reasonable time to agree
to repeal the anti-loitering law.  If no agreement is reached, Van Keuren stated
that the ACLU would file a motion for a preliminary injunction.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
