<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/23/97 -- ACLU Victorious In Cleveland Camcorder
Case</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Victorious In Cleveland Camcorder Case</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, January 23, 1997</B></P>
<P>
 CLEVELAND -- Following numerous court appeals and extended negotiations, the
American Civil Liberties Union of Ohio Foundation and the City of Cleveland have
reached a settlement in an illegal search and seizure case. 
</P>

<P>The case -- Rice v. City of Cleveland -- began not long after the Rodney
King incident when an African-American couple, Jesse and Bricelia Rice, used
their camcorder to photograph police during the arrest of a neighborhood youth.

</P>
<P>The officers, threatening to arrest Mr. Rice if he did not surrender the
tape, eventually confiscated it without a court order. On March 22, 1995,
Federal District Court Judge Kathleen O'Malley granted the ACLU's summary
judgment motion on Fourth Amendment claims arising from the warrantless seizure
of the videotape. 
</P>
<P>The defendant police officers appealed to the Sixth Circuit Court of
Appeals, which heard oral arguments on December 4, 1995. The Court of Appeals
confirmed that the confiscation of the videotape violated the Rice's rights
under the Fourth Amendment. 
</P>
<P>&quot;We believe the City now understands that it cannot seize property from
law-abiding citizens without a warrant that meets the requirements of the U.S.
Constitution,&quot; said ACLU Cooperating Attorney Steve Shafron, who, along
with J. Michael Murray, represented the Rices. 
</P>
<P>&quot;We expect that the Cleveland police will think twice before they
attempt to infringe on the Fourth Amendment rights of Cleveland citizens in the
future,&quot; Shafron concluded. 
</P>
<P>The settlement included a payment of damages to the plaintiffs and legal
fees to the ACLU.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
