<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/23/97 -- Phoenix Bus Advertising Policy
Challenged</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Phoenix Bus Advertising Policy Challenged</H2>
<H4>Religious Organizations and ACLU Say the Policy Violates First Amendment</H4></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, January 23, 1997</B></P>
<P>PHOENIX -- A federal lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of the City&#146;s
new policy that bans all non-commercial advertising on city transit buses was
filed late today in the U.S. District Court in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>Children of the Rosary (COR), its president Katherine Sabelko and the
Arizona Civil Liberties Union(AzCLU) filed suit jointly after their requests to
place advertisements were denied because they did not meet with the City&#146;s &quot;Advertising
Standards.&quot;  
</P>
<P>The new policy enacted November 1, 1996 states, &quot;the subject matter of
bus advertising shall be limited to speech which proposes a commercial
transaction.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Both AzCLU and COR attempted to place advertisements on the exterior of City
transit buses and had them rejected. The plaintiffs subsequently filed suit
seeking a permanent injunction against the policy arguing that the policy
violates their First Amendment rights. 
</P>
<P>&quot;The policy clearly violates the First Amendment because once the City
opens this forum for expression it cannot restrict otherwise protected speech on
the basis of its content or viewpoint,&quot; said ACLJ Attorney Benjamin W. Bull
who is representing COR and Sabelko. 
</P>
<P>The City&#146;s new policy was passed after their initial guidelines were
declared unconstitutional. In a 1995 lawsuit, COR and Sabelko succeeded in
having the policy which banned &quot;religious&quot; messages held
unconstitutional. Children of the Rosary then ran advertisements on two buses
until the city passed a new policy at which time the ads were rejected. 
</P>
<P>&quot;Such a policy is clearly designed to prohibit unpopular speech and to
get around the court&#146;s earlier ruling,&quot; said Katrina Nylund, Interim
Director of the Arizona Civil Liberties Union. &quot;If the City is going to
permit advertising, they have to allow everyone to advertise; they cannot pick
and choose their clients. That&#146;s called censorship and is a violation of
one of our most cherished ideals -- free speech.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Children of the Rosary and Katherine Sabelko are represented by attorney
Benjamin W. Bull of the American Center for Law and Justice, a public interest
law firm specializing in religious free speech issues. COR is a pro-life
religious organization that promotes peaceful expression in opposition to
abortion.  
</P>
<P>The Arizona Civil Liberties Union is a non-profit organization dedicated to
defending constitutional rights guaranteed in the Bill of Rights. The AzCLU is
represented by Phoenix attorney Nicholas Hentoff. This is the first case in any
court in which the ACLJ and the ACLU have joined together in a civil rights
lawsuit. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
