<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/15/97 -- National Campaign on Affirmative
Action?</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>National Campaign on Affirmative Action?</H2>
<H3>Statement of Dorothy Ehrlich Executive Director, ACLU of Northern
California</H3></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Wednesday, January 15, 1997</B></P>
<P>SAN FRANCISCO -- Despite Ward Connerly&#146;s repeated announcements that he
is launching a national campaign to bring Proposition 209 to other states, his
campaign remains stalled and his analysis deeply flawed. 
</P>
<P>Proposition 209 failed to deliver what his backers aimed to deliver -- the
wedge issue that would muster Republican support and undermine a Democratic
victory in November, 1996.  More important than its lack of political potency, 
Prop. 209 has not yet been implemented because an initial review before the
federal courts has found that it is unconstitutional.  The Department of Justice
also believes it conflicts with federal civil rights laws. 
</P>

<P>Prop. 209-styled legislation was introduced in nearly a dozen state
legislatures during the past two years, or circulated as a ballot proposition,
but except for California, succeeded in no jurisdiction -- including Congress. 
In fact, Prop. 209 was defeated by the California legislature for two
consecutive years, and would not have made it to the ballot, but for a last
minute influx of funds from the national Republican Party to pay for the
signature drive.  In fact 80% of the signatures had to be supplied by paid
signature gatherers in the final days of the failing campaign. 
</P>
<P>A Republican bailout also enabled the measure to pass by a slim 8 percent
margin, only after high-dollar, out-of-state right-wingers agreed to pump
millions of dollars of advertising into the measure as a way to boost the
sagging campaign of Presidential hopeful Bob Dole, and to rescue vulnerable
Republican seats with this divisive wedge issue. 
</P>
<P>It may be a very cynical strategy, but it is surely not a winning one.  The
effort to take away the government&#146;s ability to ensure equality for women
and minorities, and to try to mask that strategy as a civil rights measure has
largely been a recipe for defeat, in every other part of the country.  The ACLU
and our coalition partners will pursue our federal class action suit on behalf
of equal opportunity and will also continue our efforts to prevent further
legislative proposals which threaten civil rights on the state and national
level.  
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
