<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/15/97 -- Individual Rights Have 'Low Profile'
At Aviation Security Conference</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Individual Rights Have 'Low Profile' At Aviation Security Conference</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Wednesday, January 15, 1997</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON &#150; The American Civil Liberties Union today criticized Vice
President Al Gore for continuing to virtually ignore the civil liberties
implications of airport security measures being discussed and proposed by his
special commission. 
</P>
<P>Out of over 130 panelists on aviation safety and security that were invited
from around the world to address the just-ending &quot;International Conference
on Aviation Safety and Security in the 21st Century,&quot; only one
<A HREF="/congress/t011497a.html">civil liberties expert addressed the privacy
concerns raised by the proposals</A>. The conference was co-sponsored by George
Washington University and the White House Commission on Aviation Safety and
Security (&quot;Gore Commission&quot;). 
</P>
<P>&quot;Legitimate and widespread concerns about the implications for our
civil liberties have been sidelined at this conference,&quot; said Gregory T.
Nojeim, a Legislative Counsel for the ACLU's national Washington Office who
testified on Tuesday at a panel on profiling that was closed to the public and
the media. 
</P>
<P>The ACLU said the pattern will continue on Friday when the Gore Commission
has scheduled a three-hour meeting of a &quot;civil liberties advisory panel.&quot;
 Though formation of the panel was announced four months ago following
widespread criticism of the Gore Commission's intrusive preliminary
recommendations, invitations to members were extended only last week. 
</P>
<P>The panel is to meet once, outside of public view, for only three hours. It
will have no staff, conduct no study, hold no hearings, produce no report, and
have no access to the information on which the Gore Commission has based its
recommendations so far. (The ACLU will participate.) 
</P>
<P>In his testimony before the conference, Nojeim questioned the Commission's
proposal to institute computerized profiling. 
</P>
<P>&quot;Profiling,&quot; Nojeim said, &quot;proved ineffective in stopping
hijacking in the 1970s and will do nothing to curb bombing of airplanes now. 
</P>
<P>&quot;If profiling is implemented, only those passengers who &quot;fit the
profile&quot; would be given extra attention, leaving the remaining passengers
relatively unchecked,&quot; Nojeim said. &quot;Passengers who 'fit a profile'
could easily employ the services of a fellow passenger who does not to plant a
bomb.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Nojeim also told the conference that profiles can be discriminatory. &quot;They
are nothing more than stereotypes of a terrorist, and they often have
discriminatory effects, based on race, religion or national origin,&quot; he
said. 
</P>
<P>In order to determine whether passengers should be subjected to heightened
security measures, airlines would be required to maintain data bases with
personal information about all travelers. The Gore Commission has even
preliminarily recommended using criminal history data bases, including records
of arrests that do not result in convictions, to supplement personal travel
information that airlines can collect on their own. 
</P>
<P>&quot;The government has no business forcing airlines to track a passenger's
travel and other personal information to fit someone's notion of what a
terrorist looks like,&quot; Nojeim said, &quot;let alone asking them to
incorporate incomplete and often inaccurate criminal data supplied by law
enforcement agencies.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Passengers who fit the profile of a terrorist could also be subject to
examination by intrusive imaging devices, already being developed by private
companies, that would project a naked image of the passenger's body in the
search for explosives and other contraband. Many of these images are
frighteningly detailed, showing genitalia and one's navel, underneath the
clothing. 
</P>
<P>&quot;The privacy rights and other liberty interests of passengers deserve
far more attention than the Gore Commission is giving them,&quot; said Nojeim. &quot;The
Commission seems to be taking a &#145;head in the sand' approach to the civil
liberties implications of aviation security measures.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
