<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/14/97 -- ACLU Urges Supreme Court to Strike
Down Georgia Law Requiring Urine Drug Tests for Candidates</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Urges Supreme Court to Strike Down Georgia Law Requiring Urine Drug
Tests for Candidates</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Tuesday, January 14, 1997</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- In an important review of drug testing policies, the American
Civil Liberties Union today urged the Supreme Court to strike down a Georgia law
requiring candidates for statewide office to submit to, and pass, a urine drug
test before qualifying for nomination or election.</P>
<P>The ACLU, which filed a <A HREF="/court/chandler.html">friend-of-the-court
brief</A> in the case, said the invasive drug tests violate the Fourth
Amendment's protection against suspicionless searches.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;This law demonstrates how our constitutional rights are being
sacrificed in pursuit of the so-called 'war on drugs',&quot; said Steven R. 
Shapiro, the ACLU's national legal director.  &quot;The Supreme Court has
repeatedly emphasized that suspicionless drug testing passes constitutional
muster only where it is aimed at specific or immediate threats.  No such threat
exists here.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The ACLU also argued that the drug tests are an invasion of privacy and
intrude upon a candidate's bodily integrity.  </P>
<P>The case heard today was brought by three political candidates in Georgia
who challenged a 1990 law requiring them to produce a urine specimen at a
state-certified laboratory in order to test for marijuana and other Schedule I
or II controlled substances such as cocaine, opiates, amphetamines and
phencyclidines.</P>
<P>The law covers many of the state's highest offices, including the Governor,
Lieutenant Governor, Secretary of State, Attorney General, State School
Superintendent, Justices of the Supreme Court, appellate and lower court judges,
and members of the General Assembly.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Although I passed my test, refusal to undergo suspicion-free tests
must be upheld as a valuable civil liberty,&quot; said Walker Chandler, a
plaintiff in the case who unsuccessfully ran for Lieutenant Governor in 1992 as
a Libertarian.  &quot;The Supreme Court cannot allow the war on drugs to take
our civil liberties hostage.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>In his own words:  Walker Chandler</H2>
<P><B><I>Walker Chandler is the plaintiff in the U.S. Supreme Court case
Chandler v. Miller, which will be heard on January 14, 1997.  The case
challenges the constitutionality of Georgia's law requiring drug testing of
candidates.</I></B></P>
<P>This week the Supreme Court will hear arguments in the <I>Chandler v.
Miller Case</I>, a constitutional challenge to Georgia's unique law which
mandates one-time drug testing of candidates for political office.  This case
has serious ramifications not only for political candidates, but for society as
a whole.</P>
<P>I am Walker Chandler, the plaintiff in the Supreme Court case against
Governor Miller and the State of Georgia.  I will be representing myself and a
fellow candidate, who ran for state office, before the Supreme Court.   When I
ran for Lieutenant Governor of Georgia as a libertarian in 1992, I was forced by
Georgia law to take a drug test to become a candidate.  Although I passed the
test, I contend that this is a serious infringement on our Fourth Amendment
protection against unreasonable search and seizure.  The law is a direct assault
on all Americans' constitutional rights and personal liberty, which this country
claims to hold in highest esteem and protect at all cost. </P>
<P>At first glance, particularly to those who are already subjected to
workplace drug testing, the matter, being one of simple equity, might not appear
to offer much cause for concern.  After all, if other groups of employees must
submit to pre-employment tests, then why not politicians?  However, the current
and - perhaps more importantly - potential implications of this law make the
issue anything but mundane.</P>
<P>The major battlefield of the war for individual liberty is not in the court
systems of the nation.  The struggle for human dignity must be carried on each
and every day in both the political and personal arenas.  But even if we choose
to set aside this inherent infringement on personal liberty and the democratic
process because this law may not seem so unreasonable, pressing issues remain. 
Even if we choose to ignore the fundamentally flawed nature of any type of
suspicion-free drug testing policy, we cannot ignore the Pandora's box the
statute opens.</P>
<P>A law is not a self-contained entity, but rather part of the legal fabric on
which future laws and judicial decisions are based.  The Georgia law, if not

struck down, would set a dangerous precedent of infringement on personal
liberty.  By extending the purview of suspicion-free drug testing, the
floodgates are opened wide to testing in anyone's place of business.  Currently,
workers are being force to take tests in private businesses, many government
agencies, and now, the House of Representatives will conduct mandatory testing
of its employees.   </P>
<P>Who can guarantee that this suspicion-free testing won't extend beyond
politics and into our very homes?  If we are to make government the Good
Shepherd controlling its flock of sheep, why not administer drug tests to
couples who want to have a child, people who are trying to buy property, or even
voters, since voters hold perhaps the most important civic responsibility in any
democracy.</P>
<P>Those of you who decry this line of thinking as some sort of Orwellian
paranoia have to understand the deeper impact of the drug testing law for our
future.  This kind of blatant constitutional infringement could be modified and
extended to suit the issues of the day, further threatening our civil liberties.
 We do not know what the cultural norms of future generations will be.  To
validate a law that contains within its construction seeds for such logical
possible extensions as the outrageous tests mentioned above is irresponsible and
short-sighted.</P>
<P>We may ask how such a law could be passed, one that makes a mockery of our
country's credo of &quot;innocent until proven guilty.&quot;  A brief look at
today's political climate is all we need to find the source of such a flawed
statute.  Considering the mounting pressure resulting from this nation's
stagnating war on drugs, we should not be surprised how this faulty bill could
be passed.  Legislators have attempted to vent their frustrations by infringing
upon the electoral arena through whimsical policy.  This, perhaps, may be the
most dangerous implication of all.  Everyone who runs for office must agree with
the majority-elect over certain policy issues.</P>
<P>However great the problem of drugs may be in this country, this does not
give policy-makers free license to pass such a constitutionally flawed law. 
Regardless of our personal opinion of the crusade against drugs, we should not,
as a society, mandate symbolic allegiance to the drug war.  Refusal to undergo a
suspicion-free test must be upheld as a valuable civil liberty.  The Supreme
Court cannot allow the war on drugs to take our civil liberties hostage.  </P>
<P><B><I>Walker Chandler of Zebulon, Georgia, who objected to the drug
testing requirement when he ran for Lieutenant Governor in 1994, will be
representing himself and a fellow candidate who ran for statewide office. 
Chandler contends that Georgia's drug testing political candidates law is
unconstitutional under the Fourth Amendment.</I></B></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
