<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/13/97 -- 'Equal Justice For All' Means the
President is Not Above the Law </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>'Equal Justice For All' Means the President is Not Above the Law </H2>
<H3>Statement of Steven R. Shapiro, ACLU National Legal Director</H3></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Monday, January 13, 1997</B></P>
<P>NEW YORK -- In the case of <I>Clinton v. Jones</I> being argued today
before the Supreme Court, the ACLU has submitted a <A HREF="/court/jones.html">friend-of-the-court
brief</A> supporting the right of Paula Corbin Jones to sue the President.</P>
<P>The ACLU has taken this position because we believe that no person should be
above the law and that every person, including the President, should be
accountable for his or her behavior.</P>
<P>The last time the Supreme Court confronted the question of presidential
immunity was in <I>Nixon v. Fitzgerald</I>.  The Court held in that case that
President Nixon could not be sued for his official conduct while in office
because of its concern that the threat of litigation might discourage presidents
from making hard decisions.</P>
<P>This case arises under very different circumstances.  Most importantly, it
does not involve the official duties of the President.  To the contrary, the
lawsuit is based on conduct that allegedly occurred while Mr. Clinton was still
Governor of Arkansas.</P>
<P>In seeking to have the lawsuit deferred until he leaves office, the
President's lawyers have stressed the burden on the President's time.  However,
as the lower court pointed out in rejecting that argument, the actual burden on
the President's time is likely to be minimal.  Furthermore, it is reasonable to
assume that the trial court will, and should, do everything possible to
accommodate the President's schedule.</P>
<P>On the other hand, a rule automatically delaying all litigation until the
President leaves office has real costs.  At the most practical level, memories
fade and evidence becomes stale.  The prospect of success on even meritorious
claims therefore declines with each passing year.  At a symbolic level, the rule
that President Clinton is seeking necessarily implies that a  president sued for
nonpresidential conduct is subject to a different set of legal rules than every
other citizen.  That is not the principle on which this country was founded.
</P>
<P>The President has also argued that a decision permitting Ms. Jones to go
forward with her suit will lead to an avalanche of politically motivated suits
against future presidents.  History does not support that contention.  Moreover,
the legal system already imposes severe sanctions against litigants who file
frivolous lawsuits.</P>
<P>The ACLU takes no position on the merits of Ms. Jones' charges, nor will
this Supreme Court case resolve them.  The only issue before the Supreme Court
is whether Ms. Jones is entitled to pursue her charges.  No court has ever
recognized the broad immunity that President Clinton now seeks.  The Supreme
Court should decline President Clinton's invitation to do so now.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
