<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/09/97 -- LEGAL SERVICES PROGRAMS CHALLENGE
RESTRICTIONS ON NON-LSC FUNDS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>LEGAL SERVICES PROGRAMS CHALLENGE RESTRICTIONS ON NON-LSC FUNDS</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, January 9, 1997 </B> </P>
<P><A HREF="#materials">Case materials</A></P>
<P>Honolulu, Hawaii -- In the first sweeping challenge of its kind, five legal
services programs from Hawaii, California and Alaska, which together serve over

a million low-income families and individuals, have asked a federal court to
prevent the Legal Services Corporation (LSC) from enforcing restrictions on the
use of funds given to the organizations by non-LSC sources, such as states,
municipalities, charitable foundations and private donors.  Those restrictions,
which were imposed by Congress as part of the 1996 and 1997 appropriations, are
challenged as unconstitutional in the suit, <I>Legal Aid Society of Hawaii, et
al. vs. Legal Services Corporation</I>, filed today in United States District
Court in Hawaii.  The suit contends that the restrictions impose an &quot;unconstitutional
condition&quot; upon the First Amendment rights of legal services programs as
well as their clients, lawyers and donors.</P>
<P>The five legal services programs each receive a portion of their funding
from the LSC, a private non-profit corporation that receives annual
appropriations from Congress to fund legal services to low-income people across
the nation.  The programs receive a significant portion of their funds from
non-LSC sources.</P>
<P>Under the new restrictions, legal services organizations that obtain any
portion of their financial support from the LSC are prohibited from using funds
received from any other source for certain purposes, including pursuing
legislative advocacy, filing class action lawsuits, challenging federal or state
welfare laws, or seeking attorneys fees in cases where such fees are authorized
by statute.  In addition, the restrictions prohibit the programs from
representing certain clients, including prisoners and large numbers of aliens. 
These restrictions serve to severely limit access to critical legal assistance
for low-income people.</P>
<P>According to the suit, there is a long-established rule against the
government granting a benefit predicated on the condition that the recipients
relinquish their constitutional rights.  The restrictions on the use of non-LSC
funds to engage in constitutionally-protected advocacy represents such an &quot;unconstitutional
condition.&quot;</P>
<P>In seeking a preliminary injunction, the plaintiffs assert that the
restrictions violate their First Amendment rights of speech and association.</P>
<P>In addition, according to the plaintiffs' brief, &quot;the challenged
restrictions specifically interfere with the rights of indigent clients to
retain counsel of their choice and prevent clients and lawyers from engaging in
meaningful advocacy.&quot;</P>
<P>Stephen V. Bomse, lead counsel for the plaintiffs in the Hawaii suit, said, &quot;Attempting
to limit the use of non-LSC funds for constitutionally-protected purposes
interferes with the rights of local governments and private donors to decide
what programs and activities deserve their support.&quot;</P>
<P>Mr. Bomse added, &quot;That is particularly unfortunate at a time when the
number of poor people in need of legal assistance is growing because of cutbacks
in services and changes in regulations affecting the legal rights and
entitlements of the poor.&quot;</P>
<P>Victor Geminiani, executive director of the Legal Aid Society of Hawaii,
emphasized that the programs are not challenging the federal government's right
to decide how its own allocations are spent.  At issue, says Mr. Geminiani, is
the right of local governments and private citizens to determine their
priorities.  At present, the Legal Aid Society of Hawaii receives approximately
35% of its total revenues from the state of Hawaii, 30% from private sources,
28% from LSC, and 7% from other federal programs designed to assist the elderly.</P>
<P>In 1995, the five legal services programs filing the suit handled more than
70,000 cases, serving a combined client population of more than one million
people who live at or below the poverty level.</P>
<P>The plaintiffs in the suit are: Legal Aid Society of Hawaii, Legal Services
of Northern California, Inc., San Fernando Valley Neighborhood Legal Services,
Legal Aid Society of Orange County, and Alaska Legal Services Corporation.  Also
named as plaintiffs are:  California State Client Council, which represents
legal services clients; The Hawaii Justice Foundation and The Impact Fund, which
donate funds to legal services programs; and Lloyd Van De Car and Gary Smith,
two legal services program lawyers whose practices have been affected by the new
restrictions.</P>
<P>Representing the plaintiffs pro bono are the following:  Stephen V. Bomse,
Charles N. Freiberg. Adam M. Cole, Hope L. Hudson and Rakesh K. Anand of Heller
Ehrman White &amp; McAuliffe (San Francisco, California); Steven R. Shapiro and
Robin L. Dahlberg of the American Civil Liberties Union (New York); Margaret C.
Crosby of ACLU of Northern California (San Francisco, California); Paul Alston
and Bradford L. Tannen of Alston, Hunt, Floyd &amp; Ing (Honolulu, Hawaii); and
Stanley Levin of Davis, Levin, Livingston, Grande (Honolulu, Hawaii).</P>
<P><A NAME="materials"></A><A HREF="/court/lsccomplaint.html">Complaint</A></P>
<P><A HREF="/court/lscmemolaw.html">Memorandum of Law</A></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">PLAINTIFF ORGANIZATIONS</P>
<DL>
<DT><B>Legal Aid Society of Hawaii</B></DT>
<DD>Primary location:  Honolulu<BR>Number of offices:  9<BR>Population
served:  125,000<BR>Cases handled in 1995:  10,000</DD>
<DT><B>Legal Services of Northern California, Inc.</B></DT>
<DD>Primary location:  Sacramento<BR>Number of offices:  6<BR>Population
served:  270,000<BR>Cases handled in 1995:  33,000</DD>
<DT><B>San Fernando Valley Neighborhood Legal Services</B></DT>
<DD>Primary location: Pacoima<BR>Number of offices:  1<BR>Population served: 
250,000<BR>Cases handled in 1995:  9,300</DD>
<DT><B>Legal Aid Society of Orange County</B></DT>
<DD>Primary location:  Santa Ana<BR>Number of offices:  4<BR>Population
served:  500,000<BR>Cases handled in 1995:  13,000</DD>
<DT><B>Alaska Legal Services Corporation</B></DT>
<DD>Primary location:  Anchorage<BR>Number of offices:  6<BR>Population
served:  66,000<BR>Cases handled in 1995:  5,000</DD></DL>
<HR>
<P>EXAMPLES OF LEGAL SERVICES PROVIDED BY PLAINTIFFS</P>
<UL>
<LI>Provide representation in domestic violence cases for undocumented aliens</LI>
<LI>Protect the rights of Native Alaskans to engage in subsistence hunting and
fishing</LI>
<LI>Help to ensure fairness in eviction procedures in public and subsidized
housing</LI>
<LI>Compel public housing authorities to repair poorly constructed homes</LI>
<LI>Fight discrimination against non-English-speaking Alaska Natives, African
Americans, and Southeast Asian immigrants</LI>
<LI>Aid frail elderly in Medicare cases</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
