<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/08/97 -- Arkansas Schedules Triple Execution of

Death Row Prisoners </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Arkansas Schedules Triple Execution of Death Row Prisoners </H2>
<H3>Statement of Rita Spillenger, Executive Director, ACLU of Arkansas</H3></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Wednesday, January 8, 1997</B></P>
<P>The United States is the only industrialized nation in the world to use the
death penalty: every other nation has realized that it has no place in a society
that cherishes justice, humanity, and the rule of law.</P>
<P>The fact that we have become so nonchalant as to commit a triple execution
because it is &quot;more efficient, less costly and causes less stress for the
executioners&quot; should make us weep with shame.</P>
<P>If we want to end violence in our country, we must ask why we are, all of
us, so enured to violence.  For the death penalty is nothing less than an act of
violence committed by the state against its citizens.</P>
<P>The question of whether to use the death penalty has nothing to do with
admittedly compelling issues like the feelings of the victims' families, or the
heinousness of the crimes.  The question is simply whether or not the state
should be in the business of vengeance, whether the people want to endorse an
act of cold-blooded murder.</P>
<P>There is also the constitutional question of due process.  First of all,
there is no doubt that the people executed, who are usually destitute, often get
shamefully inadequate legal representation.</P>
<P>Second, the death penalty is usually applied, as with most penalties, in a
rather arbitrary fashion, in large part depending on the feelings of the jury in
that particular town about that particular defendant and victim.  There is
bountiful evidence that both juries and prosecutors consider factors like race
and gender of both the defendant and the victim in deciding whether to seek or
apply the death penalty.  This kind of arbitrariness, unavoidable in most cases,
is unconscionable when applied to a penalty as serious as death.</P>
<P>Third, there is always the possibility that new evidence exonerating the
offender will be discovered: the death penalty leaves no room for exoneration.</P>
<P>I am often asked whether or not the death penalty constitutes &quot;cruel
and unusual punishment.&quot;  If waiting for the appointed hour when you will
be taken into a room and killed isn't torture, what is?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>

<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
