<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/08/97 -- Supreme Court Should Heed Compassion
and the Constitution in Physician Aid-In-Dying Case, ACLU Says</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Supreme Court Should Heed Compassion and the Constitution in Physician
Aid-In-Dying Case, ACLU Says</H2>
<H3>Statement of Steven R. Shapiro, Legal Director, ACLU </H3></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Wednesday, January 8, 1997</B></P>
<P>The case before the Court today touches on issues with profound significance
to a person's individual, familial, moral, spiritual and religious beliefs, and
is bound to affect the way we as a society deal with death and dying in the
years to come.  </P>
<P>The Court has agreed to review the question, in the consolidated cases of
<I>Vacco v. Quill</I> and<I> Washington v. Glucksberg</I>, of whether states
may prohibit doctors from prescribing life-ending drugs for mentally competent
but terminally ill patients who no longer want to live. </P>
<P>The answer to that question, from a constitutional and compassionate point
of view, can only be &quot;No.&quot; </P>
<P>In our <A HREF="/court/quill.html">friend-of-the-court brief</A> submitted
on behalf of the national ACLU, the ACLU of Washington State  and 11 other
organizations, we argue that the right of patients to choose physician-assisted
hastening of death is well-grounded in constitutional doctrine and Court
precedents. </P>
<P>The basis of those rights can be found in the liberty interest of the Due
Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, which says that no State shall &quot;deprive
any person of life, liberty, or property, without due process of law&quot; and
in the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment which specifies that
&quot;all persons similarly circumstanced shall be treated alike.&quot;   </P>
<P>As articulated in our brief, the decision of a dying person to escape
unendurable suffering with the aid of a doctor is too intimate, too personal,
and too central to the totality and meaning of a person's life for the State to
impose its own philosophical and moral imperatives upon that decision.  </P>
<P>Indeed, as the Court ruled in <I>Planned Parenthood v. Casey</I>,
concerning Pennsylvania citizens' legal access to abortion, &quot;It is settled
now...that the Constitution places limits on a State's right to interfere with a
person's most basic decision about family and parenthood, as well as bodily
integrity.&quot;  </P>
<P>That enduring principle of liberty interest has found expression in numerous
cases over the years involving decisions that go to the very heart of what it
means to be an autonomous individual -- decisions relating to marriage, family
relationships, conception, procreation, child reading, education, and the
refusal or termination of life-saving medical treatment.  </P>

<P>The constitutional right to equal protection is also at issue here.  As
argued in their briefs before the Court, both Washington and New York State have
asserted an interest in preserving human life and precluding undue influence or
mistake in hastening death.  But these concerns, however legitimate, do not
justify an absolute ban on physician aid-in-dying for terminally ill
individuals. </P>
<P>In fact, Washington, New York, and most other states have recognized the
right of a competent, terminally ill patient to choose to end a dehumanizing
process of dying with the aid of a physician. But these and most other states
limit this right only to those dependent on life-support or receiving artificial
nutrition or hydration.  Other terminally ill patients, also facing imminent
death but not undergoing such treatments, are not granted this right.  </P>
<P>As asserted in our brief, allowing one category of terminally ill patient,
but not another, to end his or her life with the aid of a physician violates the
Constitution's Equal Protection Clause.   This distinction between &quot;natural&quot;
and &quot;unnatural&quot; deaths has warped treatment decisions made by
compassionate doctors wishing to respond to requests from terminally ill
patients who are not on respirators or IV drips for food and water.</P>
<P>Many of these individuals, denied assistance from physicians fearing
criminal penalties, resort to &quot;back-alley euthanasia&quot; -- an option
that provides no safeguards at all and thus no assurance that a hastened death
is appropriate or that the methods used will minimize further pain, or even
succeed.</P>
<P>Indeed, the current unregulated practice of assisted suicide by the
terminally ill is clearly more subject to the kind of abuse and mistakes that
concern the states than a situation in which checks and balances could be
implemented prior to an ultimate decision. </P>
<P>Several model statutes for physician aid-in-dying already exist that
incorporate procedural safeguards, including requirements of witnesses,
reasonable waiting periods to preclude rash decisions, and confirmation by a
second physician that the patient has been receiving proper care and is not
suffering from depression.</P>
<P>The American Civil Liberties Union and others support the use of legislative
safeguards to ensure that all requests of the terminally ill for aid in dying
are the product of thoughtful and informed self- determination, not the decision
of legislators and government bureaucrats.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
