<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  01/07/97 -- ACLU Welcomes 105th Congress; Warns of

Anti-Liberty Leftovers from 104th</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Welcomes 105th Congress; Warns of Anti-Liberty Leftovers from 104th</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Tuesday, January 7, 1997</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON  As Congress returns to Washington for the beginning of its 105th
Session, the whirlwind surrounding Newt Gingrichs bid for re-election Speaker of
the House has taken center stage. But the American Civil Liberties Union, deeply
concerned about what will follow this initial burst of activity, warned of
continued attacks on civil liberties after the opening session flurry. 
</P>
<P>&quot;Left over from Congresss last session is a host of anti-civil
liberties proposals just waiting to be reintroduced,&quot; said Laura W. Murphy,
director of the ACLUs Washington Legislative Office. &quot;Even battles that we
won in the last Congress will resurface this year in the war to keep the Bill of
Rights intact.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Some of the ACLU's key issues and legislative priorities for the 105th
Congress follows: 
</P>
<P><B>Freedom of Expression
</B>

</P>
<P>The ACLU said that a proposal certain to return in the 105th Congress is a
constitutional amendment to outlaw political expression in the form of &quot;flag

desecration.&quot; Although the House passed this measure in 1995, it was
narrowly defeated in the Senate. Since then, key proponents of the measure have
labeled it a top priority for this year and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
has said it will be among the first bills considered. 
</P>
<P>Congresss continuing attempt to limit political speech by considering
various campaign finance reform bills also clashes with the First Amendment.
Although the estimated dollar figures that members of Congress alone spent
during the last election are high, the ACLU said that current proposals for
change are unconstitutional caps on protected political expression. 

</P>
<P><B>Religious Liberty</B> 
</P>
<P>High on the list of priorities for conservatives in Congress are a variety
of measures that will invite government into our nations churches and religious
schools. Among these proposals that would destroy religious autonomy from
government control are taxpayer-funded vouchers for parochial school tuition and
social service contracts between the government and houses of worship. The ACLU
said it will vigorously oppose these legislative schemes intended to sideline
religious liberty in this country. 
</P>
<P><B>Reproductive Freedom</B> 
</P>
<P>Congresss unsuccessful attempt to criminalize a rare but necessary late-term
abortion technique last term provided only temporary relief for women.
Anti-choice members of the House and Senate will soon reintroduce a bill similar
to the &quot;Partial Birth Abortion Act of 1996&quot; threatening not only this
life-saving technique, but the future of all reproductive freedoms. Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle recently said that he was working on a &quot;compromise&quot;
that would avoid another Presidential veto. 
</P>
<P><B>Counter-Terrorism and Privacy</B> 
</P>
<P>The findings of the White House Commission on Aviation Safety and Security,
which will be released next month, could quickly turn into legislation requiring
the use of profiles to subject air passengers to heightened security measures.
Profiles can be discriminatory and were ineffective in curbing hijacking
activities in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Implementing profiling as a security measure would require a database of
individual travel habits, therefore violating the privacy rights of all air
travelers. The Commission is also poised to recommend funding for development of
body scanners capable of projecting a naked image of air passengers in the
search for explosives. 
</P>
<P><B>Criminal Justice
</B>
</P>
<P>One bright spot in the Congressional agenda, the ACLU said, is legislation
introduced today designed to address the problem of racially targeted police
traffic stops occurring on our nations highways. The bill, entitled the &quot;Traffic
Stops Statistics Act of 1997,&quot; will require police departments to keep a
record of the race, the alleged traffic infractions of citizens they stop, as
well as the rationale for any subsequent search and the nature of any contraband
discovered in the search. 
</P>
<P>In introducing the legislation, Representative John Conyers said that
although African Americans make up about 14 percent of the population, they
account for 72 percent of routine traffic stops. 
</P>
<P>The ACLU itself, in an ongoing lawsuit filed against the Maryland State
Police for discriminatory stops, reported police statistics documenting that 73
percent of the traffic stops and searches on I-95 between Baltimore and Delaware
since January of 1995 were conducted on cars driven by African Americans, even
though African Americans only made up 14 percent of the drivers along that
highway. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
