<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  1/3/97 -- COURT DISMISSES CRIMINAL CHARGES BROUGHT

AGAINST WOMAN FOR HER CONDUCT DURING PREGNANCY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>COURT DISMISSES CRIMINAL CHARGES BROUGHT AGAINST WOMAN FOR HER CONDUCT
DURING PREGNANCY</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Friday, January 3, 1997</B></P>
<P>NEWARK, NJ -- A trial court judge today dismissed criminal charges of
aggravated manslaughter and child endangerment brought against a woman who was
alleged to have used cocaine during her pregnancy and who gave birth prematurely
to a fetus that died shortly after birth.  Judge Donald S. Goldman, of Essex
County Criminal Court, held that the legislature did not intend for activities
by a woman during pregnancy which may harm her fetus to constitute crimes under
New Jersey law.   </P>
<P>The American Civil Liberties Union of New Jersey and the Association of
Criminal Defense Lawyers of New Jersey participated as amici curiae in the case.
 </P>
<P>&quot;We are pleased that the court reaffirmed a woman's right to become
pregnant and carry her pregnancy to term without having to fear that her
prenatal conduct may subject her to criminal prosecution,&quot; said Lenora M.
Lapidus, legal director of the ACLU of New Jersey.     </P>
<P>The court's decision was consistent with that of nineteen out of twenty
states which have found charges brought against women for alleged prenatal drug
or alcohol use to be unconstitutional or unsupported by law.  </P>
<P>&quot;Punitive approaches, such as this prosecution, harm women and children
by frightening pregnant women away from needed drug treatment and prenatal care,&quot;
said Laura K. Abel, of Crummy, Del Deo, Dolan, Griffinger and Vecchione, who,
along with Lawrence S. Lustberg, filed the brief on behalf of the ACLU-NJ and
the ACDL-NJ.  &quot;For this reason, every leading public health organization
concerned with the issue has opposed the prosecution of women for their conduct,
including drug use, during pregnancy.&quot;  </P>
<P>The defendant went into labor at approximately 24 weeks of pregnancy and
delivered a premature fetus that died within an hour after delivery. 
Prosecutors charged her with first-degree aggravated manslaughter and
second-degree endangering the welfare of a child, alleging that she used cocaine
during her pregnancy which caused the death of her premature fetus.  In
dismissing these charges, Judge Goldman held that the legislature did not intend
these criminal statutes to be applied to women for their conduct while pregnant
that may affect their fetuses.</P>
<P>The Defendant was represented by Assistant Deputy Public Defender, Donna
Scocozza (Office of Public Defender) and Priscilla Smith of the Center for
Reproductive Law and Policy. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
