<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572"> </P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<H3>December 1996 Press Releases</H3>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n123196a.html">12/31/96 -- ACLU Says
Clinton Lags Way Behind Public on Medical Marijuana</A><BR>NEW YORK -- The
American Civil Liberties Union today said the Clinton Administration's
uncompromising opposition to legalizing marijuana for medicinal purposes is out
of step, not only with the voters of Arizona and California, but with public
opinion nationwide. </P>
<P><A HREF="#criminal"></A><A HREF="n123096a.html">12/30/96 -- ACLU Says
Clinton Response on Medical Marijuana is Out of Control</A><BR>WASHINGTON --
The Clinton Administration's response to the California and Arizona voters'
endorsement of the use of marijuana for medical purposes shows the extent to
which our government's drug policies have spun out of control and are now poised
to go off the deep end.   Prosecuting physicians who prescribe marijuana to
alleviate suffering is a ridiculous use of limited federal law enforcement
resources that will only cause further suffering.</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A NAME="women"></A><A HREF="n122396b.html">12/23/96
-- PROPOSITION 209 CANNOT BE ENFORCED; U.S. DISTRICT COURT ORDERS PRELIMINARY
INJUNCTION</A><BR> Today (Monday, December 23, 1996) U.S. District Court Judge
Thelton Henderson issued a preliminary injunction barring the enforcement of the
anti-affirmative action measure Proposition 209. </P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n122396a.html">12/23/96 -- ACLU Sues For
Disclosure of Police Investigation Of Denver's TJ High School Incident</A><BR>DENVER
-- The American Civil Liberties Union of Colorado filed suit today under the
Colorado Open Records Act seeking disclosure of the report that the Denver
Police Department prepared after its internal investigation of alleged police
misconduct in connection with a disturbance at a dance at Thomas Jefferson High
School last May 4.</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n121996a.html">12/19/96 -- TV Ratings Scheme
is Government-Coerced Censorship; &quot;Don't Let Big Brother Take Over The
Remote Control,&quot;ACLU Says
</A><BR>The heavy hand of government is all over today's announcement by the
television industry of a new &quot;age-based&quot; TV rating scheme.
</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n121796a.html">12/17/96 -- HISTORIC FREE
SPEECH DECISION FROM APPELLATE DIVISION IN CONDOMINIUM CASE</A><BR> NEWARK, NJ
-- The Appellate Division of Superior Court today issued an historic free speech
ruling requiring a private residential condominium to give political candidates
a right to reply to messages distributed to residents by the condominium
association.
</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n121696b.html">12/16/96 -- Vermont Supreme
Court To Hear Oral Arguments in Property Tax Suit
</A><BR>BURLINGTON, VT -- The Vermont Supreme Court will hear oral arguments
this week to decide whether the lawsuit brought by the American Civil Liberties
Union to overturn the state's educational funding system should go to trial. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n121696a.html">12/16/96 -- Supreme Court Grants Mississippi Mother
Right to Appeal Loss of Children</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court today
ruled in a case brought by the American Civil Liberties Union that Mississippi
may not deny a mother the opportunity to appeal the termination of her parental
rights solely because she could not afford to pay $2,352.36 in court fees. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n121296b.html">12/12/96 -- Kathryn Engustian Joins ACLU Washington
Office As Legislative Counsel</A><BR>WASHINGTON &#150; Kathryn M. Engustian has
joined the ACLU's National Washington Office as a Legislative Counsel
responsible for issues of      reproductive freedom and women's rights.  
</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n121296a.html">12/12/96 -- Bradford v.
Maryland State Board of Education: Summary of Settlement</A><BR>BALTIMORE -- In
1994, the ACLU filed suit against the Maryland State Board of Education on
behalf of Baltimore City schoolchildren at risk of school failure alleging that
their right to an adequate education under the Maryland constitution was being
violated. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n121096a.html">12/10/96 -- ACLU of Washington
Defends Judicial Free Speech</A><BR>SEATTLE -- The American Civil Liberties
Union of Washington has announced that it is providing legal representation for
Washington Supreme Court Justice Richard Sanders in his defense against charges
that he violated the Code of Judicial Conduct by speaking publicly to a &quot;March
for Life&quot; gathering of abortion opponents.
</P>
<P><A HREF="n120996c.html">12/9/96 -- ACLU-NC Honors United Farm Workers
Leader Dolores Huerta at Bill of Rights Day Celebration</A><BR> Honoring United
Farm Workers leader Dolores Huerta, the ACLU of Northern California will hold
its annual Bill of Rights Day Celebration at the Sheraton Palace Hotel in San
Francisco on Sunday, December 15, at 5 PM (no-host bar and reception at 4 PM).
The Keynote Speaker will be Wade Henderson of the National Leadership Conference
on Civil Rights, speaking on civil rights following the passage of Proposition
209.
</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A NAME="womens"></A><A HREF="n120996b.html">12/9/96
-- Restraining Order Stops University of California From Implementing
Affirmative Action Initiative</A><BR>SAN FRANCISCO -- The University of
California has been stopped from implementing Proposition 209 and ending 
programs designed to eliminate race and gender bias by a Temporary Restraining
Order issued by U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n120996a.html">12/9/96 -- Drug-Testing
Welfare Recipients Would be Useless, Costly and Unconstitutional</A><BR>BALTIMORE
-- No one doubts that the goal of the proposal -- to get drug users in treatment
and make sure their public benefits go to satisfy their children's needs -- is a
laudable one. But plan is wrong because its useless, its costly, and it violates
people's constitutional rights.
</P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n120696a.html">12/06/96 -- Supreme Court to
Review Landmark Decision Barring Internet Censorship</A><BR>NEW YORK-The
Supreme Court's decision to review Reno v. ACLU comes as no surprise,
considering that this is an important case challenging an important federal
statute.
</P>
<P><A HREF="n120696b.html">12/6/96 -- ACLU Files Suit To Prevent Oregon
'Victims Rights' Measure From Taking Effect</A><BR>PORTLAND, OR -- The American
Civil Liberties Union of Oregon filed a lawsuit this week in Marion County
Circuit Court seeking a declaration that Measure 40, known as the &quot;victims
rights&quot; amendment, is unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A HREF="n120396b.html">12/03/96 -- CIVIL LIBERTIES
COALITION CALLS TAX ASSESSMENT SYSTEM RACIALLY  DISCRIMINATORY, ASKS COUNTY FOR
REFORM</A><BR>Claiming that Nassau County's system of tax assessment of homes
discriminates against blacks and Latinos, the Nassau Chapter of the New York
Civil Liberties Union and a coalition of civic groups and individuals has today
sent a letter to county officials asking for reform.
</P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n120396a.html">12/03/96 -- Hawaii Judge OK's
Marriage for Three Lesbian and Gay Couples</A><BR>HONOLULU -- In a closely
watched lesbian and gay civil rights case that has spurred legislative action in
more than 30 states and Congress, a Hawaii judge today paved the way for three
lesbian and gay couples to marry, ruling that the state's denial of marriage
licenses violates Hawaii's Constitution.  
</P>
<P><A NAME="church"></A><A NAME="criminal"></A><A NAME="cyber"></A><A
NAME="death"></A><A NAME="free"></A><A NAME="aids"></A><A NAME="immigrants"></A><A
NAME="gay"></A><A NAME="security"></A><A NAME="racial"></A><A
NAME="reproductive"></A><A NAME="students"></A><A NAME="voting"></A><A
NAME="womens"></A><A NAME="workplace"></A></P>
