<TITLE>ACLU Press Releases -- November 1996</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572"> </P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<H3>November 1996 Press Releases</H3>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A HREF="n112796a.html">11/27/96 -- ACLU APPLAUDS
FEDERAL COURT TRO IN PROPOSITION 209 CHALLENGE</A><BR>On November 27, Judge
Thelton Henderson issued a Temporary Restraining Order in the case of Coalition
for Economic Equity v. Wilson, challenging the constitutionality of Proposition
209.
</P>
<P><A NAME="aids"></A><A HREF="n112296e.html">11/22/96 -- Drop in AIDS Among
Infants Proves Mandatory Testing Not Necessary, ACLU Says</A><BR>WASHINGTON --
A new government report showing a sharp decline of AIDS cases among infants was
heralded by the American Civil Liberties Union as further proof that counseling
and voluntary testing are the best ways to stem HIV transmission between the
mother and the newborn.  </P>
<P><A NAME="church"></A><A HREF="n112296d.html">11/22/96 -- Federal Court

Rules Unconstitutional Barrington's Practice of Snow-Plowing for Churches</A><BR>PROVIDENCE,
RI -- Ruling in an ACLU of Rhode Island lawsuit that generated a great deal of
controversy, a federal court has ruled unconstitutional the Town of Barrington's
practice of providing special tax-supported services to local religious
institutions.  Those benefits, not provided to non-religious institutions,
involved free trash collection and free clearing of snow from churches' parking
lots.  </P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n112296a.html">11/22/96 -- Federal Court
Re-Hears Challenge to Military's Anti-Gay Ban</A><BR>The American Civil
Liberties Union and Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund debated government
lawyers before a federal judge in Brooklyn district court this week, arguing
that the military's so-called &quot;Don't Ask, Don't Tell&quot; law is
unconstitutional for requiring total celibacy as well as secrecy from lesbian
and gay service members and not from non-gay service members.</P>
<P><A NAME="immigrants"></A><A HREF="n112296b.html">11/22/96 -- CLASS ACTION
SUIT AGAINST LANGUAGE DISCRIMINATION IN INSURANCE SETTLED:  PLAINTIFFS WIN
DAMAGES, COMPANY WILL DROP ENGLISH REQUIREMENT</A><BR>The Northwestern Mutual
Life Insurance Company will not bar non-English speakers from their life
insurance policies as a result of a settlement of the class action lawsuit, Kim
v. Northwestern, affirmed by U.S. District Court Judge Lowell Jensen on November
20.</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n112296c.html">11/22/96 -- U.S. DISTRICT COURT
TO HEAR ARGUMENT ON BERKELEY'S ANTI-SITTING ORDINANCE</A><BR>On November 22, in
U.S. District Court in Oakland, ACLU-NC Managing Attorney Alan Schlosser will
argue that an injunction barring the enforcement of Berkeley's &quot;anti-sidewalk
sitting&quot; ordinance should remain in place.</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A HREF="n111496a.html">11/14/96 -- ACLU MOVES TO
HAVE MARYLAND STATE POLICE HELD IN CONTEMPT</A><BR>The American Civil Liberties
Union of Maryland is asking a federal district court in Baltimore to hold the
Maryland State Police agency in contempt of court and to impose a $250,000 &quot;conditional
civil contempt monetary penalty,&quot; based upon a showing that state police
are violating a 1995 court decree by continuing a pattern of race discrimination
in drug interdiction activities carried out along the Interstate 95 corridor. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n111296a.html">11/12/96 -- ACLU Declares
Victory in Education Suit For the Children of Baltimore</A><BR> BALTIMORE --
Two years after filing a lawsuit to enforce the constitutional rights of
Baltimore City's poorest schoolchildren, the ACLU today declared a victory for
the children when the parties announced an agreement in principle to settle the
case. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A HREF="n110696a.html">11/6/96 -- ACLU Files Federal
Lawsuit to Block Implementation of California's Anti-Affirmative  Action
Initiative</A><BR>SAN FRANCISCO -- The ACLU affiliates in Northern and Southern
California -working with the Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights, the Employment
Law Center and a coalition of civil rights organizations -- filed a lawsuit in
federal district court in San Francisco this morning to block implementation of
Proposition 209.</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n110596a.html">11/5/96 -- Ninth Circuit Court
of Appeals Rules NEA Decency Requirement Unconstitutional
</A><BR>SAN FRANCISCO -- Acting in a longstanding, nationally significant
dispute over artists free speech, the U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals today
declared unconstitutional a statute requiring the National Endowment for the
Arts to take into account &quot;general standards of decency&quot; in making
grant decisions.</P>
<P></P>
<P><A HREF="oct96.html">Previous Month's Releases</A><BR><A
HREF="pressarc.html">News Release Archives</A><BR><A HREF="newssearch.html">Search
ACLU News Releases</A></P>
