<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -- October 1996 Press Releases</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572"> </P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<H3>October 1996 Press Releases</H3>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n103196a.html">10/31/96 -- ACLU Asks Court to
Affirm Landmark Decision Barring Internet Censorship</A><BR>WASHINGTON--The
American Civil Liberties Union today filed a motion asking the Supreme Court to
affirm a lower court decision rejecting as unconstitutional government
censorship of the Internet.  </P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n103196b.html">10/31/96 -- ACLU Background
Briefing <I>Reno v. ACLU</I>: The Road to the Supreme Court</A><BR>Following a
landmark victory in June for free speech rights in cyberspace, <I>ACLU v. Reno</I>
now awaits Supreme Court action.   </P>
<P><A NAME="voting"></A><A HREF="n103196c.html">10/31/96 -- Minnesota Civil
Liberties Union Challenges Law Prohibiting Former Sex Offenders from Voting</A><BR>
MINNEAPOLIS -- The Minnesota Civil Liberties Union has filed a lawsuit
challenging the constitutionality of a state law that prohibits individuals
committed as Sexual Psychopathic Personalities or Sexually Dangerous Persons
from ever voting.       </P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n102996a.html">10/29/96 -- D.C. Curfew Law
Struck Down</A> <BR>WASHINGTON -- In a major defeat for curfew laws aimed at
keeping minors off the streets, a federal court in Washington today struck down
the city's juvenile curfew law, saying that the measure violates the rights of
teenagers and their parents. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n102996b.html">10/29/96 -- California Supreme Court to Hear
Challenge to San Jose Anti-Gang Injunction </A><BR>SACRAMENTO -- An ACLU
challenge to San Jose's use of a civil injunction to deal with alleged gang
activity will be argued before the California Supreme Court next week.
</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n102996c.html">10/29/96 -- ACLU and NAACP
Begin Pittsburgh Public School Curriculum  To Improve Police-Community Relations</A>
<BR>PITTSBURGH --  Pittsburgh School District Superintendent Louise Brennen
announced today at a news conference that the District has begun a new one week
curriculum --  developed primarily by the ACLUs Greater Pittsburgh Chapter and
the Pittsburgh Branch of the NAACP -- about students rights and responsibilities
when interacting with the police. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n102696a.html">10/26/96 -- ACLU Stands
With Abortion Providers On National Day of Appreciation</A><BR>Statement of
Janet Gallagher, Director ACLU's Reproductive Freedom Project
</P>
<P><A HREF="n102496b.html">10/24/96 -- The Votes Are In: 104th Congress Flunks
Civil Liberties, New ACLU Online Voters Guide Shows</A><BR> WASHINGTON -- From
Internet censorship to increased wiretapping and a punitive immigration law, the
104th Congress flunked civil liberties, according to a new online voters guide
launched today by the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n102496a.html">10/24/96 -- ACLU Says Mall's
Restrictive Leafletting Policy Violates High Court Ruling on Free Speech</A><BR>NEWARK,
NJ -- The ACLU of New Jersey said that it will go to court tomorrow morning to
prevent a New Jersey mall from imposing unreasonable burdens on political groups
seeking to distribute leaflets on its premises. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n102396a.html">10/23/96 -- ACLU Argues Landmark
Gay Rights Case Before Full U.S. Appeals Court in Georgia </A><BR>ATLANTA -- In
a breakthrough case seeking to protect lesbian and gay relationships, a Federal
appeals court today heard oral argument in a case brought by a Georgia lawyer
who was fired by the state Attorney General after she and her lesbian partner
participated in a religious commitment ceremony.</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n102296a.html">10/22/96 -- ACLU Suit Helps
Reporter Break Down &quot;Blue Wall of Silence&quot;</A><BR>NEWARK, NJ -- In an
important victory for a free press, the ACLU-NJ today settled a suit challenging
police officials' decision to retaliate against a reporter who had written
articles critical of the police department and its Chief of Police. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="voting"></A><A HREF="n102296b.html">10/22/96 -- ACLU and
Allegheny County Resolve Dispute Over Socialist Workers Party on the Ballot</A><BR>
PITTSBURGH -- The American Civil Liberties Union announced today that a dispute
with the Allegheny County Department of Elections over the placement of the
Socialist Workers Party on the ballot in the 22nd legislative district has been
resolved. Under the agreement, the County will treat the Socialist Workers Party
the same as other political parties in the race by giving it its own row on the
ballot. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n102196a.html">10/21/96 -- Lambda and ACLU
Respond to Supreme Court Refusal to Review a Challenge to Military's Ban on Gay
Troops</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The United States Supreme Court today declined to
hear without comment a challenge to the government's so-called &quot;Don't Ask,
Don't Tell&quot; ban on lesbians and gay men in the military, leaving  the
question open as to whether the law will survive constitutional scrutiny.</P>
<P><A NAME="immigrants"></A><A HREF="n101696a.html">10/16/96 -- ACLU Sues
Over CO Policy Of Confiscating 'Suspicious' Immigration Documents</A><BR>DENVER
-- The American Civil Liberties Union of Colorado filed suit today to challenge
a policy of the Colorado Division of Motor Vehicles that instructs low-level
employees to confiscate immigration documents that they suspect are fraudulent.
</P>
<P><A NAME="death"></A><A HREF="n101596a.html">10/15-96 -- U.S. Supreme Court
Declines California's Appeal on Gas Chamber</A><BR>SAN FRANCISCO -- Today's
United States Supreme Court decision remanding the case Fierro v. Gomez to the
Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals on technical grounds reaffirms the ACLU's
fundamental argument that the use of lethal gas to kill Death Row inmates
constitutes cruel and unusual punishment, said Michael Laurence, a cooperating
attorney with the American Civil Liberties Union of Northern California who
brought the original      challenge in 1992.
</P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n101596b.html">10/15/96 -- Minnesota Court of
Appeals Upholds Dismissal of Indictment Against Candidate</A><BR>MINNEAPOLIS --
In a decision filed today, the Minnesota Court of Appeals upheld the dismissal
of an indictment against a former Congressional candidate for violating state
campaign laws. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="immigrants"></A><A HREF="n100996a.html">10/9/96 -- U.S. Judge
Bars INS From Denying Hearings to Immigrants</A><BR>SEATTLE, Wash. -- In a
ruling that affects thousands of immigrants nationwide who are facing
deportation, a federal district court in Seattle issued a permanent injunction
last week against the Immigration and Naturalization Service for failing to
inform individuals of their right to a hearing prior to deportation.
</P>
<P><A NAME="workplace"></A><A HREF="n100896a.html">10/8/96 -- ACLU Challenges
Municipal Drug Testing Policy Before California Supreme Court</A><BR>  LOS
ANGELES -- The California Supreme Court will hear arguments tomorrow in an ACLU

of Southern California case challenging a drug testing policy adopted by the
City of Glendale in 1986 that requires all job applicants and candidates for
promotions to submit to a drug test. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n100796a.html">10/7/96 -- Mississippi Mom Who Lost Children Takes
Case to U.S. Supreme Court</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties
Union today argued before the U.S. Supreme Court that Mississippi may not deny a
mother the opportunity to appeal the termination of her parental rights solely
because she could not afford to pay $2,352.36 in court fees.  
</P>
<P><A HREF="n100396b.html">10/3/96 -- ACLU Denounces President and Congress
For Attack on the Basic Rights of Immigrants</A><BR>Calling the federal
immigration bill signed by President Clinton within the budget legislation &quot;the
worst immigration bill since the racist National Origins Act of 1924,&quot; the
ACLU's offices in California and its national Immigrants' Rights Project today
condemned the measure as an outrageous example of political maneuvering which

shreds our most basic Constitutional guarantees.
</P>
<P><A NAME="racial"></A><A HREF="n100396a.html">10/3/96 -- ACLU Says 
'Redlining' by Philadelphia Mortgage Company Keeps Black Home Buyers from
Realizing American Dream</A>     
<BR>PHILADELPHIA -- Saying that a Philadelphia-area mortgage company has widely
discriminated against African-Americans in the home loan application and
approval process, the American Civil Liberties Union today filed a class-action
complaint with the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission.  
</P>
<P><A HREF="n100296a.html">10/2/96 -- ACLU Says 104th Congress Will Be
Remembered As a Benchmark for Anti-Liberty Extremism</A><BR> WASHINGTON -- The
American Civil Liberties Union today issued a stinging assessment of the 104th
Congress, saying that actions by      Congress during the pass two years have
amounted to one of the harshest attacks on civil liberties in the nations
history. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n100296b.html">10/2/96 -- ACLU Condemns CA
Effort to Stop Unmarried Couples From Adopting Children</A><BR>LOS ANGELES --
The ACLU of Southern California denounced as cruel and politically motivated
Governor Wilson's effort to stop unmarried couples from adopting children. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n100196a.html">10/1/96 -- ACLU Commends CA
Veto Of Bill On Police Misconduct</A><BR>SACRAMENTO -- Following is the
statement issued by the California affiliates of the American Civil Liberties
Union: We applaud Gov. Wilson's decision to veto SB 282, a bill that would have
significantly undermined efforts to monitor police officers' behavior and hold
them accountable for their actions.</P>
<P></P>
<P><A HREF="sep96.html">Previous Month's Releases</A></P>
