<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -- September 1996 Press Releases</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572"> </P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<H3>Steptember 1996 Press Releases</H3>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n092696a.html">9/26/96 -- ACLU
Applauds Senate for Upholding President's Veto on Rare Abortion Technique</A><BR>WASHINGTON
-- By upholding President Clinton's veto of the so-called &quot;Partial Birth
Abortion Ban Act of 1996&quot; by a vote of 57-41, the Senate has protected the
basic relationship between a doctor and patient when determining the need to end
a fatally flawed pregnancy, the American Civil Liberties Union said today.
</P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n092496a.html">9/24/96 -- Groups Challenge
Georgia Law Restricting Free Speech in Cyberspace<BR>
</A>ATLANTA--The American Civil Liberties Union, Electronic Frontiers Georgia,
Georgia State Representative Mitchell Kaye and others today filed a lawsuit
seeking a preliminary injunction against a Georgia statute restricting free
speech in cyberspace. </P>
<P><A HREF="n092496b.html">9/24/96 -- Federal Court Says US Must Stand Trial
For Kidnapping Mexican Doctor</A><BR>LOS ANGELES -- The Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeal today ruled that Dr. Humberto Alvarez Machain may pursue his civil trial
against the United      States for his abduction, torture and imprisonment,
rejecting the Government's attempt to be free of all accountability for the
April 1990 kidnapping of      Dr. Humberto Alvarez Machain from his medical
office in Guadalajara, Mexico. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n091996a.html">9/19/96 -- ACLU
Condemns House Override of Bill Criminalizing Late-Term Abortion Method<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The American Civil Liberties Union today strongly
condemned the House of Representatives for overriding President Clinton's veto
of the so-called &quot;Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act,&quot; a bill that

criminalizes a late-term abortion procedure. </P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n091896a.html">9/18/96 -- ACLU Files
Class-Action Lawsuit Against Pittsburgh Public Defenders for Failing to Counsel
the Poor<BR>
</A>PITTSBURGH -- In a major case seeking to protect the constitutional rights
of poor criminal defendants, the American Civil Liberties Union and its
Pittsburgh chapter today filed a class-action lawsuit against Allegheny County
for failing to provide adequate legal representation to its indigent clients.</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n091896b.html">9/18/96 -- ACLU Files Open
Records Request For Police Investigation of TJ High School Incident <BR>
</A>DENVER -- The American Civil Liberties Union of Colorado formally asked the
City of Denver today to release the report of the Denver Police Department's
internal investigation of alleged police misconduct in connection with a
disturbance at a dance at Thomas Jefferson High School last May 4. </P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n091796a.html">9/17/96 -- Minnesota Court of
Appeals Overturns Ban On 'The Original Crazy Horse Malt Liquor' Brand Name<BR>
</A>MINNEAPOLIS -- In a decision filed today, the Minnesota Court of Appeals
reversed the decision of the Commissioner of Public Safety revoking the brand
label registration for &quot;The Original Crazy Horse Malt Liquor&quot; brand
name. The court held that the Minnesota statute, which prohibits the
registration of a malt liquor brand label that &quot;states or implies a false
connection with an actual living or dead American Indian leader,&quot; was an
impermissibly content-based restriction on commercial free speech in violation
of the First Amendment to the United States Constitution.
</P>
<P><A NAME="criminal"></A><A HREF="n091796b.html">9/17/96 -- ACLU Condemns
Governor For Signing Mandatory Chemical Castration Law<BR>
</A>SAN FRANCISCO -- Charging that the mandatory chemical castration law to be
signed by Governor Wilson today is &quot;barbaric, unconstitutional and
ultimately ineffective in protecting our children,&quot; the American Civil
Liberties Union said today that it is considering challenging the new law in
court. </P>
<P><A HREF="n091796c.html">9/17/96 -- ACLU Positions On November 1996 Ballot
Initiatives Vote to Defend Affirmative Action, Support Medical Marijuana <BR>
</A>SAN FRANCISCO -- The American Civil Liberties Union of Northern California,
representing more than 25,000 people, is urging its members and supporters to
vote for civil liberties on the November 5 ballot. The ACLU is playing a key
role in the campaign to defeat Proposition 209, the anti-affirmative action
initiative, and is also urging voters to support measures allowing for the
medical use of marijuana and raising the minimum wage. </P>
<P><A NAME="cyber"></A><A HREF="n091696b.html">9/16/96 -- ACLU Congratulates
Princeton on Revised Internet Policy<BR>
</A>NEW YORK, NY--The American Civil Liberties Union today congratulated
Princeton University for effectively ending its policy barring students and
staff from using the computer network for &quot;political purposes.&quot;
</P>
<P><A NAME="students"></A><A HREF="n091696a.html">9/16/96 -- Oral Arguments
to Begin In Vermont Educational Equity Lawsuit <BR>
</A>HYDE PARK, VT -- In the first court action in the educational
equity-property tax suit filed by ACLU last year, lawyers for the State and for
the American Civil Liberties Union of Vermont will go head to head in oral
arguments here on Wednesday, September 18. </P>
<P>9/13/96 -- <A HREF="n091396a.html">ACLU Implores LA To Oppose Welfare
Provisions on Immigration Status</A><BR>LOS ANGELES -- In testimony before the
U.S. Civil Rights Commission this morning, ACLU of Southern California's
Executive Director, Ramona Ripston called upon Mayor Richard Riordan and the Los
Angeles City Council to oppose provisions in the new federal anti-welfare bill
that would dismantle directives prohibiting public employees from asking about a
person's immigrant status.  
</P>
<P><A NAME="reproductive"></A><A HREF="n091296a.html">9/12/96 -- ACLU Urges
Congress to Uphold President's Veto On Rare Abortion Technique<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union today strongly urged
Congress not to undo the work of President Clinton who secured the reproductive
rights of women in the United States by vetoing the so-called &quot;Partial
Birth Abortion Ban Act of 1996&quot; in April. </P>
<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n091096b.html">9/10/96 -- ACLU Condemns
Restriction On Soldiers' Rights; Says Litigation Likely Against Censorship<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union denounced as
unconstitutional a provision of the Defense Authorization bill approved by
Congress today that offends the First Amendment rights of the men and women of
the Armed Forces. </P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n091096a.html">9/10/96 -- ACLU Blasts Senate
Passage of Anti-Gay Marriage Ban; Calls Vote a &quot;Deplorable Act&quot; and
Vows Legal Challenge<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union today denounced the Senate
for passing a bill designed to ban same-sex marriages, calling the vote a
deplorable act of hostility toward lesbian and gay Americans and pledging to
challenge the measure in court. </P>
<P><A NAME="gay"></A><A HREF="n090696a.html">9/6/96 -- Non-Bias Job Law for
Gays Scheduled for Free-Standing Senate Vote on Tuesday<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON -- In an unexpected turn of events, Senate leaders announced
Thursday evening that the Employment Non-Discrimination Law will come up for a
floor vote as a free-standing measure next Tuesday, Sept. 10. The American Civil
Liberties Union, which has been lobbying support for the bill, called the vote
an important step towards ensuring fairness. </P>

<P><A NAME="free"></A><A HREF="n090696b.html">9/6/96 -- ACLU WINS FIRST ROUND
IN CHALLENGE TO COLORADO BEGGING LAW<BR>
</A>The ACLU of Colorado won the first round today in its federal court
challenge to a Colorado statute that makes it a crime to &quot;loiter[] for the
purpose of begging.&quot;</P>
<P><A NAME="security"></A><A HREF="n090596a.html">9/5/96 -- ACLU Seeks
Greater Airport Safety; Calls For Measures That Also Protect Individual Liberty<BR>
</A>WASHINGTON In testimony before the White House Commission on Aviation Safety
and Security, the American Civil Liberties Union today called for measures that
improve airport safety without sacrificing privacy and equality rights.</P>
<P><A NAME="voting"></A><A HREF="n090496a.html">9/4/96 -- ACLU Background
Briefer -- The End of Reconstruction Redux: Voting Rights On Trial in South
Carolina<BR>
</A>COLUMBIA, SC -- In April 1877, William J. Whipper, an African American
member of the South Carolina General Assembly, left office in the waning days of
Reconstruction to assume a local judgeship but was prevented from ever taking
his seat on the bench. He was among the last African Americans to serve in the
General Assembly for the next 100 years. Today, more than one hundred years
later, Seth Whipper, his great-great nephew, is fighting to retain his seat in
the General Assembly and to vindicate the rights of the voters who put him
there.</P>
<P><A NAME="workplace"></A><A HREF="n090196a.html">9/1/96 -- ACLU Marks Labor
Day With Workplace Rights Video and Report</A> <BR> Redoubling its efforts to
protect the rights of employees in the workplace, the American Civil Liberties
Union today launched its &quot;Campaign for Fairness in the Workplace&quot; with
the release of a 12-minute video and a white paper report that documents how
employees are being increasingly spied upon and monitored at work. </P>
<H4>To <A HREF="/news/newssearch.html">search press releases by subject</A>
rather than date, use our site search, featuring the powerful Excite search
engine.</H4>
