<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -- June Press Releases</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">
<P></P>
<H1>ACLU Press Releases</H1>
<P></P>
<H3>June Press Releases</H3>
<P><A HREF="n062896c.html">06/28/96 -- Government  to Appeal ACLU v. Reno
Decision  Protecting Free Speech in Cyberspace; ACLU Encouraged by Supreme Court
Ruling on Cable &quot;Indecency&quot; 
</A><BR>WASHINGTON, D.C.--ACLU v. Reno, the challenge to censorship provisions
of the Communications Decency Act,  is headed for the Supreme Court. 		 	</P>
<P><A HREF="n062896b.html"> 06/28/96: ACLU Wins Supreme Court Challenge 
Against Political Retribution in Government Contracting</A><BR>CHICAGO -- The
American Civil Liberties Union of Illinois scored a ground-breaking victory for
the First Amendment today when the United States Supreme Court ruled that
government bodies may not deny public contracts solely because of the political
associations of the company's owner.  The decision came in the case O'Hare Truck
Service v. City of Northlake, which ACLU of Illinois attorneys argued before the
Supreme Court last March.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062896a.html">06/28/96 -- ACLU Says 1995 Supreme Court Term
Marked by Historic Victories for Gay Rights and Women's Rights</A><BR>The
American Civil Liberties Union today released its annual summary of the 1995 
U.S. Supreme Court term, giving high marks to the Court's historic rulings on
gay rights, women's rights and its protection of free speech.   	</P>
<P><A HREF="n062796a.html">06/27/96 -- Elizabeth Alexander Named Director for
the ACLU National Prison Project</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil
Liberties Union today announced that Elizabeth Alexander has been appointed
director of its National Prison Project, which has been in the forefront of the
battle for prisoners' rights for 25 years.  She succeeds Alvin J. Bronstein, who
had been director since the start of the Project in 1972.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062696b.html">06/26/96 -- ACLU Calls H.R. 3565 a Civil Liberties
Nightmare for Nation's Children</A><BR>WASHINGTON, DC--It comes as no surprise
that H.R. 3565, the &quot;Violent Youth Predator Act of 1996,&quot;  is being
introduced in an election year, when competition for who can sound toughest on
crime is practically an Olympic sport.  </P>
<P><A HREF="n062696a.html">6/26/96 -- U.S. Supreme Court Overturns VMI's
All-Male Policy;  ACLU Says Ruling Ends Chapter in Sex Discrimination</A><BR>WASHINGTON
-- In an important victory for women's rights, the United States Supreme Court
today overturned the Virginia Military Institute's policy of excluding all
women, saying that it violated the Constitution's guarantee of equal protection.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062596a.html">06/26/96 --  RI Supreme Court Issues Major Ruling
in ACLU Case In Support of Rhode Islanders' Right to Petition Government</A><BR>In
what the ACLU called &quot;a resounding victory for the First Amendment rights
of all Rhode Islanders to petition government,&quot; the R.I. Supreme Court
today unanimously ruled that a &quot;defamation&quot; lawsuit filed against
North Kingstown resident Nancy Hsu Fleming for contacting the Department of
Environmental Management with concerns about a local landfill must be dismissed.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062596b.html">06/25/96: RI Supreme Court Issues Major Ruling in
ACLU Case In Support of Rhode Islanders' Right to Petition Government</A><BR>In
what the ACLU called &quot;a resounding victory for the First Amendment rights
of all Rhode Islanders to petition government,&quot; the R.I. Supreme Court
today unanimously ruled that a &quot;defamation&quot; lawsuit filed against
North Kingstown resident Nancy Hsu Fleming for contacting the Department of
Environmental Management with concerns about a local landfill must be dismissed.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062496b.html">06/24/96 -- Suit Filed Over Pat-Down Search Of
Westerly 6th Graders For Missing Pizza Knife</A><BR>WESTERLY, RI -- The ACLU of
Rhode Island has today filed a lawsuit in federal court challenging Westerly
school officials' actions in January in performing pat-down searches on more
than 200 sixth-graders in the Babcock Middle School cafeteria.  Officials had
been looking for a missing pizza knife, which was later found in a kitchen trash
can where a worker had accidentally thrown it out.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062496a.html">6/24/96 -- Supreme Court Imposes New Burdens on
Prisoners Attempting to Gain Access to Courts</A><BR>The Supreme Court issued
tough new burdens on prisoners' access to the courts by raising the standard
required for inmates to demonstrate that their rights have been violated.</P>
<P><A HREF="n062096b.html">06/20/96 -- ACLU RESPONDS TO CALIFORNIA SUPREME
COURT RULING ON THREE-STRIKES LAW STATEMENT FROM RAMONA RIPSTON       EXECUTIVE

DIRECTOR OF THE ACLU OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA</A><BR> &quot;The ACLU of Southern

California has always believed that the three-strikes law was not only
unconstitutional, but an obstruction to judicial discretion in appropriate
sentencing which is a bedrock of our justice system.      </P>
<P><A HREF="n062096a.html">6/20/96 -- Statement of Jordan Budd, Managing
Attorney              ACLU of San Diego and Imperial Counties </A><BR>SAN DIEGO
-- Today we are filing suit against the City of San Diego and the Republican
National Committee.  The purpose of the lawsuit is to obtain an injunction
prohibiting the RNC and the City from moving the Police Department's designated
free speech zone several hundred feet farther away from the Convention Center, 
simply to placate the demands of the Republican Party.        </P>
<P><A HREF="n061996a.html">6/19/96 -- ACLU Expresses &quot;Profound Concern&quot;
Over Reports of White House Access to FBI Files</A><BR>In a letter sent to
President Clinton, the American Civil Liberties Union expressed &quot;profound
concern&quot; over recent reports that the White House improperly obtained FBI
files on more than 400 individuals and said that the circumstances under which
the information has come to light are &quot;disconcerting.&quot;</P>
<P><A HREF="n061896a.html">6/18/96 -- Ozarks ACLU Challenges 'Prophecy'
Prohibitions
</A><BR>SPRINGFIELD, MO -- The Ozarks Chapter of the ACLU has challenged a 
city ordinance here that violates First Amendment rights of city  residents. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n061796a.html">6/17/96 -- State Admits Error of Out-of-State
Export of Juveniles</A><BR>DETROIT -- Attorneys for the Engler administration
today admitted that the state failed to hold required hearings before shipping
juvenile wards to private, for-profit detention facilities in Colorado, Iowa,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, and Texas. 
</P>
<P><A HREF="n061396a.html">6/13/96 -- ACLU Criticizes Supreme Court's
Continues Assult on Voting Rights Act</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil
Liberties Union today criticized  the Supreme Court's two decisions this morning
striking down majority-minority districts, saying that the Court's continued
assault on the Voting Rights Act will have a crippling effect on civil rights.
</P>
<P><A HREF="n061296a.html">6/12/96 -- ACLU LAUDS JUDGES' RULING PROTECTING
FREE SPEECH IN CYBERSPACE</A><BR>PHILADELPHIA -- In a resounding victory for
First Amendment rights everywhere, a three-judge panel in federal district court
in Philadelphia today struck down a law that would criminalize free speech in
cyberspace.        </P>
<P><A HREF="n061196b.html">6/11/96 -- ACLU Condemns Weakening of Voting Rights
Act</A><BR>WASHINGTON -- The House Judiciary Committee is scheduled to consider
legislation today that would repeal portions of the Voting Rights Act that bar
states from discriminating against some American citizens who are not proficient
in English. The bill would also repeal requirements that some states provide
bilingual ballots and oral assistance.
</P>
<P><A HREF="n060496a.html">6/4/96 -- ACLU Releases Special Report on the 104th
Congress' Attacks on Independence of Federal Courts</A><BR>The American Civil
Liberties Union released a special report that examines how a series of
legislative actions this Spring are undermining fundamental constitutional
rights by eroding the independence, scope and power of the Federal court system.
</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/news/n060396a.html">6/3/96 -- Mississippi
Mother Wins School Prayer Challenge Before U.S. Judge</A><BR>OXFORD, Miss. -- 
In a closely-watched school prayer case, a federal judge today ruled that a
Mississippi public school system had violated the First Amendment rights of a
mother whose children had to sit through religious teachings in the classrooms.

</P>
<P><A HREF="/library/vision1.html">6/2/96 -- &quot;Visions of Liberty,&quot; a
cyberspace column by ACLU Executive Director Ira Glasser</A><BR>Today, we
inaugurate a regular, weekly cyberspace column focusing on civil liberties in
America.  Why a column, why now, why here?</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
