<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -- Current Press Releases</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<blockquote>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif"><P>
<center>
<h1> ACLU Press Releases</h1>
</center>
<P>
<h3>February Press Releases</h3>
<a href="n022996d.html">2/29/96 --  House Prepares to Consider Revised Terrorism Bill:  Individual Rights, Personal Freedom Even More At Risk</a><br>Ignoring continuing  bipartisan concerns about federal law
enforcement, privacy and free speech, the full House of Representatives is
scheduled to consider H.R. 2768.<p>
<a href="n022996c.html">2/29/96 --  Mother's Challenge to Mississippi School Prayer 
Goes to Trial Before U.S. Judge on Monday, March 4th</a><br>A major school prayer challenge, brought by a Mississippi
mother on behalf of her five school children,  will go to trial on Monday,
March 4th before a federal judge in Oxford, Miss.

  
<P><a href="n022996b.html">2/29/96 -- ACLU Expresses Concerns on TV Rating Scheme;
Says "Voluntary" System is Government-Backed Censorship</a><br>The American Civil Liberties Union today expressed serious concerns about the federal government's heavy-handed attempt to force a
content rating scheme on the television industry.  

  
<P>
<a href="n022996.html">2/29/96 --  ACLU Urges Senate to Stand Firm Against
Unconstitutional Provisions of DC Columbia Appropriations Bill</a><br>The ACLU called on the Senate to continue its opposition because it would impose an unconstitutional school voucher plan,
restrictions on reproductive rights and anti-gay restrictions on the citizens of Washington, DC.

  
<P>
<a href="n022796.html">2/27/96 --  ACLU Says Immigration Bill Is Unconstitutional, 
                       Unwise and Un-American</a><br>The House and Senate are scheduled to vote shortly on the most
wide-ranging set of immigration proposals in decades.

  
<P>
<a href="n022696.html">2/26/96 --  "ACLU Argues Against State Funding of Religious Schools"</a><br>The Wisconsin
Supreme Court in Madison will hear arguments for and against religious school
choice in a case that has national importance. 

  
<P>
<a href="n022696c.html">2/26/96 --  ACLU Says Court Case Exposes America's Dirty Little Secret:
          The Criminal Justice System is Racially Biased</a><br>The US Supreme Court case US v.
Armstrong may provide the critical first step in
identifying a major source of racial discrimination in the nation's criminal
justice system.

  
<P><a href="n022696b.html">2/26/96 -- ACLU Urges Court to Purge Criminal Justice System of Racial Bias</a><br>In a strictly legal sense, the case of U.S. v. Armstrong appears to involve a  narrow procedural issue:  under what circumstances must a federal prosecutor reveal
to the defense her reasons for bringing a prosecution.

  
<P>
<a href="n022396c.html">2/23/96 -- ACLU Names Two New Legislative Counsels</a><br>The American Civil Liberties Union has appointed two new
legislative counsels in its Washington National Office.

  
<P>
<a href="n022396b.html">2/23/96 -- Long Beach School Uniform Case Settled</a><br>An out-of-court settlement was reached Wednesday in the California school uniform
lawsuit.

  
<P>
<a href="n022396.html">2/23/96 -- **Media Advisory*** ACLU v Reno: Update </a><br>
 Government will refrain from pursuing Internet prosecution<br>
      Abortion speech restrictions, already acknowledged unconstitutional, not
addressed<br>
      ACLU hearing dates set for March 21 and 22 in Philadelphia

  
<P>
<a href="n021596b.html">2/15/96 -- Supreme Court to Review ACLU Challenge 
to Censorship Provisions of the 1992 Cable Act</a><br> February 21, the Supreme 
Court will hear arguments in the consolidated cases of  Denver Area 
Educational Telecommunications Consortium, Inc. (DAETC) and 
American Civil Liberties Union  v. FCC and the United States, and 
Alliance for Community Media v. FCC and the United States.
 <p>
<a href="n021596.html">2/15/96 -- Judge Grants Temporary Restraining Order on Indecency Provisions; 
ACLU Claims Partial Victory, But Warns Netizens to Beware</a><br>
 Judge Agrees with ACLU that vague "indecency" provisions are
unconstitutional<br>
 Denies TRO on "patently offensive" material<br>
 Denies TRO on Comstock law abortion provisions, asserting "no irreparable
harm"<br>
 Three-judge panel convened for a full hearing on the case  <p>
<a href="n021496.html">2/14/96 -- Alabama Judge Rebuffs State Attorney General and 
Clears the Way for Gay Students' Conference</a><br>A federal judge in Alabama today paved the way for a
lesbian and gay student's conference to take place this Friday, putting an
end to repeated efforts by state officials to cancel the meeting.
<p>
<a href="n021096.html">2/10/96 -- ACLU Criticizes Clinton for Signing Military 
              Budget Bill Barring Overseas Abortions; 
           Prepares to Challenge HIV Provisions in Court
</a><br>The American Civil Liberties Union today criticized President
Clinton for signing a military budget bill containing Republican-sponsored
provisions that would bar overseas abortions in military hospitals.  
<p>
  

<a href="n020996.html">2/9/96 -- ACLU Says Clinton is Right Not to Defend
  HIV Provisions in Military Budget Bill</a><br>The ACLU issues response to President Clinton's announcement today that he considers the provisions in the military budget bill 
 requiring the discharge of HIV-positive troops to be unconstitutional.
  
<P>

<a href="n020896c.html">2/8/96 --  School District Will Not Transfer Pat Lee,
 ACLU of Nevada and District Negotiate Settlement 
 to High School Censorship Case </a><br>The case of Pat Lee, a McQueen High student disciplined for
 publishing an underground newspaper, was settled on Wednesday, February 7.
  
<P>

<a href="n020896.html">2/8/96 -- **Media Advisory*** ACLU v Reno: Update </a><br>
 Judge Sets Date for Government to File Reply Brief<br>
      Government Agrees Not to Prosecute for 7 days<br>
      Government Concedes that Abortion Speech Restrictions Are Unconstitutional

  
<P>
<a href="n020896b.html">2/8/96 -- Why We Are Challenging the Communications Decency Act of the Telecommunications Reform Act of 1996</a><br>
The ACLU has filed ACLU v. Reno to stop the government from "gagging" free speech on the Internet.  The new telecommunications legislation extends the reach of the 19th-century Comstock Act, which long suppressed information about birth control and abortion, so that it will apply to the latest state-of-the-art communications technologies.  

<P>
<a href="n020796.html">2/7/96 --   Lawsuit Challenging Internet  Indecency' Provisions To be Filed As
Soon As Clinton Signs Legislation
</a><br>  Saying that its chilling effects would be
immediately felt throughout the online world, the American Civil Liberties
Union today announced plans to seek a temporary restraining order against the
"indecency" provisions of the telecommunications legislation <P>
<P>
<a href="n020696.html">2/6/96 --   ACLU Challenges North Clackamas School District's Policy of Censoring Student Speeches
</a><br>  The ACLU of Oregon  is representing Clackamas
High School senior Sarah Yearout in her challenge of a school district policy
that caused school officials to censor her student government campaign
speech.<p>
<a href="n020196b.html">2/1/96 --   ACLU and Americans United Sue Alabama Schools
on Church/State Violations</a><br> An array of religious activities occurring in Alabama public school districts unconstitutionally promote religion, violate religious liberty and ignore
over thirty years of established law.<P>
<a href="n020196.html">2/1/96 --   Statement of Maryland ACLU On Baltimore City Video Cameras: "We're Lobsters in Cold Water"</a><br> Baltimore City Mayor Kurt Schmoke announced
 his plan to install video cameras in a number of downtown business areas.<P>

<p>
<a href="n0201961.html">2/1/96 -- ACLU Denounces Passage of Telecom Bill
       and Prepares to Challenge Online Censorship Provisions</a><br>
Citing grave free speech and privacy concerns, the American Civil Liberties Union today denounced the passage of the Telecommunications Deregulation law, and announced immediate plans to file a lawsuit on behalf of more than a dozen plaintiffs... <p>
