<center>
<h1> ACLU Press Releases</h1>
</center>
<P>
<h3>March 1995</h3>

<a href="n033195a.html">3/31 -- ACLU Background Briefing: House to Consider Ominous Counter-Constitution Act
</a>
<br> Next Thursday, April 6th, the House Judiciary Committee will hold hearings on "International
     Terrorism: Threats and Responses." One piece of legislation under consideration will be the Clinton
     Administration's proposal, the so-called Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995.

<P>
<a href="n033195.html">3/31 -- The American Civil Liberties Union of Alabama
</a>
<br>The American Civil Liberties Union of Alabama today filed a lawsuit to stop religious practices led or initiated by
     judges in Alabama's courtrooms.

<P>
<a href="n033095a.html">3/30 -- Federal Judge Strikes Down "Don't Ask, Don't Tell" Six Lesbian and Gay Servicemembers Win Lawsuit
</a>
<br>In a major blow to the current law barring open lesbians and gay men from serving
     in the armed forces, a federal judge today ruled in favor of six servicemembers who sued the federal government
     in the first direct constitutional challenge to the so-called "Don't Ask, Don't Tell" law. 

<P>
<a href="n033095.html">3/30 -- ACLU, Lamda Win "Don't Ask, Don't Tell"
</a>
<br>Statement of Matthew Coles, Director National Lesbian and Gay Rights Project American Civil Liberties Union
<P>
<a href="n032995.html">3/29 -- ACLU Urges Internet Providers to Fight Censorship; Issues Open Letter Against Senate Proposal
</a>
<br>Saying that the U.S. Senate is heading toward approval of a bill that would violate the civil
     liberties of every present and future member of the online community, the American Civil Liberties Union today
     sent an open letter to online providers strongly urging them to wage a "full-scale fight" for the constitutional rights
     of online users. 
<P>
<a href="n032695.html">3/26 -- William Olds Announces Departure From Connecticut CLU
</a>
<br>William Olds, for 25 years executive director of the Connecticut Civil Liberties Union, has
     announced that he will be stepping down from that post on August 1 of this year. 

<P>
<a href="n032395.html">3/23 -- Montana ACLU Applauds Senate Reversal on Gay Registering
</a>
<br>The ACLU of Montana is pleased that the Montana Senate has reconsidered its earlier
     embarassing and extreme position relating to including gays and lesbians in their sex offender registration bill (HB
     214). 

<P>
<a href="n032295.html">3/22 -- Say What??!! 4:High School Students Speak Out At ACLU Student Conference Celebrating Freedom of Expression
</a>
<br>More than 700 high school students from all over northern California have signed up to attend the fourth annual
     "Say What??!! Students Celebrating Freedom of Expression Conference," organized by the Howard A. Friedman
     First Amendment Education Project of the ACLU of Northern California and the ACLU Berkeley Student
     Caucus. 
<P>
<a href="n032195.html">3/21 -- Paternalism and the Harkin-Bradley Bill: Proposal on Tobacco Advertising Would Violate the First Amendment
</a>
<br>The American Civil Liberties Union once again rejects as unconstitutional the legislation to limit the deductibility of
     tobacco advertising and promotion to be introduced today by Senators Tom Harkin of Iowa and Bill Bradley of
     New Jersey.
<P>
<a href="n031595b.html">3/15 -- ACLU Challenges San Diego's Curfew Law; Lawsuit Filed in Federal Court on Behalf of Teenagers, Parents
</a>
<br> Acting on behalf of thousands of law-abiding young people in San Diego, the American Civil
     Liberties Union of San Diego & Imperial Counties filed suit today in San Diego federal district court to challenge
     the City's juvenile curfew ordinance. 

<P>
<a href="n031595a.html">3/15 -- Statement of Linda Hills Executive Director ACLU Foundation of San Diego & Imperial Counties
</a>
<br>Acting on behalf of thousands of law-abiding young people in San Diego, the ACLU today filed suit in federal
     district court challenging the City of San Diego's juvenile curfew law. 
<P>
<a href="n031595.html">3/15 -- Statement of Jordan Budd Staff Counsel ACLU Foundation of San Diego & Imperial Counties
</a>
<br>In the first six months of the City's "aggressive" curfew enforcement program, almost 2,300 young people were
     arrested for curfew violations -- more than 1,300 more than during the same period the year before.
<P>
<a href="n031395a.html">3/13 -- Judge Denies California State's Request to Dismiss Prop. 187 Lawsuit; ACLU, MALDEF Trial to Start on September 5
</a>
<br> U.S. District Court Judge Mariana Pfaelzer has denied the state of California's motion to
     dismiss four federal lawsuits challenging Prop. 187, or to move the lawsuits to state court. Judge Pfaelzer set the
     trial date as September 5.
<P>
<a href="n031395.html">3/13 -- Mandatory AIDS Testing Ruled Unconstitutional in New Jersey
</a>
<br> Finding a recent mandatory HIV testing statute to be harmful rather than helpful to the victims of
     sexual assault, a New Jersey Superior Court has ruled that the statute is unconstitutional. 

<P>
<a href="n031295c.html">3/12 -- Ban on Gays in the Military Goes On Trial; 'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Faces Challenge in Brooklyn
</a>
<br>The trial in Able et al v. U.S.A., the first and only direct constitutional
     challenge to the government's current law barring lesbians and gay men from openly serving in the military, will
     begin Monday, March 13, in federal District Court in Brooklyn.
<P>
<a href="n031295b.html">3/12 -- American Civil Liberties Union Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund
</a>
<br>Filed in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York, Able v. USA challenges the constitutionality
     of the military's latest ban on open lesbian and gay service members, which was signed into law by President
     Clinton in 1993. 
<P>
<a href="n031295a.html">3/12 -- Statement of Matthew Coles, Director, ACLU National Lesbian and Gay Rights Project On the Challenge to "Don't Ask, Don't Tell" in Able v. USA
</a>
<br>"Tomorrow we will go to court on behalf of six ordinary, capable people who wish only to serve their country.
     But because of officially sanctioned government prejudice, they cannot be here today.
<P>
<a href="n031295.html">3/12 -- Statement of Beatrice Dohrn, Legal Director Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund
</a>
<br>Americans should be judged by what they do, not who they are. Able v. USA challenges one of the most
     sweeping, basic, government sponsored affronts to that principal.
<P>
<a href="n031095.html">3/10 -- Governor Weld 'Perpetrating Fraud' by Advocating Death Penalty; Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts Descries State Crime Proposals
</a>
<br>The Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts today accused Governor William Weld of a lack of
     sincerity about fighting crime and protecting police officers. 
<P>
<a href="n030695a.html">3/6 -- Mugging the Constitution, Part II Senate Proposal on Exclusionary Rule Even More Radical
</a>
<br>Going even further than the self-styled revolutionaries in the House of Representatives, the U.S. Senate is
     scheduled to begin hearings on the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Improvement Act of 1995.
<P>
<a href="n030695.html">3/6 -- Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund American Civil Liberties Union
</a>
<br>Trial Begins Monday, March 13 in Constitutional Challenge To Government's New Policy on Gays in the Military

<p>
<a href="n030395a.html">3/3 -- ACLU Asks Supreme Court to Hear Assisted Suicide Case; Michigan Case Had Been Filed On Behalf of Cancer Patients, Doctors
</a>
<br> Acting to protect personal rights and freedoms, the American Civil Liberties Union and the ACLU
     of Michigan said today that it would ask the U.S. Supreme Court to consider the constitutionality of the state's
     assisted suicide law. 

<P>
<a href="n030395.html">3/3 -- "One Down, Nine To Go" ACLU of Michigan Issues Dubious Honor to Seven Representatives
</a>
<br>Seven of Michigan's representatives to Congress have been honored by the American Civil
     Liberties Union of Michigan with the organization's "Your Home Used to be Your Castle" award.
<P>
<a href="n030295.html">3/2 -- ACLU, Lawyers Committee Win Injunction in Motor Voter Case; State Indicates An Appeal
</a>
<br>The ACLU of Northern and Southern California, the Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights of the San Francisco
     Bay Area and a coalition of other voting rights groups have won a permanent injunction in the lawsuit Voting
     Rights Coalition v. Wilson.
<P>
<a href="n030195.html">3/1 -- Supreme Court Justices Express Concern About Computer Privacy; Opinions Suggest Mounting Interest on Nation's Highest Court
</a>
<br>A majority of the justices of the U.S. Supreme Court, ruling in a criminal evidence case, today suggested that they
     had serious concerns about the potential invasion to individual privacy raised by the nation's increasing reliance on
     computer technology. 

