<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU in the Courts: GLBA v. Alabama</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>In the United States Court of Appeals<BR>For the
Eleventh Circuit</B></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">No. 96-6143</P>
<HR WIDTH="70%">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>GAY LESBIAN BISEXUAL ALLIANCE</B>, Plaintiff-Appellee,</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">versus</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>FREDERICK P. WHIDDON, in his official capacity as
President of the University of South Alabama; DALE T. ADAMS,	in his official
capacity as Dean of Students of the University of South Alabama</B>, Defendants,</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>JEFF SESSIONS, in his official capacity as ATTORNEY
GENERAL of the STATE OF ALABAMA,</B> Defendant-Appellant.</P>
<HR WIDTH="70%">
<P ALIGN="CENTER">On Appeal from the United States District Court for the
Middle District of Alabama</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>Brief of Appellee</B></P>
<HR>
<H4>STATEMENT REGARDING ORAL ARGUMENT</H4>
<P>Plaintiff-appellee respectfully seeks the opportunity for oral argument in
light of the significant constitutional law issues that are central to the
resolution of this appeal.  Appellee believes that colloquy between counsel and
the Court will facilitate its consideration of this matter.</P>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">TABLE OF CONTENTS</H4>
<P><B>STATEMENT REGARDING ORAL ARGUMENT</B></P>
<P><B>STATEMENT OF JURISDICTION</B></P>
<P><B>STATEMENT OF THE ISSUES</B></P>
<P><B>STATEMENT OF THE CASE</B></P>
<P>A. Statement of Proceedings and Disposition Below</P>
<P>B. Statement of Facts</P>
<P>1.  Section 16-1-28
</P>
<P>2.  The Enforcement of Section 16-1-28 Against GLBA
</P>
<P>C. The District Court's Decision </P>
<P>D. Standards of Review</P>
<P><B>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT</B></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>I. PLAINTIFF HAS STANDING TO CHALLENGE 16-1-28</B></P>
<P><B>II. SECTION 16-1-28 IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL ON ITS FACE AND  AS IT HAS BEEN
APPLIED TO GLBA</B></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>A. The Supreme Court's Decision in Rosenberger Determines the Outcome of
This Case </P>
<P>B. Section 16-1-28 is Unconstitutionally Vague and Overbroad</P>
<P>C. Section 16-1-28 Has Been Applied to GLBA in Violation of the Equal
Protection Clause</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>III.SECTION 16-1-28 IS NOT SUSCEPTIBLE TO A NARROWING CONSTRUCTION, NOR
CAN ANY PART OF IT BE SAVED THROUGH SEVERANCE</B></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>CONCLUSION</B></P>
<HR>
<H4>STATEMENT OF JURISDICTION</H4>
<P>The U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Alabama issued a final
decision on January 29, 1996.  This Court has appellate jurisdiction over
defendant-appellant Jeff Sessions' appeal from that decision pursuant to 28
U.S.C. &#167; 1291.  Subject matter jurisdiction over this 42 U.S.C. &#167; 1983
case to vindicate plaintiff-appellee's First and Fourteenth Amendment rights
exists under 28 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1331 and 1343(a)(3).</P>
<H4>STATEMENT OF THE ISSUES</H4>
<OL>
<LI>  Whether the standing of plaintiff-appellee Gay Lesbian Bisexual Alliance
(GLBA) to challenge Section 16-1-28 of the Alabama Education Code has been
established, especially given the defendant-appellant Attorney General's own
application of that statute to the detriment of GLBA?
</LI>
<LI>  Whether the district court correctly concluded that Section 16-1-28, both
on its face and as applied to GLBA, discriminates against expression and
association on the basis of viewpoint?
</LI>
<LI>  Whether the district court correctly held that Section 16-1-28, both on
its face and as applied to GLBA, violates the First and Fourteenth Amendments? 

</LI></OL>
<H4>STATEMENT OF THE CASE</H4>
<P>A. Statement of Proceedings and Disposition Below</P>
<P>Plaintiff-appellee GLBA, a student group at the University of South Alabama
in Mobile, filed the present challenge to Section 16-1-28 of the Alabama
Education Code on September 27, 1993.  The Complaint named the Attorney General
of the State of Alabama, then Jimmy Evans, and two officials at the University
of South Alabama, President Frederick P. Whiddon and Dean of Students Dale T.
Adams, as defendants in their official capacities.  GLBA alleged that Section
16-1-28, on its face and as applied, imposed impermissible content- and
viewpoint-based limitations on the freedom of expression and freedom of
association protected by the First Amendment.  R1-1-16 to 17 (first and second
causes of action).  The student group also alleged that the statute was
unconstitutionally vague and overbroad, and that defendants had targeted GLBA
and similar groups for enforcement of the law, in violation of the Equal
Protection Clause, because the groups were supportive of and associated with a
homosexual sexual orientation.  R1-1-17 to 19 (third and fourth causes of
action).  Defendants Whiddon and Adams answered the Complaint on October 20,
1993.  The Attorney General, after the district court's denial of his motion to
dismiss, answered on February 18, 1994.</P>
<P>At the suggestion of the district court, the parties agreed to submit the
case for final resolution on a joint written record, to be supplemented by
briefs and oral argument.  Following discovery, the Joint Record of two bound
document volumes and two deposition transcripts was filed with the district
court.  R1-24.  Both sides submitted &quot;pre-trial&quot; briefs and the
district court heard oral argument on June 17, 1994.  By memorandum opinion
dated January 29, 1996, the district court ruled &quot;that &#167; 16-1-28,
facially and as applied to GLBA, violates the first and fourteenth amendments.&quot;
 R2-45-2. </P>
<P>Only one of the three defendants, Attorney General Jeff Sessions, has
appealed from the district court's decision; his notice of appeal was filed on
February 5, 1996.  R2-48.  On February 8, Sessions moved in the district court
for a stay pending appeal of the ruling that Section 16-1-28 is facially
unconstitutional.  The Attorney General sought to use the statute either to stop
or to punish students participating in the upcoming Fifth Annual Lesbian, Gay
and Bisexual College Conference of the Southeastern United States, to be held
later in February at the University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa.  R2-55-3 to 5.  In
response to Sessions's motion, GLBA, whose members were to attend the Tuscaloosa
conference, moved for injunctive relief.  On February 13, 1996, the district
court denied the motion for a stay, ruling that Sessions had failed to establish
any of the four prerequisites for such &quot;'extraordinary relief.'&quot; 
R2-55-5 to 12.  The court also denied GLBA injunctive relief, after &quot;the
Attorney General ha[d] reassured the court that he will act in accordance with
the court's judgment of January 29 and this order as long as they remain in
effect.&quot;  R2-55-13.</P>
<P>B. Statement of Facts</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>1. Section 16-1-28</P>
<P>Alabama Education Code Section 16-1-28 provides that</P>
<P>(a)  No public funds or public facilities shall be used by any college</P>
<P>or university to, directly or indirectly, sanction, recognize, or support 
the activities or existence of any organization or group that fosters or 
promotes a lifestyle or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual   misconduct
laws of Sections 13A-6-63 to 13A-6-65, inclusive.</P>
<P>(b)  No organization or group that receives public funds or uses  public
facilities, directly or indirectly, at any college or university shall permit or
encourage its members or encourage other persons to engage in  any such unlawful
acts or provide information or materials that explain how  such acts may be
engaged in or performed.</P>
<P>(c)  This act shall not be construed to be a prior restraint of the first 
amendment protected speech.  It shall not apply to any organization or  group
whose activities are limited solely to the political advocacy of a  change in
the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws of this state.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Ala. Code &#167; 16-1-28.</P>
<P>The Alabama Legislature passed Section 16-1-28 in response to a controversy
at Auburn University, a public institution in Auburn, Alabama.  In 1990, Auburn
students had formed a new campus organization, the Auburn Gay and Lesbian

Association (AGLA).  In 1991, AGLA's application for permanent status as an
officially-recognized Auburn student group was rejected by the Auburn Student
Government Association because AGLA did &quot;not meet the idea[l]s entrusted to
the Student Senate on behalf of the students of Auburn[.]&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 1 at

82.  On January 7, 1992, however, the university administration overruled the
Student Government and recognized AGLA, R1-24-Vol. 1 at 80, providing it with
equal access to such things as meeting rooms and funding as other chartered
organizations.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 91-175 (examples of press coverage).  Despite
efforts to change its position by the Student Government, Auburn alumni, the
Rutherford Institute, and &quot;Students for a Healthy Auburn,&quot; the
university stood firm in its protection of AGLA's First Amendment rights. 
R1-24-Vol. 1 at 78, 81, 85-90.</P>
<P>On January 31, 1992, the Alabama Senate passed a resolution &quot;Expressing
Support of the Student Senate of the Student Government Association of Auburn
University,&quot; recognizing the &quot;courageous stand&quot; of the Auburn
Student Government in &quot;boldly object[ing]&quot; to &quot;the acceptance of
erotic life styles,&quot; and concluding</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>That the Senate of Alabama does not condone violations of the laws of the
State of Alabama, nor does it recognize an erotic life style, but rather
acknowledges that the State of Alabama is and resolves that it shall remain,
historically traditional in its views of the family, and that the State of
Alabama is a place where families can live and grow without being debased or
immoralized.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R1-24-Vol. 1 at 45-46.  On February 26, the House of Representatives passed
its own resolution, repeating much of the Senate resolution, but substituting &quot;homosexual
life style&quot; for &quot;erotic life style.&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 47-49.  On
that same day, both houses approved the bill that would become Section 16-1-28
(H. 454) and it was signed into law on May 14, 1992.  Id.</P>
<P>In its session law form, Section 16-1-28 included the following explanatory
preamble:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>To prohibit any college or university from spending public funds or  using
public facilities, directly or indirectly, to sanction, recognize, or  support
any group that promotes a lifestyle or actions prohibited by the  sodomy and
sexual misconduct laws; to prohibit any group from permitting  or encouraging
its members or others to engage in or provide materials on  how to engage in the
lifestyle or actions.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R1-24-Vol. 1 at 43.  </P>
<P>Although Section 16-1-28 is broadly and vaguely worded, its purpose of
eliminating gay and lesbian student groups(1) from Alabama college campuses has
never been in doubt and has been conceded by defendants.  All contemporaneous
accounts, including legislators' statements, describe H. 454 as a measure
designed to restrict gay and lesbian student groups such as AGLA.  R1-24-Vol. 1
at 192-97.(2)  As defendant Adams testified, &quot;This law was passed, and I
think it was understood to be passed, in direct opposition to any homosexual
group having access to a campus or funds.&quot;  R1-24-Adams Dep. at [75?]; see
also id. at 31, 36-37, 93-94.  Attorney General Evans concurred, stating that he
knew of no &quot;problem&quot; other than the &quot;controversy which was the
press item which surrounded, I assume, the passage of this legislation&quot; to
which Section 16-1-28 might be addressed.  R1-24-Evans. Dep. at 15; see also
Brief of Appellant at [6?].</P>
<P>Under part (a), a public school could not allow any &quot;group that fosters
or promotes a lifestyle or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual
misconduct laws&quot; to, for example, hold a forum (no matter what the topic)
in a campus auditorium, become an officially-recognized student group, or
directly or indirectly benefit from public funds.  Section 16-1-28(a), by
contrast, places no restrictions on groups that discourage or condemn the &quot;lifestyle
or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws.&quot;</P>
<P>While that much is clear, the language of part (a) provides little guidance
as to what kind of organization might be deemed to &quot;foster[] or promote[] a
lifestyle or actions&quot; prohibited by Alabama Criminal Code sections 13A-6-63
through 13A-6-65.  Those criminal provisions outlaw, inter alia, forcible acts
of &quot;deviate sexual intercourse;&quot; such acts with a minor or someone
incapable of consent; vaginal intercourse under certain circumstances, including
where the consent of a female is obtained through the use of any fraud or
artifice by the male (Section 13A-6-65(a)(1)); and consensual oral or anal
intercourse between any two unmarried persons of the same or of different
genders (Section 13A-6-65(a)(3)).  </P>
<P>Nowhere in the sodomy or sexual misconduct laws is a &quot;lifestyle&quot;
prohibited.  Lifestyle's tie to the &quot;homosexual lifestyle&quot; and the gay
and lesbian student group condemned in the legislature's prior resolutions,
however, indicates that at least such gay-positive student organizations are
targeted by Section 16-1-28.(3)  The defendant-appellant Attorney General has
repeatedly affirmed this reading of part (a), first in the Attorney General's
opinion dated July 29, 1993, and later, for example, at the oral argument below.
 R1-24-Vol. 1 at 210-11; R3-21 and 35.</P>
<P>Under part (b) of Section 16-1-28, if a group at some point receives public
funds or uses public facilities, it shall not (1) &quot;permit or encourage its
members or encourage other persons to engage in any such unlawful acts&quot;  --
referring to the &quot;lifestyle or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual
misconduct law&quot; specified in part (a); or (2) &quot;permit or encourage its
members or encourage other persons to .  .  . provide information or materials
that explain how such acts may be engaged in or performed.&quot;  The
organizations, however, are free to discourage people from &quot;engag[ing] in
any such unlawful acts&quot; or from &quot;explaining how such acts may be
engaged in or performed.&quot;</P>
<P>The first sentence of part (c) purports to illuminate the earlier
subsections, stating that the law &quot;shall not be construed to be a prior
restraint of the first amendment protected speech.&quot;  Simply declaring that
to be so, however, cannot deprive federal courts of the obligation to read the
statute and to apply First Amendment doctrine themselves.  Governing First
Amendment precedent, moreover, has already held a university's refusal to
recognize a student group and allow its activities on campus to be a form of
prior restraint.  See Widmar v. Vincent, 454 U.S. 263, 267 n.5 (1981).</P>
<P>The second sentence of part (c) excludes from Section 16-1-28 one narrow
category of organization:  any group &quot;whose activities are limited solely
to the political advocacy of a change in the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws
of this state.&quot;  Such an exception is virtually useless for student groups
formed and seeking the benefits of chartered status at Alabama universities.  As
illustrated by GLBA, see infra, those groups serve students and educational
purposes at their respective schools, rather than focusing on legislative change
in the Montgomery statehouse.</P>
<P>2. The Enforcement of Section 16-1-28 Against GLBA</P>
<P>The University of South Alabama believes that diverse student groups are
important to its educational mission.  R2-45-6 (District Court Opinion,
hereinafter &quot;Dt. Ct. Op.&quot;); R1-24-Vol. 2 at 481, 483.  Dean Adams
testified that &quot;outside of the classroom activities&quot; are &quot;an
opportunity for our students to encounter different viewpoints, ideas,
perspectives.&quot; R1-24-Adams Dep. at 13.  &quot;There are over 100 registered
student organizations at the university.&quot;  R2-45-6 (Dt. Ct. Op.) 
Registered student group enjoy various benefits:  free use of the meeting rooms
and conference space at the University Center; priority use of those and other
facilities over non-university-affiliated organizations; free on-campus banking
services; eligibility for direct university funding awarded by the USA-SGA from
student activity fees; etc.  R1-24-Vol. 2 at 506, 489, 484-85.  </P>
<P>Among the dozens of student organizations at the University, GLBA has been
the only group subject to enforcement of Section 16-1-28.  The group is an
educational, social, political and cultural organization (R2-45-6 (Dt. Ct. Op.);
</P>
<P>R1-24-Vol. 1 at 213-16) open to all members of the USA community,
heterosexual as well as gay or bisexual, but providing a singularly supportive
environment for gay, lesbian and bisexual students.  Id.  GLBA is &quot;an open
forum where current political issues can be discussed&quot; and an organization
that works &quot;to further basic human rights and awareness within the
university,&quot; including working &quot;fervently to combat homophobia.&quot; 

R1-24-Vol. 2 at 316-17; R1-24-Vol. 1 at 213.  See also R2-45-6 (Dt. Ct. Op.)</P>
<P>In addition to specifically gay/bisexual issues, GLBA focuses on AIDS
awareness and education, both among its membership and in its programs for
others.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 214-215.  The group meets weekly on campus, with GLBA
members also visiting classes and participating in forums to educate and to
advance GLBA's views, and the group itself sponsoring events for the entire
university community.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 215-16.  The court further found that,
according to the defendant Dean of Students' own testimony,</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>the GLBA has made a contribution to the university in the areas of HIV
awareness and AIDS education, support for gay, lesbian, and bisexual students,
and in educating other students, faculty, and staff about issues pertaining to
homosexual life.  </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R2-45-7 (Dt. Ct. Op.)  GLBA has never had as one of its purposes the goal of
bringing about violations of any of the criminal laws of Alabama, nor has it
lobbied the state legislature for a repeal of the consensual sexual misconduct
law or any other criminal statute.  Id.</P>
<P>From the summer of 1992 until the district court's judgment against them,
the defendants relied on Section 16-1-28 to (1) render on-campus banking
facilities useless for GLBA; (2) disqualify GLBA from receiving USA-SGA funding,
despite the student government having voted to fund the group; (3) convene a &quot;fact-finding
committee&quot; to investigate GLBA and its members; and (4) treat GLBA,
uniquely, as a second-class citizen among the many organizations that use USA
facilities and are supported by university funds.  The history of Section
16-1-28's enforcement is exhaustively treated in Plaintiff's Brief on the Merits
below, see R1-25-20 to 44, and is accurately reflected in the district court's
independent, well-referenced findings of fact, see R2-45-6 to 11.  Here,
plaintiff-appellant will simply touch upon the important facts for purposes of
this appeal.</P>
<P>In June 1992, GLBA requested an on-campus bank account.  R1-24-Vol. 2 at
327.  Although defendant Adams's initial reaction was to grant this routine
request, he consulted with university counsel.  R1-24-Vol. 2 at 328.  GLBA
President Wilson testified that  </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The school effectively denied our request by informing us that, at that
time, such an account would be useless or even detrimental to our financial
situation, given the school's interpretation of Section 16-1-28 as possibly
relating to GLBA.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R1-24-Vol. 1 at 22; see also R1-24-Adams Dep. at 48-49, 53-54; R2-45-8 (Dt.
Ct. Op.) (&quot;the university effectively denied GLBA an on-campus bank
account.&quot;)  Dean Adams did not advise any other student group that because
of Section 16-1-28 its money, if put in an on-campus account, might become
unavailable.  R1-24-Adams Dep. at 54.  Because the university's interpretation
of the statute deprived GLBA of the benefit of on-campus banking, the group was
forced to pay the fees and endure the inconvenience of always dealing with a
commercial bank.  R1-24-Vol. 2 at 242, 399, 484-85; R1-24-Adams Dep. at 23-25.</P>
<P>As early as the late spring or summer of 1992, USA officials had concluded
that &quot;since the bill was vague to us and we did not really understand some
of the words in it that we were going to have to get an attorney general's
opinion sooner or later on what it meant.&quot;  R1-24-Adams Dep. at 45-46.  See
also R2-45-8 to 9 (Dt. Ct. Op.)  In the meantime, GLBA would not be funded,
while funding of all other groups, no matter what the content of their programs
or the views expressed by their members, would proceed normally.  Id. at 46-47 &amp;
92-93; R2-45-8 (Dt. Ct. Op.) (GLBA has also been denied funding.&quot;)  Until
the resolution of this suit below, it continued to be USA's position that
Section 16-1-28 and the need to enforce its provisions, however unclear, stood
in the way of allowing public funds to go to GLBA.  See, e.g., R1-24-Vol. 2 at
449; R1-24-Adams Dep. at 70-71, 97; R1-24-Vol. 1 at 246, 231-32.</P>
<P>GLBA, however, sought funding so that it could increase its contributions to
and visibility on the campus.  In the first quarter of 1993, for example, the
group submitted a budget request of $884 to the USA-SGA, with approximately $625
budgeted to bring in a guest speaker for a program on the legal rights of gay
men, lesbians and people with HIV disease.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 222-24, Vol.2 at
382-84.  The SGA's executive council preliminarily approved GLBA's request for
funding the speaker, allocating $651 to the group.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 222, Vol. 2
at 384.  Before the full SGA could meet on the request, Dean Adams ended any
chance for funding by directing &quot;the SGA to table the budget request until
the request could be reviewed by the Attorney General.&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 1 at
222-23; R1-24-Adams Dep. at 69-70; R1-24-Vol. 2 at 396.  GLBA was forced by the
university's enforcement of Section 16-1-28 to cancel its plans for the
out-of-town speaker on legal issues, who has never subsequently appeared on the
USA campus.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 224.</P>
<P>In Spring Quarter 1993, the group submitted a budget request for $720, with
the main planned event being a GLBA-sponsored speech by a scholar from Emory
University.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 224-25.  The USA-SGA voted an appropriation of $570
to GLBA to pay for, among other things, the scheduled speaker, for the student
government &quot;believed that the GLBA should receive funding, notwithstanding
Section 16-1-28&quot; because of the worth of its planned educational programs. 
R1-24-Vol. 1 at 225, Vol. 2 at 448.  Dean Adams, however, made clear to the SGA
that he would not be in a position to sign off on any actual funding going to
GLBA until he received guidance from the Attorney General.  R1-24-Adams Dep.
76-77.  He also told GLBA that its &quot;funding will be held up until we
receive approval from the Attorney General.&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 2 at 449.  GLBA
was still intent upon sponsoring the Emory speaker, but had to cancel its plans
because of the Section 16-1-28 block on funds.  R1-24-14 to 16.  At the close of
the Spring Quarter, Dean Adams continued to string GLBA along, writing the
group's president, &quot;We are still waiting for that opinion.&quot; 
R1-24-Vol. 2 at 452.</P>
<P>The Attorney General, responding to a request from defendant Whiddon dated
February 12, 1993, R1-24-Vol. 1 at 198, issued his opinion on funding GLBA in
late July of that year.  The two-page opinion merely quoted a prior Attorney
General's opinion, quoted part (a) of Section 16-1-28, and answered &quot;in the
negative&quot; Whiddon's inquiry as to whether GLBA could receive USA-SGA funds
without violating the statute.  R1-24-21-11; R2-45-9 to 10 (Dt. Ct. Op.)  The
opinion provided no reference to or analysis of any aspects of GLBA that caused
it to assertedly run of afoul of Section 16-1-28, nor did the opinion point to
exactly what provision in part (a) of the law was implicated by GLBA's
activities.  Id.</P>
<P>Although the Attorney General had firmly opined that GLBA functioned in some
way contrary to Section 16-1-28's restrictions, USA then decided to invent  its
own enforcement process for the statute and to establish an &quot;ad hoc
fact-finding committee&quot; that would conduct interviews with GLBA members and
&quot;any others&quot; to determine if the group had &quot;fostered or promoted
a life-style or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws.&quot;
 R1-24-Vol. 1 at 455-56 &amp; R1-24-Vol. 2 at 238, 240; R2-45-10 (Dt. Ct. Op.) 
Adams told GLBA that &quot;[b]ased on this group's finding we will determine
your eligibility for funding,&quot; but more pointedly told the committee that
if GLBA &quot;violated [Section 16-1-28], they could lose their registration&quot;
altogether.  Id.  </P>
<P>As the defendants concede, there are no particular facts about GLBA's
activities that caused the enforcement of Section 16-1-28 against the group. 
Rather, Section 16-1-28 was read to relate to this gay and lesbian student
group, and only this group, at USA because it was the controversy about such a
group at Auburn that had triggered the legislation.  R1-24-Adams Dep. at 36-37,
74-75, 93-94; R1-24-Evans Dep. at 24-25, 26-31; R2-45-16  (Dt. Ct. Op.)  Indeed,
the defendants have trouble even explaining what is prohibited by the statute,
let alone how GLBA contravened its prohibitions.  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 249-50, 267;
R1-24-Evans Dep. at 16-17, 29, 31.</P>
<P>Yet, simply because GLBA is a group supportive of homosexuals, Section
16-1-28 has worked to its significant detriment.  The district court found, in
sum, that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>as a result of the enforcement of &#167; 16-1-28, GLBA has been denied
on-campus banking facilities, disqualified from receiving funding, and subjected
to an intrusive and highly personal fact-finding investigation.  In addition,
although the university has not prevented GLBA from meeting in campus facilities
or from being recognized as an official student group, the group is still
considered by the Attorney General and university officials as falling within
the prohibitions of &#167; 16-1-28 and thus [also] not entitled to use
university facilities.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R2-45-10 to 11.  &quot;These actions have hindered GLBA's ability to
function as a student group, to sponsor events and speakers, and to attract new
and maintain old members.&quot;  R2-45-10.  </P>
<P>C. The District Court's Decision </P>
<P>Examining the challenged statute, the district court concluded that  Section
16-1-28, throughout all three of its sections, discriminates on the basis of
viewpoint.  R2-45-13 to 15.  Under subsection (a), for example, the court
emphasized that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>State colleges and universities, although making their facilities and funds
available to various and differing student organizations to convey their own
messages, must silence the expression of one, and only one, viewpoint.  This is
self-evident from the plain language of the statute.  The statute prohibits only
those groups that &quot;foster&quot; and &quot;promote&quot; a &quot;lifestyle
or actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws&quot; from using
public funds and facilities; groups that &quot;oppose&quot; such &quot;lifestyle
or actions&quot; would not fall within its prohibition.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R2-45-13.</P>
<P>As the lower court explained, the &quot;naked viewpoint discrimination,&quot;
R2-45-13, that is obvious from the statute's language &quot;is reinforced by the
history of &#167; 16-1-28.&quot;  R2-45-15.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The statute was passed in the wake of the State Legislature's displeasure
with the decision of Auburn University to allow a group addressing homosexual
issues to be formed on campus.  . . .  And the &quot;lifestyle&quot; condemned
in the statute clearly refers to the &quot;homosexual lifestyle&quot; condemned
in the resolution passed by the State House just before the introduction of the
legislation that would become the statute.  . . .  This history reflects an open
effort by the State  Legislature to limit the sexuality discussion in
institutions of higher learning to only one viewpoint:  that of heterosexual
people.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>R2-45-16.  As the district court noted, &quot;it is undisputed that the
statute is intended to target only speech concerning issues of homosexuality,&quot;
R2-14 n.37, and that the law was intended to bar &quot;'gay and lesbian student
organizations at Alabama's public colleges and universities,'&quot; R2-16 n.40.</P>
<P>The court held that Section 16-1-28 violates the First Amendment just as the
university regulation did in Rosenberger v. Rector and Visitors of the
University of Virginia, [cite].  Once the government has opened a limited public
forum, such as the public funds and public facilities available to aid
expression by student groups on university campuses, &quot;'the State . . . may
not . . . discriminate against speech on the basis of its viewpoint.'&quot; 
R2-45-12 (quoting Rosenberger).  Summarizing and applying Rosenberger, the
district court concluded:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>[T]he danger to free speech . . . &quot;is especially real in the University
setting, where the State acts against a background and tradition of thought and
experiment that is at the center of our intellectual and philosophic tradition. 
. . .  For the University, by regulation, to cast disapproval on particular
viewpoints of its students risks the suppression of free speech and creative
inquiry in one of the vital centers for the nation's intellectual life, its
college and university campuses.&quot;  [Rosenberger], 115 S.Ct. at 2520.  The
[Supreme] Court concluded that, having made funds available to varied and
differing student organizations &quot;to convey their own messages, the
University may not silence the expression of selected viewpoints.&quot;  Id. . .
. at 2519.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Section 16-1-28 similarly violates the first amendment.</P>
<P>R2-45-12 to 13.</P>
<P>In addition to ruling that the whole of Section 16-1-28 constitutes
impermissible viewpoint discrimination, the court held that subsection (b) &quot;violates
associational rights as well,&quot; because a group that fails to exclude
certain members &quot;would be guilty of violation of the statute merely by
association with [such a] member.&quot;  R2-45-14 n.38. </P>
<P>The court rejected defendants' arguments that Section 16-1-28 was an &quot;inchoate
criminal statute&quot; that constitutionally addressed the advocacy of criminal
conduct.  The court wrote, &quot;Section 16-1-28 . . . is not limited to
advocacy 'directed to inciting or producing imminent lawless action and . . .
likely to incite or produce such action.'  Brandenburg [v. Ohio], 395 U.S. at
447 . . . .  Indeed, it attempts to draw within its reach even a 'lifestyle,'
which in some instances could require little more than a frame of mind.&quot; 
R2-45-22 to 23.  Thus, Section 16-1-28 fails to draw the &quot;'critical line'&quot;
necessary to ever support the statute as a measure not limiting protected speech
but instead addressing criminal conduct.  R2-45-22 (quoting Healy v. James, 408
U.S. 169, 188 (1972)).</P>
<P>Finally, the district court &quot;agree[d] with GLBA&quot; that Section
16-1-28 &quot;is unconstitutionally vague and overbroad&quot; but declined
formally to reach those claims, since it had already struck down the entire
statute as an impermissible, viewpoint-based limitation on expression and
association.  The court also declined to reach GLBA's equal protection claim.  A
declaratory judgment invalidating Section 16-1-28 was entered on January 29,
1996.  The district court retained jurisdiction &quot;should an injunction or
other supplemental relief become necessary.&quot;  R2-46. </P>
<P>D. Standards of Review</P>
<P>The district court's findings of fact &quot;shall not be set aside unless
clearly erroneous.&quot;  Fed. R. Civ. P. 52(a).  See Anderson v. City of
Bessemer, 470 U.S. 564, 573-74 (1985).  The constitutional standards that govern
plaintiff's claims and the application of those standards to the record are
reviewed by this court de novo.  Bose Corp. v. Consumers Union of United States,
Inc., 466 U.S. 485 (1985); Waldrop v. Southern Co. Services, Inc., 24 F.3d 152
(11th Cir. 1994).</P>
<H4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT</H4>
<P>The University of South Alabama provides facilities and funds so that
student groups may meet and communicate their views amongst themselves and to
the campus at large.  The University has prohibited one group -- GLBA -- from
receiving funds based on Alabama Education Code Section 16-1-28.  The statute
prohibits public colleges and universities from providing facilities or funds to
groups that &quot;foster&quot; or &quot;promote&quot; a &quot;lifestyle or
actions prohibited by the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws,&quot; or whose
members &quot;encourage . . . such unlawful acts or provide information or
materials that explain how such acts may be engaged in or performed.&quot; 
Section 16-1-28.  The Attorney General has determined that the statute applies
to GLBA and the University has denied GLBA funding and initiated an
investigation into the group's members.  (Dt. Ct. Op.) R2-45-__.  GLBA has
standing to challenge the constitutionality of Section 16-1-28 because of the
defendants' enforcement of the statute against the group as well as because of
the statute's chilling effect on expression and association.  See Secretary of
State of Maryland v. J.H. Munson Co., 467 U.S. 947, 956-58 (1984).  </P>
<P>In Rosenberger v. Rector and Visitors of the University of Virginia, 515
U.S. ___, 135 L.Ed.2d 700, 715 (1995), the Supreme Court held unconstitutional a
public university's viewpoint-based denial of funding to a student group. 
Alabama Code Section 16-1-28 and its application by the defendants in this
action to GLBA are similarly unconstitutional because they &quot;select[] for
disfavored treatment&quot; communication that is positive about homosexuality. 
Rosenberger, 135 L.Ed.2d at ___.  The district court correctly concluded that
because the statute punishes speech so far beyond that &quot;directed to
inciting imminent lawlessness,&quot; it cannot be considered to be properly
limited to unprotected expression.  See Brandenburg v. Ohio, 395 U.S. 444
(1969). </P>
<P>In addition, the statute covers so much protected speech that it is
unconstitutionally overbroad; at the same time, it is also unconstitutionally
vague in its failure to specify the types of expression and association it
covers.  See Grayned v. City of Rockford, 408 U.S. 104, 108-09 (1972); Gooding
v. Wilson, 405 U.S. 518, 522 (1972).  The defendants' application of Section
16-1-28 to GLBA also violates the group members' rights to equal protection, for
it disfavors them out of pure animosity.  See Romer v. Evans, 116 S.Ct. 1620
(1996).  For all of these reasons Section 16-1-28 and its application to GLBA
are unconstitutional. </P>
<H4>I. PLAINTIFF HAS STANDING TO CHALLENGE SECTION 16-1-28</H4>
<P>To invoke the jurisdiction of a federal court, a plaintiff must show injury
as a result of the challenged government regulation or conduct and that it is
likely that the injury will be redressed by a favorable judgment.  Northeastern
Fla. Gen. Contractors v. City of Jacksonville, 508 U.S. 656, 663-64 (1993). 
When a statute is actually enforced, there is &quot;little question&quot; that
it causes injury that a judgment preventing further enforcement will redress. 
Lujan v. Defenders of Wildlife, 504 U.S. 555, 561-62 (1992).  See also Larson v.
Valente, 456 U.S. 228, 241, (1982) (finding injury, causation and redressability
where state attempted to enforce statute against plaintiff).  </P>
<P>Alabama Education Code Section 16-1-28 has been enforced against GLBA.  As
the district court found, in June of 1992 the University denied GLBA an
on-campus bank account, forcing it to go to a commercial bank, pay commercial
fees and forego the advantage of making on-campus money transfers.  (Dt. Ct.
Op.) R2-45-8.  In July of 1993 the Attorney General issued an opinion stating
that GLBA could not be funded by the University without violating Section
16-1-28.  (Dt. Ct. Op.) R2-45-10.  Finally, the district court found, the
University launched an &quot;investigation into the lives of group members
[that] affected GLBA's ability to maintain and increase its membership.&quot; 
(Dt. Ct. Op.) R2-45-10.  The district court concluded that &quot;the defendants'
actions have hindered GLBA's ability to function as a student group, to sponsor
events and speakers and to attract new and maintain old members.&quot;  (Dt. Ct.
Op.) R2-45-10. </P>
<P>These harms were redressed by the district court's judgment in favor of GLBA
declaring the statute unconstitutional.  On appeal, the Attorney General
contests GLBA's standing to challenge Section 16-1-28, claiming that the actions
of the University as found by the district court below &quot;quite simply never
occurred,&quot; characterizing the injuries to GLBA as non-existent or
self-inflicted.  Appellant's Br. at 21-22.  The district court rejected this
view of the facts, and the Attorney General points to no evidence that would
begin to prove the district court's findings to be clearly erroneous.  See
Anderson v. City of Bessemer, 470 U.S. 564, 573-74 (1985).  By attempting to
relitigate the facts on appeal he only highlights the firm foundation of the
district court's findings: (1) when he points to the fact that a speaker who was
the subject of one of GLBA's funding requests was eventually brought to campus
by another group he only underscores that Section 16-1-28 was enforced to
prevent the funding of GLBA to bring that speaker to campus; and (2) his
suggestion that the denial of a campus bank account to GLBA was based on a
policy that funds in such accounts can't be used for unlawful activities only
underscores that Section 16-1-28 has worked to GLBA's detriment.</P>
<P>GLBA also suffers injury from the existence of the law itself, for its
members have &quot;an actual and well-founded fear that the law will be enforced
against them,&quot; both with regard to the type of funding decisions that have
already been made as well as with regard to the very existence of GLBA as a
student group.  Virginia v. American Booksellers Ass'n, Inc.,484 U.S. 383, 393
(1988).  The ability to challenge laws that restrict speech and expression is
especially important because of the special danger of &quot;self-censorship; a
harm that can be realized even without an actual prosecution.&quot;  Id. 
Because GLBA &quot;has suffered both threatened and actual injury as a result of
the statute,&quot; Secretary of State of Maryland v. J.H. Munson Co., 467 U.S.
947, 954-55 (1984), its standing to challenge the constitutionality of Section
16-1-28 is firmly established. </P>
<H4>II. SECTION 16-1-28 IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL ON ITS FACE AND AS IT HAS BEEN
APPLIED TO GLBA</H4>
<P>Universities are &quot;vital centers for the nation's intellectual life,&quot;

making the &quot;danger [ ] to speech from the chilling of individual thought
and expression . . . especially real in the University setting[.]&quot; 
Rosenberger v. Rectors and Visitors of the University of Virginia, 132 L.Ed.2d
700, 719 (1995).(4)  Thus, as the University of South Alabama itself has
recognized, the safeguarding of First Amendment freedoms is especially important
in this context.  See, e.g., Shelton v. Tucker, 364 U.S. 479, 487 (1960); Sweezy
v. New Hampshire, 354 U.S. 234, 250 (1957).  In Keyishian v. Board of Regents of
New York, 385 U.S. 589, 603 (1967), the Court explained,</P>
<P>The Nation's future depends upon leaders trained through wide exposure to
that robust exchange of ideas which discovers truth &quot;out of a multitude of
tongues, [rather] than through any kind of authoritative selection.&quot; 
United States v. Associated Press, 52 F. Supp. 362, 372.</P>
<P>Because Section 16-1-28 focuses on the university environment, it calls for
the strict application of free expression and free association principles to
test its constitutionality.</P>
<P>A. The Supreme Court's Decision in Rosenberger Determines the Outcome of
This Case</P>
<P>The district court below correctly centered its holding on the recent
Supreme Court decision in Rosenberger v. Rector and Visitors of the University
of Virginia, 135 L.Ed.2d 700 (1995).  See R2-45-11 (Dt. Ct. Op.) (&quot;The
outcome of this case is significantly guided, if not determined, by the recent
opinion of the Supreme Court in Rosenberger[.]&quot;)  That case concerned a
student group at the University of Virginia that published a newspaper with a
Christian religious editorial perspective.  The activity funds generally
available to student groups were denied to the petitioner, based on the
religious editorial perspective of the newspaper.  </P>
<P>The Supreme Court held that the denial was viewpoint-based and therefore
violates the First Amendment.(5)  The Court reaffirmed that &quot;[d]iscrimination
against speech because of its message is presumed to be unconstitutional&quot;
and explained that &quot;the violation of the First Amendment is all the more
blatant&quot; when the &quot;government targets not subject matter but
particular views taken by speakers on a subject[.]&quot;  Id. at ___ (&quot;[v]iewpoint
discrimination is thus an egregious form of content discrimination.&quot;)  The
Court made the impermissibility of viewpoint-based restrictions explicit: &quot;the
government must abstain from regulating speech when the specific motivating
ideology or the opinion or perspective of the speaker is the rationale for the
restriction.&quot;  Id. at ___.  Having opened a limited public forum for
expression, the government can not exclude unpopular viewpoints from that forum.
 Id. at ___.  </P>
<P>The Court held that the university's distribution of funds to student groups
creates a limited public forum for expression just as the provision of
university facilities does, and the same prohibition against
viewpoint-discrimination applies.  Id. at 716.  Finally, the Court cited the
university context as requiring even greater scrutiny of restrictions on speech.
 Id. at ___.(6)    </P>
<P>Like the restrictions on student expression in Rosenberger, Section 16-1-28
and its application to GLBA are unconstitutional.  The University provides
facilities and funding to foster expression and association by a wide range of
student organizations.  Parts (a) and (b) of Section 16-1-28 both restrict
constitutionally-protected expression and association in those fora.  See supra
at __.  The interference with these protected activities takes three different
forms, each of which is an injury of constitutional significance:  denial of
official recognition (as in Healy); denial of use of campus facilities (as in
Widmar); and denial of student activity funds (as in Rosenberger).  </P>
<P>The restrictions imposed by Section 16-1-28 are unequivocally viewpoint
based.  Under part (a), no group can have any presence on a public university
campus if it is deemed to &quot;foster[] or promote a lifestyle or actions
prohibited by the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws.&quot;  In contrast, if a
group has a viewpoint that discourages such a &quot;lifestyle or actions&quot;
its activities are not restricted by the statute.  Part (b) mandates that a
student group using university facilities or funds cannot &quot;encourage its
members or other persons to . . . provide information or materials that explain
how such acts may be engaged in[.]&quot; On the other hand, a group expressing a
viewpoint discouraging the provision of such information is not covered by the
statute and left free to exercise its First Amendment rights on campus.  </P>
<P>Thus, under part (a), a fraternity might be thrown off campus because the
state determined that its culture and its social rituals &quot;foster[ed] and
promot[ed]&quot; men obtaining consent for vaginal intercourse through fraud or
artifice (punishable under the state's sexual misconduct law section
13A-6-65(a)(1)), or &quot;foster[ed] or promot[ed]&quot; unmarried couples
participating in consensual oral sex (punishable under the state's sexual
misconduct law section 13A-6-65(a)(3)).  Likewise, a college chapter of the ACLU
could well be implicated under part (a) because of the organization's position
that all private consensual sexual activity among adults is constitutionally
protected.  On the other hand, a conservative political group that affirmatively
discouraged any form of premarital sex could continue to use university
facilities and funds.  </P>
<P>Under part (b), a student organization that invited university medical staff
to a meeting to educate its members about preventing sexually transmitted
diseases could be barred from using campus facilities for any purpose at all if
a physician at that meeting provided accurate information about sexual behaviors
to the students.  In contrast, a student group that asked a religious speaker to
lecture on the immorality of discussing sexual acts, without indicating &quot;how
such acts may be engaged in,&quot; would not be subject to the statute.  </P>
<P>The University and the Attorney General have applied Section 16-1-28 in a
manner that disadvantages GLBA based on the identities and perspectives of its
members.  As the district court below found, they admittedly and intentionally
singled GLBA out for differential treatment because it is a gay/lesbian/bisexual
group.  See supra __.  While GLBA remained ineligible for funding, other
registered student organizations obtained money for social events or for
bringing speakers of special interest to campus.  Yet Section 16-1-28 was only
enforced against GLBA.  The fact that funding for a speaker sought by GLBA was
denied to the group and given to a different group to bring the same speaker to
campus is the plainest demonstration that GLBA has been denied the opportunity
to exercise its First Amendment rights as other, non-gay groups on campus are
permitted.(7)  </P>
<P>This case presents even greater offense to the First Amendment than
Rosenberger because here, the very purpose of the state regulation is the
suppression of a viewpoint perceived to be &quot;dangerous&quot; or &quot;unhealthy.&quot;
 Through its resolutions and the chain of events leading up to Section 16-1-28,
the Alabama legislature has made clear that its goal here was to ensure that
colleges and universities in the state would not &quot;accept[] the homosexual
life style&quot; by supporting student groups identified with that &quot;life
style.&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 47-49.  (House resolution).  The House and Senate
both identified that &quot;lifestyle&quot; as a threat to &quot;the family&quot;
and to &quot;the State of Alabama . . . a place where families can live and grow
without being debased or immoralized.&quot;  R1-24-Vol. 1 at 45-49.  Because the
restrictions are directed at unpopular speech there can be no question as to its
constitutional infirmity.  See, e.g., Healy v. James, 408 U.S. 169, 187-88
(1972) (&quot;The College, acting here as an instrumentality of the State, may
not restrict speech or association simply because it finds the views expressed
by any group to be abhorrent.&quot;); Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. 397, 414 (1989)
(&quot;If there is a bedrock principle underlying the First Amendment, it is
that the Government may not prohibit the expression of an idea simply because
society finds the idea itself offensive or disagreeable.&quot;); Regan, 461 U.S.
at 548 (government may not &quot;discriminate invidiously in its subsidies in
such a way as to &quot;aim at the suppression of dangerous ideas.'&quot;) </P>
<P>The Attorney General argues that there is a distinction between allowing
student groups access to facilities and access to funds.  Appellant's Br. At 40.
 The Supreme Court, however, specifically rejected such a distinction in
Rosenberger, holding funding of student groups to be a limited public forum. 
132 L.Ed.2d at 719.  Because the provision of funding and facilities by a
university creates a limited public forum for students to communicate their
views, cases involving the government's communication of its views are
inapposite.  The presumptive unconstitutionality of viewpoint-based restrictions
on speech by private citizens does not attach to the government's own speech;
the government is free to determine the content and viewpoint of the messages it
communicates.  See Rosenberger, 132 L.Ed.2d at 718.  </P>
<P>The same rule applies when the government speaks through private entities it
has paid to convey its message.  Thus, in Rust v. Sullivan, 500 U.S. 173 (1991),
the Supreme Court upheld a prohibition against abortion-related advice by
private entities in the context of family planning counseling paid for by the
government.  See also Rosenberger, 132 L.Ed.2d at 718 (explaining need for
government &quot;to ensure that its messages are neither garbled nor distorted
by the grantee.&quot;) Similarly inapposite to the case at bar are those relied
on by the Attorney General addressing whether or not the government is obligated
to provide funding to support private expression.  See Regan v. Taxation with
Representation of Washington, 461 U.S. 540 (1983); Lyng v. International Union,
UAW, 485 U.S. 490 (1981); Gay Men's Health Crisis v. Sullivan, 733 F. Supp. 619
(S.D.N.Y. 1989).  These cases do not address the situation here, where the
government opens up a forum for student expression by providing funding, and
then disfavors certain viewpoints in that forum.  Although &quot;a group has no
right to [university] funding </P>
<P>. . . when funds are made available, they must be distributed in a
viewpoint-neutral manner.&quot; Gay and Lesbian Students Association v. Gohn,
850 F.2d 361, 366 (8th Cir. 1988).  </P>
<P>Even if the viewpoint-based distinction here is not rejected outright as
unconstitutional as the Supreme Court did in Rosenberger, the government would
have to prove, first, that Section 16-1-28 serves a state interest of the
highest order and second, that this compelling state interest could not be
adequately served through some means less restrictive of First Amendment
freedoms.  See Simon &amp; Schuster Inc. v. New York State Crime Victims Board,
502 U.S. 105, 120-21 (1991); see also Widmar (no compelling interest in
content-based exclusion of particular student groups from use of generally open
university facilities). </P>
<P>There is no evidence that might substantiate a connection between this law
and a grave state interest.  R2-45-__.  University Dean Adams saw no need for
the law, had hoped that it wouldn't pass, and testified that other state
universities in Alabama were ignoring it.  (Cite).  The Attorney General
testified that he was &quot;totally without . . . knowledge&quot; as to any
facts that might support the need for the law.  When asked &quot;what interests
of the state of Alabama does this statute attempt to advance?,&quot; the
Attorney General referred to the &quot;police power&quot; and the state's &quot;interest
in taking steps through the civil law or the criminal law, to prevent violations
of the law.&quot; (Cite).  But the government made no record to establish a
compelling interest in increasing the state's police powers relative to the
sodomy and sexual misconduct prohibitions.  Indeed, apart from furnishing an
opinion letter regarding GLBA and seeking a stay of the district court's
judgment, the Attorney General has taken no steps to enforce the law and has not
received any requests to do so.  Even if it was an otherwise proper purpose, the
government made no record to establish a compelling interest in increasing the
state's police powers relative to the sodomy and sexual misconduct
prohibitions.(8)</P>
<P>Defendants also had the burden of proving the statute to be narrowly
tailored to advance a compelling state interest.  The failure of the legislature
to narrowly tailor Section 16-1-28 is evident in the wide range or expression
restricted, its use of broad, undefined terms like &quot;promote,&quot;&quot;foster,&quot;
and &quot;encourage,&quot; and its extrapolation of the sodomy and sexual
misconduct laws to prohibit some &quot;lifestyle&quot; not referred to in those
provisions.  </P>
<P>As the district court below noted, all kinds of expression  -- however
abhorrent to some or even to the majority -- are protected by the First
Amendment, including advocacy of &quot;the use of force or of law violation
except where such advocacy is directed to inciting or producing imminent lawless
action and is likely to incite or produce such action.&quot;  Brandenburg, 395
U.S. at 447 (1969).  Under the latter, very limited circumstances, advocacy
crosses the line into action that can be legally proscribed.  Id. at 448-49.</P>
<P>When the government seeks to restrict expression on these grounds its burden
is exceptionally high.  In Healy, for example, a public university asserted that
potential campus disruption justified its failure to recognize a chapter of
Students for a Democratic Society (SDS) at the school.  The Supreme Court
rejected this argument, stressing the lack of &quot;substantial evidence&quot;
to support the university's contention.  Healy, 408 U.S. at 190.  It emphasized
that the &quot;critical line&quot; was the one drawn in Brandenburg and that,
without convincing proof of incitement to &quot;imminent lawless action,&quot;
the students' First Amendment rights must prevail.  Id. at 189-91.(9)</P>
<P>The Attorney General argues that Section 16-1-28 must be upheld because the
viewpoint it restricts has to do with the criminality of sodomy, which is not a
&quot;debatable public question.&quot;  Appellant's Br. at 35-37.  But the fact
that sodomy is criminalized does not somehow make discussion of it somehow
constitutionally unprotected, as if a production of Macbeth could be shut down
for its description of murder.  See R2-45-__.  It is equally apparent that
Section 16-1-28 is not a permissible attempt to restrict a limited public forum
to the purposes for which it was created.(10)  The topics of sodomy and sexual
misconduct are not removed from discussion by the statute; rather, one viewpoint
on these topics is favored.  </P>
<P>The defendants here have made no showing, and certainly not a &quot;substantial&quot;
one, that the speech and association restricted by Section 16-1-28 is inciting
or will likely lead to imminent lawlessness.  Section 16-1-28 establishes in
part (a) a blanket rule that any group that is somehow deemed to merely &quot;foster&quot;
or &quot;promote&quot; either a &quot;lifestyle&quot; or the referenced illegal
acts can be completely expelled from Alabama campuses.  Part (b) of the law is
still broader (and less likely to serve the supposed state interest), because it
forbids any university-supported organization from allowing its members, or
encouraging others, to simply explain how the referenced criminal laws might be
violated.  The &quot;restriction of First Amendment rights . . . may be
justified only by a far greater showing of a likelihood of imminent lawless
action[.]&quot; Gay Lib v. University of Missouri, 558 F.2d 848, 855 (8th Cir.
1977).(11)  </P>
<P>The Attorney General's argument that it is a &quot;much more reasonable
interpretation&quot; of Section 16-1-28 to apply only to advocacy directed
toward inciting imminent lawlessness, Appellant's Br. at 26, simply has no basis
in the terms of the statutes. </P>
<P>*   *   *   *</P>
<P>As the district court found, &quot;th[e] history [of Section 16-1-28
reflects an open effort by the state legislature to limit the sexuality
discussion in institutions of higher learning to only one viewpoint: that of
heterosexual people.&quot;  R2-45-__ (Dt. Ct. Op.)  The restrictions on
expression and association based on the &quot;identity or perspective&quot; of
the speaker is just the type of &quot;blatant&quot; First Amendment violation
held unconstitutional in Rosenberger.  The district court's judgment declaring
the statute and its application to GLBA to violate the First Amendment should
therefore be affirmed.</P>
<P>B. Section 16-1-28 is Unconstitutionally Vague and Overbroad</P>
<P>The district court below agreed with GLBA that Section 16-1-28 is
unconstitutionally vague and overbroad.  R2-45-25 (Dt. Ct. Op.)  Due process &quot;requires
that a statute be sufficiently clearly defined so as not to cause persons 'of
common intelligence -- necessarily [to] guess at its meaning and [to] differ as
to its application.'  Connally v. General Construction Co., 269 U.S. 385, 391 .
. . (1926).&quot;  Finley v. National Endowment for the Arts, 795 F. Supp. 1457,

1471 (C.D. Cal. 1992).  Section 16-1-28 (1) fails to give fair warning of what

it prohibits; (2) does not provide explicit standards to be applied by
government enforcers, and does not even specify the enforcement process, thereby
inviting discriminatory application; and (3) creates a profound chilling effect
for those who fear that they may be covered by its restrictions.  See Grayned v.
City of Rockford, 408 U.S. 104, 108-09 (1972) (outlining dangers addressed by
vagueness doctrine). </P>
<P>There is no discernible line in the statute dividing permitted association
and speech from association and speech that are restricted.  What kind of group,
or what actions by any group, for example, might be deeemed to &quot;foster&quot;
violations of the &quot;deviate sexual intercourse&quot; provision?  Do all
groups that function as a meeting place for like minded adults &quot;foster&quot;
or &quot;promote&quot; consensual sexual relations and thus promote violations
of Section 13A-6-65(a)(3)?  What does it mean to &quot;encourage&quot; others to
violate the referenced criminal laws?  How explicit does one have to be to &quot;provide
information . . . that explain[s] how such acts may be engaged in&quot;?</P>
<P>The President of GLBA testified that the group's members were uncertain as
to the scope of the statute and had &quot;never been told what, if anything it
could do to ensure that Section 16-1-28 did not cover GLBA's activities or its
members[.]&quot; JR I 0229.  The President and Dean of the University testified
that Section 16-1-28 is &quot;vague,&quot; and that the University asked the
Attorney General to clarify the meaning of the statute.  Cite.  The Attorney
General's opinion letter informed the University that GLBA was covered by the
statute but provided no explanation and the Attorney General was unable to
explain what facts about GLBA led his office to this conclusion.  (Cite).</P>
<P>The imprecise enforcement standards embodied in Section 16-1-28 have already
led to &quot;arbitrary and discriminatory enforcement&quot; against GLBA.  See
Grayned, 408 U.S. at 408.  The chilling effect of the statute is also apparent:
gay student groups at other state campuses &quot;have become more conservative
in [their] on-campus activities in the hopes of at least continuing to exist as
a recognized student organization.&quot;  JR I 0234.</P>
<P>In sum, the constitutionally-impermissible vagueness of Section 16-1-28 is
evident from the imprecision of its key terms (&quot;promote,&quot; &quot;foster,&quot;
and &quot;encourage&quot;), its sweeping regulation of expression in the
university environment, and the harms already demonstrated by its existence and
enforcement.</P>
<P>Section 16-1-28 also fails constitutional review because it is substantially
overbroad.  To survive overbreadth scrutiny the statute must be carefully drawn
or be authoritatively construed to punish only unprotected speech and not be
susceptible of application to protected expression.  &quot;Because First
Amendment freedoms need breathing space to survive, government may regulate in
the area only with narrow specificity.&quot;</P>
<P>Gooding v. Wilson, 405 U.S. 518, 522 (1972) (quoting NAACP v. Button, 371
U.S. 415, 433 (1963)).</P>
<P>As discussed above, the only conceivable type of expression that Section
16-1-28 could constitutionally regulate is expression &quot;directed to inciting
or producing imminent lawless action and . . . likely to incite or produce such
action.&quot; Brandenburg, 395 U.S. at 447.  But Section 16-1-28's language is
grossly overencompassing if that is its goal.  In addition, the statute
precludes the use of university facilities or funds by any group that at any
time or in any place conveys the particular messages targeted, even if the group
seeks to use a meeting room or spend funds for activities totally unrelated to
the subjects covered by Section 16-1-28. </P>
<P>Quite simply, &quot;'encouraging' and 'promoting,' like 'advocating,' do not
necessarily imply incitement to imminent lawless action.&quot;  NGTF, 729 F.2d
at 1274 (holding policy unconstitutionally overbroad); Mathews, 544 F.2d at 166
(&quot;the suppression of associational rights because the opportunity for
homosexual contacts is increased constitutes prohibited overbreadth&quot;). </P>
<P>C. Section 16-1-28 Has Been Applied to GLBA in Violation of the Equal
Protection Clause</P>
<P>The University and the Attorney General have singled out GLBA for
enforcement of Section 16-1-28. GLBA has been denied on-campus banking services
available to other groups, has been denied funding available to other groups and
has been subject to an investigation of its members that no other group has
undergone.  In Romer v. Evans, cite, the Supreme Court held that the State of
Colorado's differential treatment of gay, lesbian and bisexual people violated
their rights to equal protection.  The Court rejected the dissent's view that
disapproval of sexual conduct by gay people is a legitimate reason for
discriminating against them.  Cite.  See also Cleburne v. Cleburne Living
Center, 473 U.S. 432, 448 (1985) (&quot;mere negative attitudes . . . are not
permissible bases&quot; for government action); Palmore v. Sidoti, 466 U.S. 429,
433-34 (1984) (&quot;[p]rivate biases may be outside the reach of the law, but
the law cannot, directly or indirectly, give them effect&quot;); U.S. Department
of Agriculture v. Moreno, 413 U.S. 528, 534 (1973) (&quot;a bare congressional
desire to harm a politically unpopular group cannot constitute a legitimate
governmental interest.&quot;)  </P>
<P>Even if Section 16-1-28 were otherwise constitutional, which it is not, see
supra __ to __, defendants application of the statute to GLBA alone would
violate the equal protection rights of GLBA's members.  Without any evidence
that GLBA's members have violated the criminal statutes of the state or that
GLBA members have violated Section 16-1-28, the University and the Attorney
General have singled GLBA out for investigation and denial of privileges,
treating the group less favorably based on its connection with homosexuality. 
After Romer, there is no question that disapproval of gay people or of sexual
conduct by gay people does not justify discrimination.  The defendants'
application of Section </P>
<P>16-1-28 to GLBA should therefore be held to violate the Fourteenth
Amendment.  </P>
<H4>III SECTION 16-1-28 IS NOT SUSCEPTIBLE TO A NARROWING CONSTRUCTION, NOR CAN
ANY PART OF IT BE SAVED THROUGH SEVERANCE</H4>
<P>Courts have no authority to rewrite legislation -- only where a statute is &quot;obviously
susceptible&quot; of a narrowing construction can it be so limited.  See City of
Houston v. Hill, 482 U.S. 451, 471 (1987).  See also City of Jasper v. Sherer,
273 Ala. 356, 358, 141 So. 2d 202 (Ala. 1962) (reading must be &quot;fairly and
reasonably support[ed]&quot; by the statute).  The federal courts must be &quot;particularly
reluctant to rewrite the terms of a state statute&quot; in order not to
interfere with the state legislative process.  Dimmitt v. City of Clearwater,
985 F.2d 1565 (11th Cir. 1993).  </P>
<P>The Attorney General asks this court to narrow Section 16-1-28 to limit the
terms &quot;foster,&quot; &quot;promote&quot; and &quot;encourage&quot; to only
that &quot;advocacy likely to result  in imminent violation of the law.&quot; 
Appellant's Br. at 44.  But the breadth of activity covered by the terms &quot;foster,&quot;
&quot;promote,&quot; and &quot;encourage&quot; makes it far from obvious that
Section 16-1-28 is so limited; this is not a close case, the restricted
expression is vast and far removed from incitement of imminent lawlessness.  See
supra at __; see also Rosenberger, 132 L.Ed.2d at 720 (noting tremendous breadth
of expression restricted under term &quot;promotes.&quot;) Because the Attorney
General's proposed narrowing of Section 16-1-28 has no support in the terms of
the statute or the legislative history -- needless to say that the statute is
not &quot;obviously susceptible&quot; of such a narrowing -- for this court to
narrow the statute this way would be an unauthorized encroachment on the Alabama
legislature.  </P>
<P>The Attorney General also argues that part (b) of the statute should be read
to be limited to only those groups whose members &quot;violate state sodomy and
sexual misconduct laws at meeting or activities of the organizations.&quot; 
Appellant's Br. at 44.  The language of part (b), however, contains no such
limitation and the legislative history makes plain that no such limitation was
intended.  See supra at __.  For the court to insert one would drastically alter
the scope of the statute's reach in direct conflict with the terms chosen by the
legislature.  See Ex parte State Dept. of Revenue, 1996 Ala. LEXIS 151, *6 (Ala.
Release June 7, 1996) (&quot;[t]he court is bound to interpret [] language to
mean exactly what it says.&quot;) </P>
<P>Finally, while the Attorney General contends that the district court should
have severed only those portions of Section 16-1-28 that are unconstitutional,
Appellant's Br. at 52, he gives no indication as to which parts of the statute
he believes could be saved and why.  As detailed above, both parts (a) and (b)
of the statute are unconstitutional, leaving only part (c) --the provision
exempting from the rest of the statute expression and association that attempts
to overturn the sodomy and sexual misconduct laws.  On its own such an exemption
is meaningless and therefore the entire statute was properly held
unconstitutional by the district court.  See Hamilton v. Autauga, 289 Ala. 419,
425, 268 So.2d 30 (1972) (citations omitted)(severance only possible when the
remaining parts are &quot;complete within themselves, sensible, and capable of
execution.&quot;) </P>
<H3>CONCLUSION</H3>
<P>For all of the foregoing reasons, this court should declare Section 16-1-28
unconstitutional on its face and as it has been applied to GLBA. </P>
<HR>
<H3>Notes</H3>
<P>(1)These groups are typically and in this brief referred to as &quot;gay and
lesbian&quot; or &quot;gay, lesbian and bisexual&quot; student groups.  Such
shorthand is imprecise, however, because the groups are not simply collections
of gay men, lesbians and bisexuals.  Rather, the distinctive characteristic of
the groups is their open identification with and support of those minority
sexual orientations, in opposition to homophobia.  The groups often include
heterosexual members, just as gay students belong to all kinds of organizations.</P>
<P>(2)The Alabama Legislature does not maintain any official legislative
history of its deliberations. </P>
<P>(3)Although the derogatory use of the phrase &quot;homosexual lifestyle&quot;
is common and is relevant to the history and meaning of Section 16-1-28, there
is no single &quot;lifestyle&quot; or way that gay men and lesbians conduct
themselves in the world.  See, e.g., Gregory Herek, Myths About Sexual
Orientation:  A Lawyer's Guide to Social Science Research, 1 Law &amp; Sexuality
133, 164 (1991) (&quot;lesbian and gay male couples manifest the same range of
diversity as heterosexual couples&quot;); R2-45-16 n.41.</P>
<P>Gay people are also erroneously thought of as having some unique, inexorable
connection with sodomy.  Oral and anal sex, however, are precisely the sexual
acts that gay and heterosexual couples have in common.  Sexual orientation is
defined by the gender of those to whom one is sexually attracted, not by any
particular sexual act.  See Nan D. Hunter, Life After Hardwick, 27 Harv.
C.R.-C.L. L. Rev. 531, 544, 550-51 (1992); Developments in the Law -- Sexual
Orientation and the Law, 102 Harv. L. Rev. 1508, 1568-69 (1989). </P>
<P>(4)The doctrines discussed throughout this brief apply equally to the right
of free speech and the right of expressive association (which is not explicitly
mentioned in, but necessarily flows from, the named rights in the First
Amendment).  Appellee therefore does not separate out distinct free expression
and free association claims.</P>
<P>(5)The Attorney General's argument that &quot;Rosenberger is an
Establishment Clause case&quot; and therefore &quot;is inapplicable to the case
sub judice,&quot; Appellant's Br. at 39, ignores the Supreme Court's explicit
conclusion: &quot;we hold that the regulation . . . is a denial of
[petitioner's] right of free speech guaranteed by the First Amendment.&quot; 
Rosenberger, 132 L.Ed.2d at 720.  That the Establishment Clause was considered
and rejected by the Supreme Court as a possible justification for the speech
restriction does not somehow negate the existence of the Court's holding on the
speech claim.</P>
<P>(6)The Attorney General's argument that First Amendment review is less
stringent in the university context is unsupported.  The cases he relies on
either involved expression that could easily  be perceived as coming from the
government itself, Hazelwood v. Kuhlmeier, 484 U.S. 260, 271 (1988) (high
school-sponsored newspaper) and Bishop v. Aronov, 926 F.2d 1066 (11th Cir. 1991)
(teacher's speech in the classroom), or not viewpoint-based, Alabama Student
Party v. Student Government Assoc., 867 F.2d 1344, 1345 (11th Cir. 1989)
(generally applicable student government campaign restrictions).  In addition,
the university context does not raise the concern about the maturity of high
school children implicated in Hazelwood and other cases.  Compare, e.g., Bethel
School Dist. No. 403 v. Fraser, 478 U.S. 683, 685-86 (1986) (need for public &quot;school
authorities acting in loco parentis to protect children&quot;), with Widmar, 454
U.S. at 274 n.14 (&quot;University students are, of course, young adults.  They
are less impressionable than younger students.&quot;) </P>
<P>(7)While defendants have not yet applied Section 16-1-28 to deprive GLBA of
its status as a student group or to bar it from campus facilities, the statute
makes no distinction between these and the funding denials that GLBA has already
suffered.  </P>
<P>(8)The Attorney General also suggested that Section 16-1-28 furthers the
state's interests in promoting marriage and procreation, in preventing
transmission of sexually transmitted diseases, and in fostering good moral
character.  The district court rejected these purported justifications for the
statute, holding that a government interest is not permissibly promoted by the
exclusion of competing views from a limited public forum.  R2-45-__.  There is
also no record support for a compelling need to address any of these issues by
means of Section 16-1-28, nor is there any explanation for how Section 16-1-28
actually promotes these interests.  For example, how does a statute that limits
discussion of sexual behaviors help, rather than hinder, prevention of sexually
transmitted diseases?  See Gohn, 850 F.2d at 367 (no compelling interest
supports denial of funding to gay student group).  </P>
<P>(9)The Attorney General argues that the district court's reliance on the
Brandenburg standard was in error because &quot;[t]here is strong reason to
believe&quot; that the current Supreme Court would overrule that case.  See
Appellant's Br. at 24.  The Supreme Court, however, has consistently reaffirmed
Brandenburg.  See, e.g., Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. at 409; National Assn. for
the Advancement of Colored People v. Clairborne Hardware Co., 458 U.S. 886, 928
(1982).  The Attorney General is also wrong in claiming that the Brandenburg
standard does not apply on university campuses (Appellant's Br. at 30-33) -- the
Supreme Court in Healy applied it in just this setting.  Cite ___.</P>
<P>(10)Viewpoint discrimination is impermissible in any type of forum. 
Content-based discrimination, on the other hand, may be permissible in a limited
public forum in order &quot;to preserve the property . . . for the use to which
it is lawfully dedicated.&quot;  Perry, 460 U.S. at 46 (citations and internal
quotations omitted). </P>
<P>(11)The courts in Gay Lib; Gohn, 850 F.2d at 368; and Matthews, 544 F.2d at
166, all rejected the contention that gay student groups present an imminent
threat of lawlessness.  Similarly, the courts in Department of Education v.
Lewis, 416 So.2d 455 (Fla. 1982) and National Gay Task Force v. Board of
Education of Oklahoma City, 729 F.2d 1270, 1274 (10th Cir. 1984), aff'd by an
equally divided Court, 470 U.S. 903 (1985), found unconstitutional statutes
punishing &quot;advocacy&quot; of sexual relations because the statutes
restricted speech and association that fell short of the &quot;incitement&quot;
and &quot;imminence&quot; requirements of Brandenburg.</P>
